<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0730 06-06 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0730,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Primary-Eve Broadcast A Disaster For Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 10 grafs on botched broadcast; picks up 2nd graf
pvs bgng: Jackson accused; DELETES outdated grafs 4-5 pvs; edits to
tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson staged what was to have
been a celebratory appeal for votes on the final night of the
California primary campaign, but the half-hour show was botched when
the presidential candidate got stuck in traffic and missed half of
it.
   Jackson arrived 16 minutes into the half-hour broadcast, which
originated at Los Angeles station KTLA and shown throughout the
state at a cost of $150,000.
   Jackson fell behind schedule on campaign appearances in San
Francisco earlier in the the day, then got tied up in traffic jams
trying to get to the San Francisco airport.
   The show opened with rock disc jockey Casey Kasem, a Jackson
supporter, announcing that the chair next to him was empty because
Jackson was on his way.
   The first half of the show was given over to a video montage of
Jackson campaign appearances.
   Kasem filled time waiting for Jackson by interviewing Chris
Hammond, Jackson's state campaign manager, producing some tortured
exchanges.
   Then came a second video montage, featuring some of the same
footage already shown. Finally, Jackson appeared.
   The candidate, appearing calm but his face glistening with
perspiration, talked about the issues that he has stressed in
California _ offshore oil drilling and environmental concerns as
well as devoting defense funding to peaceful application in space
and science instead.
   He also highlighted his anti-drug message and his call for an end
to gang warfare.
   Jackson told Kasem he had a ``day of big crowds, lots of
excitement, but mostly of touching people's hearts.''
   Earlier in the day, Jackson, shifting the focus toward thd
Democratic convention this summer, said Monday he will go to the
convention mat with Michael Dukakis unless the Democratic
front-runner comes around to his position on South Africa.
   Jackson accused Dukakis of proceeding too ``cautiously and
conservatively'' in refusing to agree with Jackson that South Africa
should be declared a terrorist nation.
   ``If he will not bend on that matter, we'll simply meet on the
floor at Atlanta,'' Jackson said during a call-in radio news
conference. The tough talk was the most pointed language Jackson has
used in discussing his intentions for the convention.
   ``The matter needs to be resolved in the committee or in platform
hearings or on the convention floor,'' he told reporters later.
   He indicated he will put up a fight for his platform issues but
will do so within the framework of party rules, leaving unclear just
how hard a bargain he will drive.
   ``We can resolve our differences within the context of our party
and not in the streets _ and that's growth,'' he said at one point.
   He also said that at the convention he would ``use the rules to
have fair rules'' _ a reference to his contention that the popular
vote is not fairly reflected in the delegate count and so
delegate-selection procedures should be changed.
   As for South Africa, Jackson contends the United States should
subject that nation to the trade sanctions applied to other
countries it has put on its terrorist list such as Libya, North
Korea and Cuba.
   ``By any definition of a terrorist state South Africa
qualifies,'' he said.
   Jackson said the Democratic convention ``will have a tremendous
impact on the priorities that the ticket will have. I'm convinced
the ticket will take a strong position against apartheid and declare
South Africa to be a terrorist state.''
   As to Dukakis, he said, ``Either the governor will offer
leadership on these basic issues or be wallowing in the wave of the
convention taking him out to sea.''
   ``It's not a question of integrity, it's a question of judgment
and priorities. And the governor, like all of us, will keep
expanding and keep growing,'' he said.
   Jackson indicated he will push for platform planks on cutting
back military spending and on shifting spending to housing, health
care and other social services.
   Although polls have shown Jackson consistently trailing Dukakis
in California, Jackson said the state ``can produce an upset
tomorrow if voters listen to their convictions rather than reports
of an inevitable Dukakis win.''
   In a philosophical vein, Jackson said he believes his candidacy
has helped America grow in racial tolerance. ``It's clear America
has become more and more accustomed to Jesse Jackson as a possible
next president. ... It's a matter of growth. I'm the stimulus. I'm
the catalyst for that growth.''
</TEXT>
