<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Cocaine     06-07 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Cocaine,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Cocaine Shipment From Colombian Group Seized in Chile, Police
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they foiled the first attempt
of Colombia's `Medellin Cartel' drug barons to use Chile as a
transit point to send cocaine to the United States or Europe.
   The seizure of 22 pounds of pure cocaine worth $1.2 million on
the street was the biggest cocaine bust in Chile in 14 years, police
Maj. Jaime Rieutord said Monday.
   Two Colombians, Oscar Diaz Torres, 30, and Alberto Marquez, 42,
were arrested with the narcotic on Friday at a fashionable Santiago
hotel after arriving from Colombia, police said.
   The arrests were not immediately announced because police were
waiting for accomplices to pick up the drugs, but the accomplices
never showed, Rieutord said.
   Diaz Torres and Marquez admitted to belonging to the cartel named
after the city where it is based and ``said they were told to use
Santiago as a transit point because this city was not normally used,
and thus security could be less severe,'' the major said.
   Rieutord said cocaine traffickers had not used Chile as a transit
station for more than a decade.
</TEXT>
