<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DonkeyExpecting     06-07 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Donkey Expecting,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare French Donkey Expecting Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLIVENHAIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonnette, a rare French donkey who
narrowly escaped a government death sentence four years ago, is
expecting its first offspring.
   ``She looks like she swallowed a barrel. She looks like she wants
to have it any minute,'' said Sharon Vanderlip, who owns the donkey
with her husband, Jack Vanderlip.
   The Vanderlips, both veterinarians at the University of
California, San Diego, said Sonnette successfully mated with a
3-year-old of the same breed about a year ago and should deliver her
first foal later this month.
   Sonnette is one of four donkeys the Vanderlips imported to their
northern San Diego County farm from the Poitou region of France in
1984 and 1985.
   In 1984, federal agriculture inspectors almost put Sonnette, a
member of an endangered species, to death because the donkey failed
an equine blood test for communicable diseases.
   A public outcry ensued over the plans to destroy the animal, and
officials changed their mind when the Vanderlips and other experts
showed the test given wasn't suitable for a specialized variety such
as the Poitou donkey.
   A test designed for the rare donkey was then given to Sonnette
and it was released from quarantine after being certified as healthy
and free of disease. Since then, the Vanderlips have imported three
other rare Poitou donkeys, including the father-to-be, Tartarin.
   The Vanderlips hope to establish a herd to help the save the
breed from extinction. About 45 Poitou donkeys remain in existence,
said Mrs. Vanderlip, who learned about the species while studying
veterinary medicine in France several years ago.
   Sonnette has been separated from the other donkeys and will
remain alone with the foal until the baby is weaned at 4 months to 6
months of age. Tartarin also will be kept away from Sonnette as well
as the foal because male donkeys can become agitated around small
creatures and may even kill them, Mrs. Vanderlip said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
