<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ToughPrincipal     06-07 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tough Principal,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Crew Takes Over High School For Movie On Principal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews filming scenes for a movie about
bat-wielding principal Joe Clark have disrupted classes and
graduation plans, but some students said the film also has generated
excitement.
   ``They moved our classes. So what, it doesn't mean they are going
to stop,'' said Francis Sousa, an Eastside High junior who is an
extra in the movie. ``Mostly the only reason you sit in class by now
is to go over your review sheets. Books have already been
collected.''
   Several students and parents have complained that Warner Bros.
crews filming ``Lean on Me'' forced a change in graduation sites,
Passaic County schools Superintendent Melindo Persi said Monday.
   Clark, who gained national attention for a get-tough approach to
education that includes wielding bullhorns and baseball bats in
hallways, could not be reached for comment. Calls left with his
secretary Monday were not returned.
   As the 97-member film crew built sets, sprayed graffiti over
lockers and filmed a scene with actor Robert Guillaume, students
hanging out after school said they saw only a positive impact from
the movie.
   Sophomore Kathy Lewis, an extra waiting to be called, said
students in the movie have been given plenty of time to do their
homework, and tutors are available if needed. She said she hopes to
parlay her movie appearance into greater roles in the future.
   ``I was excited because now there is a chance for us to be
noticed,'' she said.
   Some school officials, however, were worried there are too many
distractions at a time of year when important exams are held.
   ``My concern is just for the kids,'' said Donna Brightman, a
school board member. ``I'd like them to be able to take their exams
without a lot of commotion going on.''
   Persi sent the Paterson Board of Education a letter asking how
the filming of ``Lean on Me'' is affecting the school.
   In particular, he is asking about newspaper reports that physical
education classes have been canceled to let the film crew use the
gymnasium; that hallways are being blocked with film equipment; and
that regular instruction rooms have been sacrificed for the movie.
   Producer Norman Twain, who began filming Wednesday, said his
crew's presence will have few negative academic effects.
   ``Sure, it's a little more crowded in the hallways,'' Twain said.
``This is the time of year when everybody starts `short-timing'
anyhow. Just come over here and see the exodus at noontime.''
   Twain acknowledged causing a change in graduation plans, and
attributed it to the artistic preferences of director John Avildsen.
   Avildsen had planned to film the ceremony but because of
aesthetic concerns, persuaded the school to move the location to
Baurele Field from the original and larger site, Hinchcliffe Stadium.
   Two weeks ago, Avildsen decided not to film the graduation. At
that point, another school had reserved the stadium for June 24,
forcing Eastside to change its graduation date to June 25.
</TEXT>
