<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Quade; No separates moved for the AMs cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Virgil Oliver</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgil Oliver Jr., 72, who played the
mean little kids ``Butch'' and ``Tuffy'' in early ``Our Gang'' movie
shorts, died Friday.
   Oliver played the bully for about a year in 1925, earning $7.50 a
day, before he outgrew the role. Oliver had two other non-speaking
acting jobs in films and then decided to move on to a new career in
real estate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward Quade</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Schaumberg Quade, a founder of
the methodical problem-solving method known as ``systems analysis,''
died Saturday. He was 79.
   Quade joined the research organization when it was founded in
1948 and retired in 1973. His 1968 book, ``Systems Analysis and
Policy Planning: Applications in Defense,'' defined systems analysis
as ``a systematic approach to helping a decision-maker choose a
course of action by investigating his full problem, searching out
objectives and alternatives, and comparing them in the light of
their consequences.''
   Quade's books applied systems analysis to military problems and
later to broader public policy issues.
</TEXT>
