<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BalloonRecord     06-07 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Balloon Record,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloonist Sets Altitude Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Balloonist Per Lindstrand soared more than
10 miles to set an unofficial altitude record, but had to crawl
outside his pressurized gondola at 22,000 feet and wield a pocket
knife to release stubborn sandbags.
   Lindstrand on Monday reached 59,700 feet, easily surpassing the
55,137-foot record set in 1980, but fell short of his goal of 60,000
feet in his butane- and solar-powered ``Stratoquest'' hot-air
balloon, project coordinator Peter Mason said.
   The 12-story-high craft took off into a clear sky, but was
hampered by two 200-pound sandbags that failed to release
automatically.
   ``There was no way I could make the altitude record while
carrying this sand,'' said the 39-year-old Lindstrand. `` So I had
to climb out of the capsule and cut them.''
   The first bag was no problem because it was near the hatch, but
the second was on the other side of the craft beyond the reach of
his oxygen line.
   ``I had to take a deep breath, run around, cut it off and run
back again, all the while clinging on to the outside of the
capsule,'' he said. ``That got a bit hairy.
   ``There were a few white knuckles when I was climbing around
there,'' he said.
   Linstrand figures the sandbag problem cost him about 5,000 feet
in potential altitude.
   ``It was a fairly average day, I think,'' Lindstrand said
jokingly. ``We had a particular problem with the sandbags, but
nothing my trusty Swiss Army knife couldn't handle.''
   Last year, Lindstrand and British millionaire Richard Brandson
set another record when they became the first ever to cross the
Atlantic in a hot air balloon. The two hold balloon records for
speed, 100 mph; duration, 31 hours and 41 minutes, and distance,
3,075 miles, from that flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
