<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Delegates Bjt   06-07 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Delegates, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates Flock To Dukakis As He Heads Over The Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis closed to within 200 delegates
of locking up the Democratic presidential nomination even before the
first votes were counted in today's season-ending primaries, boosted
by a surge of about 180 in the last week.
   Dukakis picked up 75 of those new delegates on Monday alone, some
prodded into declaring their support by his campaign staff and
others attracted by the near-gravitational force that surrounds a
winner.
   ``He's been on a roll,'' said Susan Brophy, deputy director of
delegate selection for the Dukakis campaign.
   ``He's shown election success week after week after week,'' she
said. ``It casts a very favorable light on Mike Dukakis.''
   Much of the surge came courtesy of ``super delegates,'' the party
leaders and elected officials who have heavily favored Dukakis, to
the chagrin of Jesse Jackson.
   The Massachusetts governor also has been converting delegates who
had been pledged to the suspended candidacies of Sens. Albert Gore
Jr. and Paul Simon.
   On Monday, Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson, a staunch supporter
of Gore, switched to Dukakis and brought the bulk of his state's
65-member delegation with him. This came two days after Wilkinson
said he would continue to support Gore.
   And in Arizona on Monday, Gov. Rose Mofford and four other
``super delegates'' moved to Dukakis from the uncommitted ranks,
where they had been since former Gov. Bruce Babbitt dropped out of
the presidential race.
   By its own estimates, the Dukakis campaign has moved within
striking distance of the 2,081 delegates needed to clinch the
nomination. With fewer than 200 delegates to go, the campaign
expects to take at least 280 of the 466 delegates at stake in
today's primaries in California, New Jersey, New Mexico and Montana.
   The intensity of the operation to contact and win delegates has
picked up as the primary season draws to a close. Delegates are told
that ``the governor would appreciate it very much if they would get
into the count earlier rather than later,'' Ms. Brophy said.
   ``The goal of all of this is to take the pressure off Dukakis
after June 7 so he can go about the process of building a coalition
for the general election,'' she said.
   Another incentive is the memory of 1984, when Walter Mondale
finished the final round of primaries without enough delegates to
lock up the nomination and spent an extra day pleading with a
handful of delegates to put him over the top.
   Some members of Dukakis' staff, including delegate chief Tad
Devine, worked for Mondale four years ago.
   Of the 178 delegates moved into the Dukakis column in the last
week, roughly half were super delegates, the party leaders and
politicians who automatically hold seats at the convention, and the
rest were delegates picked through the primaries and caucuses who
had been uncommitted or pledged to other candidates.
   ``I think that the advantage that we have is that we have been on
the phones with these people so long and there is a real strong bond
between some of these people and the campaign,'' Ms. Brophy said.
   By Monday, Dukakis held support from more than 321 of the 643
super delegates, while Jackson was backed by just 54, of whom 42 are
black, according to The Associated Press delegate count.
   Jackson has complained that the super delegates have
disproportionately favored Dukakis and hinted he may challenge the
rules that created them. He also has indicated he may launch a
convention challenge against the rules that allow some states to
pick other delegates in a manner that does not reflect the results
of the states' primaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Airport-Statistics     06-07 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Airport-Statistics,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>April Figures For 27 Airports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airline Scorecard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, ranked from best to worst, is a listing
of 27 airports and the percentage of on-time arrivals during April,
according to information provided by the airlines to the
Transportation Department and released Monday.
   The average on-time arrival percentage was 81.3.
   (Departure: The percentage in parentheses reflects the departure
record at the airport.)
   The ranking covers the 27 busiest airports in passenger volume as
determined by the Transportation Department.
</TEXT>
