<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Quade     06-07 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Quade,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Co-Founder of `Systems Analysis' Dead At 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Schaumberg Quade, who helped
develop the methodical problem-solving method known as systems
analysis, died after suffering a stroke, the Rand Corp. said. He was
79.
   Quade, who had cancer of the spine, died Saturday at Saddleback
Hospital after suffering the stroke a week earlier, Paul Weeks,
spokesman for the Santa Monica-based think tank, said Monday.
   The Jacksonville, Fla., native, a consultant to Rand at the time
of his death, joined the research group when it was founded in 1948
and retired in 1973.
   He and some colleagues devised and developed systems analysis as
a recognized scientific discipline, Weeks said.
   Quade's 1968 book, ``Systems Analysis and Policy Planning:
Applications in Defense,'' defined systems analysis as ``a
systematic approach to helping a decision-maker choose a course of
action by investigating his full problem, searching out objectives
and alternatives, and comparing them in the light of their
consequences.''
   Quade studied physics and mathematics at the University of
Florida in Gainesville, and earned his doctorate at Brown
University. After World War II service in the Navy, he returned to
the University of Florida, where he headed the math department until
joining Rand.
   Survivors include his wife, Sylvia, of Laguna Hills, and three
children.
   A memorial service is scheduled for June 26 in Pacific Palisades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BannedCleric     06-07 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banned Cleric,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Relents, Grants Banned English Cleric A Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Church of England clergyman who monitors
religious persecution in communist countries says Soviet authorities
have relented and decided to allow him to lead a party of pilgrims
to Moscow.
   The Rev. Michael Bourdeaux said the Soviet Consulate told him
Monday night that he and his wife, Lorna, had been granted visas for
their scheduled flight to Moscow today. He said the decision came
less than a week after they were refused visas.
   Bourdeaux will lead a group of pilgrims to the 1,000th
anniversary celebrations of the introduction of Christianity in
Russia.
   The clergyman said publicity over the fifth time he was refused a
visa for the Soviet Union helped convince the Soviets to change
their minds.
   ``It is very exciting,'' he said. ``I intend to make contact with
churchmen of all varieties and with human rights people.''
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Anglican state church, flew to Moscow on Saturday with a party of
British churchmen to attend the ceremonies.
   Bourdeaux, 54, who studied at Moscow State University in 1959-60,
founded the Keston College Center for the Study of Religion and
Communism near London in 1969. The center publishes frequent
information about the state of religion in communist countries.
</TEXT>
