<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0713 06-07 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says More Differences With Reagan Can Be Expected</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New information in top 12 grafs, Interior Department
suspending offshore oil project; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: Bush
brushed</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ONTARIO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Monday he
expects to find himself differing increasingly with administration
policy as the presidential campaign progresses.
   Bush said he would try to keep the situation to ``where I don't
go out and do something to tear down or be negative about this
president. It may not always be that easy.''
   ``We'll probably be dragged into more and more of these things
rather than less,'' he said at a news conference at which he was
questioned about his most recent departure from administration
policy, his advocacy of a delay in an offshore drilling lease off
the northern California coast.
   ``As I become the standard bearer of this party, I'm going to be
saying, without regard to current administration position, here's
what George Bush feels, here's what I feel, here's what my
aspirations for the country are,'' Bush said.
   He said he understood that ``somebody is going to be raising the
question, are you breaking with the president.''
   On the matter of the northern California offshore drilling,
however, the administration came around to Bush's point of view.
Interior Secretary Donald Hodel on Monday night suspended plans for
the controversial project.
   Hodel's primary-eve action came after Bush ran into criticism
from Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis over the oil-lease
question.
   Asked about that criticism, the vice president said, ``I have a
good deal more information than Mr. Dukakis. I made my living at
it.''
   He said, ``I do not favor shutting down all off-shore drilling in
this country.''
   Dukakis, also campaigning in California, said of Bush's call for
delay on the project off northern California, ``I'm pleased he's
coming around, but it's kind of late. I'm not for delaying that sale
_ I'm for canceling it.
   ``It's easy to say, `We'll delay it until after the election.'
What does that mean?''
   The proposed lease sale of the northern California tracts had
been tentatively scheduled for February 1989, pending a decision by
the next administration. But Hodel's action, announced in a
statement issued Monday night in Washington, puts the project on
hold indefinitely.
   Bush, meanwhile, brushed aside polls that show him trailing
Dukakis in California as well as nationwide.
   ``I like this concept of being behind in the polls,'' he said.
   Bush said that in one survey ``two-thirds of the respondents say
that Dukakis is more conservative than Bush.'' He said, ``There's
something weird about that.''
   He opened the news conference by reading a statement in which he
endorsed legislation that would pay reparations to
Japanese-Americans interned during World War II.
   The administration has not taken a position on the bill.
   ``It is only fair that our country provide apologies and
reparations to those innocent Japanese-Americans who suffered as a
result of their internment,'' he said.
   Bush spoke to reporters at Chaffee High School where he met with
students and faculty to talk about drug and alcohol abuse programs.
   He told the students he favored jail sentences for people
convicted of second offenses of drug use.
   ``Drug possession should lead to arrest and a sentence,'' he
said. ``The sentence doesn't have to be jail time, automatically.
There are other alternatives _ a hefty fine, suspending a license,
putting a picture in the paper. ... But failing to stay drug-free
after arrest should mean time in jail. The message should be
unambiguous: If you won't stop, then we'll stop you.''
</TEXT>
