<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LottoWinners     06-07 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotto Winners,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Jackpot Stuns Winners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the two winners who split a
record $51.4 million lottery jackpot says he was relieved he has to
share the windfall so he doesn't have to face ``all this by myself.''
   ``Honest to God, I was hoping that somebody else hit it, too,''
said Sacramento supermarket clerk Randy Pennington, 26, who will
divide North America's largest lottery jackpot with aircraft
mechanic Shelby Carroll, 53, of Vacaville.
   Carroll, a mechanic at Travis Air Force Base, said he purchased
$100 worth of tickets himself because he couldn't find someone to
share his bet.
   The winners, who found themselves instant celebrities Monday,
each will receive $25.7 million annuities that pay $1,028,000
annually, after taxes, for 20 years, lottery officials said.
   At a news conference attended by 100 people, including cheering
lottery agency workers, the Lotto 6-49 winners said they both used a
feature of the lottery ticket terminals that randomly selects
numbers for the player and that they were regular lotto players.
   The winners in Saturday's drawing said they plan to quit their
jobs and have few immediate plans for the money except to help
relatives in various ways.
   Both also said they would be ready for an onslaught of strangers
interested in their bonanza, but declined to discuss details of
their plans.
   Pennington said that after buying his tickets, ``I found a
heads-up penny.''
   ``Every time I've ever found a heads-up penny, something's always
happened good to me. I'm superstitious, I guess,'' he said.
Pennington said he has been buying $5 to $10 in lottery tickets a
week.
   Pennington was uncertain what he'll use the money for, beyond
helping his family, but said he would have more time to indulge his
hobby of collecting antique toys. He added that he has never won
anything before.
   Being single, he was asked if he had any trouble getting dates.
Replied Pennington, ``No. But who wants dates now. I don't.''
   Carroll said he couldn't find someone to match $50 with his $50
to split the bet so he purchased $100 worth of tickets.
   ``I asked my boss ... if he would like to share with me. I said,
`Give me $50 and we'll split the winnings.' At the time, it (the
jackpot) was around $40 million. I said, `Really, no one needs more
than $40 million.' He said, `No.' I asked a couple more of the guys,
and they said, `No.'''
   So Carroll bet $100 himself because, ``I had a feeling.''
   How does he feel now about not finding a partner? ``I'm glad. I
feel sorry for them. But I'm glad.''
   Carroll's wife, Ila, a clerk in the Solano County courts, said
she plans to continue working for a time even though her husband is
retiring.
   Her husband summed up the feelings both winners expressed about
their good fortune: ``It's all happened so fast.''
   The jackpot eclipsed a $46 million prize last October in
Pennsylvania. The biggest previous California jackpot that anybody
won, $25.4 million, was split by two players in October.
   The odds of picking all six numbers out of 49 were about one in
14 million. The winning numbers were 48, 42, 9, 14, 19, 31. The
tickets cost $1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
