<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Politics     06-07 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Leader's View on Disarmament Uncorks Left-Wing Fury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition Laborites feuded after party leader Neil
Kinnock said the country's nuclear weapons should be used as
bargaining chips in arms talks _ not just unilaterally scrapped.
   Kinnock's comments were taken as a strong indication he would
discard the party's commitment to elimination of Britain's nuclear
weapons.
   Party leftists have long been suspicious that Kinnock intended to
ditch the anti-nuclear policy before his next election battle
against Conservative Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   After he made his remarks Sunday in a television interview, party
leftists on Monday charged him with ignoring the socialist
movement's official policy.
   Kinnock said Sunday that in the wake of the superpower treaty to
eliminate those nations' intermediate-range nuclear missiles, a
Labor government would be wise to use the British arsenal as a
bargaining chip instead of simply scrapping the weapons and shutting
down U.S. nuclear bases.
   ``We would be complete fools, whatever our politics, to ignore
the scope and scale of the change and the opportunities and
responsibilities that go with trying to be part of that change,''
said Kinnock. ``There is no need now for a something-for-nothing
unilateralism.''
   Polaris missiles now based in Britain are due to be replaced in
the early 1990s by the new and far more potent U.S. Trident missile
system, capable of hitting most Soviet cities.
   Kinnock, 46, who has been a lifetime anti-nuclear campaigner,
refused left-wing demands to reaffirm the unilateral disarmament
pledge, saying, ``No, I am not going to issue incantations.''
   Tony Benn, a veteran of the Labor left, complained that Kinnock
was following previous Labor prime ministers _ including Harold
Wilson and James Callaghan _ who that ensured Britain remained a
nuclear power.
   ``The real problem for the Labor Party is not that we have never
persuaded the electorate to support our policies, but that we have
never persuaded our leaders,'' said Benn.
   Benn is to run against Kinnock for the leadership of the party at
the annual conference in the fall but is given little chance of
winning.
   In 1982, three years after losing power to Mrs. Thatcher, Labor's
policy-making annual conference voted for unilateral nuclear
disarmament by a two-thirds majority _ meaning it must be part of
the election platform.
   The pledge was widely seen as being one reason for Labor's two
subsequent defeats by Mrs. Thatcher in 1983 and 1987.
   Kinnock's new position is viewed as a shift to the right in an
attempt to regain power. The next election is to be held before 1992.
   For the left-wingers in his party, the Kinnock switch evokes both
anger and a sense of betrayal toward a politician who was once a
left-winger himself and had been an active member of Britain's
anti-nuclear campaign since he was a student.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
