<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AcidRain 1stLd-Writethru a0430 06-07 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acid Rain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Saw ``Writing On The Wall'' By Joining Agreement, Lawmaker
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, bgng The polluters, to correct figure to
$900 million; picks up 5th graf pvs, Rep. Gerry xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint national proposal by the governors of
Ohio and New York to reduce acid rain shows Ohio ``is finally
reading the writing on the wall'' and seeking help to curb pollution
from its coal-fired power plants, a congressman says.
   On Monday, Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste and New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo made public their proposal to reduce polluting sulfur dioxide
emissions from utility sources by 10 million tons by the year 2003.
   The plan calls for authorizing $900 million a year from the
federal government to finance up to 50 percent of the capital costs.
Most of that money would come from having the oil industry take over
the cost of filling the Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
   The polluters themselves would have to raise about $900 million a
year under the deal.
   Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., said it represents ``significant
progress'' anytime Ohio and New York can agree on acid rain.
   Sulfur dioxide emissions from the burning of coal have been
blamed as a major cause of acid rain, which environmentalists say is
destroying waters and woodlands in the Northeast.
   Much of the sulfur dioxide comes from coal-burning power plants
along the Ohio River.
   Sikorski, a member of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, is
the main sponsor of an acid rain control bill pending in committee.
His bill would mandate a 10-million-ton reduction in emissions by
1998.
   ``This agreement shows that there is renewed seriousness about
dealing with the issue,'' Sikorski said. ``It indicates that Ohio is
finally reading the writing on the wall. This could be their last
good chance at legislation that assists them with their cleanup
costs.''
   But the proposal drew fire from other lawmakers.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said that while he
is encouraged by the dialogue between Ohio and New York on acid
rain, he sees nothing new in the proposal.
   ``The key element of any effort to deal with acid rain has to be
time,'' said Byrd. ``And this proposal does not allow enough time
for the development of clean-coal technologies. Coal is essential to
America's national security, and we cannot afford to adopt an acid
rain policy that would devastate the coal industry.''
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the proposal would hurt Ohio and
accused Celeste of not speaking for Ohioans on the issue.
   Regardless of the financing ``gimmicks,'' said Luken, Ohio
consumers ``will pay millions of dollars and Ohio will lose
thousands of jobs for no known benefit.''
   Ohio, next to coal-rich West Virginia, has a significant
coal-mining industry.
   Sen. Robert Stafford, R-Vt., said he believes the proposal
represents a breakthrough because it is the first time a major
emitter of sulfur dioxide, Ohio, has attempted to come to grips with
the acid rain problem.
   Stafford, who is ranking Republican on the Senate Environment and
Public Works Committee, has been a major proponent of acid rain
control and is a co-sponsor of legislation authored by Sen. George
Mitchell, D-Maine, that would reduce emissions by 12 million tons.
   ``I think it's a very encouraging development,'' said Stafford,
adding that he expects that the Senate committee will want to review
the Ohio-New York proposal and possibly amend the pending
legislation to take advantage of the initiative.
   The proposal, an amendment to the Clean Air Act, calls for
reductions in sulfur dioxide emmissions in three phases: 3.5 million
tons by 1993, another 4.5 million tons by 1998 and another 2 million
tons by 2003.
   The agreement would also establish a 10-year, $2.5 billion
expanded clean coal technology program to achieve reductions in
sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide emissions.
   Daniel Weiss, Washington representative of the Sierra Club,
called the new proposal encouraging because it comes in part from
Ohio, the largest single emitter of sulfur dioxide in the nation.
   ``This is a statesmanlike proposal, but it doesn't include enough
reductions soon enough to adequately protect public health or the
environment,'' said Weiss.
   However, he said the environmental group believes that the
proposal will help move acid rain control legislation in Congress.
   Susan K. Roth, spokeswoman for the Edison Electric Institute,
said the deadlines in the Celeste-Cuomo proposal are not flexible
enough to allow for the use of new clean-coal technologies. And she
said the additional costs to the oil industry would be passed along
to consumers.
   ``We don't see that this is going to give us any better long-term
reductions than the program that is already in place,'' said Ms.
Roth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
