<DOCNO> AP880607-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-07 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Draws Contrasts Between Himself And Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, saying he ``can't wait for this
primary season to end,'' is going on the offensive in an effort to
portray Democrat Michael Dukakis as a ``Massachusetts liberal in the
stripe of George McGovern.''
   The primary season ends today with voting in California, New
Jersey, Montana and New Mexico.
   At a GOP function in San Bernardino Monday, Bush applied the
``Massachusetts liberal'' label to Dukakis. And at a news conference
earlier in the day, he said, ``I don't sense a swing to the left in
this country to this Brookline, Massachusetts, liberalism.''
   Brookline is the Boston suburb where Dukakis grew up and lives
today.
   In his remarks to the GOP audience, Bush ticked off a number of
issues on which he said he and Dukakis differ.
   ``I favor the death penalty for drug kingpins and he opposes
it,'' said the vice president.
   ``I'll never understand,'' he went on ``why Michael Dukakis
vetoed a bill providing for the Pledge of Allegiance to be said in
the schools of Massachusetts. I favor the Pledge of Allegiance being
said anywhere and everywhere.''
   Dukakis has said he vetoed the legislation after being advised by
the state supreme court that it was unconstitutional.
   Bush's free-wheeling attack on the Dukakis was the sort of
offensive many Republicans have been advising as a way to overcome
the advantage Dukakis currently holds in opinion polls of voters.
   At his news conference, Bush dismissed surveys suggesting he
trails Dukakis in California and nationwide.
   He said that in one survey two-thirds of the respondents said
Dukakis was more conservative than Bush.
   ``There's something weird about that,'' he said.
   Bush was certain to sweep the 175 delegates at stake in
California's winner-take-all Republican primary. All of his GOP
opponents have dropped out of the race and endorsed him for the
party's nomination to succeed Ronald Reagan.
   Dukakis was expected to pick up enough delegates in the day's
four primaries to clinch the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Bush supporters contend that the public has a distorted image of
the Massachusetts governor because he has been involved in a race
against Jesse Jackson, a contest in which Dukakis came across as a
moderate.
   A major goal for the Republicans is to portray Dukakis as a
liberal who would return the country to big spending domestic
programs.
   The Massachusetts governor twitted Bush over the vice president's
decision to call Sunday for a delay in offshore oil drilling off the
Northern California coast. Dukakis called the decision an effort to
curry favor among California voters who tend to feel strongly about
environmental issues.
   The issue subsided when Interior Secretary Donald Hodel suspended
plans to lease 1.1 million acres off the Northern California coast
for oil drilling.
   ``He can make a political challenge,'' Bush responded to Dukakis'
criticism, ``and I will be challenging him as to what he thinks is a
great energy program for the United States of America.''
   Bush said, ``I have a good deal more information than Mr.
Dukakis. I made my living at it (oil drilling).''
   Bush, drawing a contrast between his position and that of
Dukakis, said, ``I do not favor shutting down all offshore drilling
in this country.''
   He said their differences would be aired and ``I am, I think, on
the right side.''
   Dukakis, who speaks fluent Spanish has shown strength in some
surveys among California's large Hispanic population, but Bush said
he was confident of doing well among the same voters.
   ``On the Hispanics, I have some understanding there,'' he said
``because three of my grandchildren are half Mexican.'' His son
Jeb's wife is Mexican.
   ``I think I understand the heartbeat of the Hispanic community,''
he went on.
   Bush's position on the offshore drilling was another step away
from Reagan administration policy which favors more drilling, and
the vice president said more such differences would emerge.
   ``As I become the standard-bearer of this party, I'm going to be
saying, without regard to current administration position, here's
what George Bush feels,'' he said.
   ``We'll probably be dragged into more of these things rather than
less, but I will try to keep it that I don't go out and do something
to tear down or be negative about this president. It may not always
be that easy.''
</TEXT>
