<DOCNO> AP880607-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-OperaHumor     06-07 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Opera Humor,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tongue-In-Cheek Tabloid Designed To Draw Opera Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new tabloid aimed at encouraging Hoosiers
to spend a night at the opera instead of a night at the basketball
game features screaming headlines and bizarre tales _ of Hoffman.
   According to the debut edition of the Indianapolis Opera
Inquirer, an avid opera fan supposedly gave birth to a boy during
the last act of a performance of ``Tales of Hoffman.'' Three ushers
and a cast member received a standing ovation for helping with the
delivery.
   Another story tells the tongue-in-cheek tale of a teen-ager who
took off his personal stereo for the first time in three years to
hear the opera ``Carmen.''
   ``He washed the green and pink dye out of his hair, put on clean
clothes and helped me set the table,'' his thrilled mother was
quoted as saying.
   The Inquirer will be mailed to subscribers and about 20,000
non-subscribers. A ticket order form is included.
   ``I love it because you're definitely going to read it and it has
the confidence to have humor. It says that opera is for everyone,''
Indianapolis Opera Artistic Director Robert B. Driver said.
   ``Opera has always been viewed as the fat lady with the big
voice, as stodgy and only for the elite. But that's not at all
true,'' said Vaughn B. Hickman, president of Hickman and Associates
advertising agency and the brains behind the Inquirer campaign.
   Two years ago, Indianapolis Opera had 900 subscribers. Last year,
after another Hickman promotion, there were 1,300.
   Hickman and opera officials said the numbers indicate how
difficult it is to sell opera in sports-loving Indiana. They believe
the tabloid will help change attitudes.
   ``Just like sports, opera is recreation, enjoyment and fun,''
said Donna Noblitt, marketing and public relations director of
Indianapolis Opera. ``The unknown is always a little scary, but we
want to excite people and get them to try it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
