<HEAD>Japanese Red Army Members in Korea Will Try to Return, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven suspected members of Japan's Red Army
terrorist group who hijacked a Japanese airliner to North Korea 18
years ago want to come home for trial, a Japanese journalist said
today.
   Takamaro Tamiya, the group's leader, delivered that message in a
lengthy telephone call to the Tokyo-based monthly literary magazine
Bungei Shunju, said an employee of the magazine who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Tamiya urged the Japanese government to meet with his group for
talks and told the magazine they would ask to be tried in a Japanese
court.
   Last month, Japanese police arrested one of the nine suspected
Red Army members who hijacked the Japan Airlines domestic flight to
the North Korean capital of Pyongyang in 1970.
   Police believe Yasuhiro Shibata, 34, returned to Japan in April
1985 from North Korea with a false passport. He is the only suspect
arrested in the hijacking.
   Investigators in Tokyo were questioning Shibata about the
hijacking and whether he and other members of the group were
plotting renewed terrorist action, police said.
   One of the original nine men died of illness recently in
Pyongyang.
   The Red Army, formed in the late 1960s, advocates ``simultaneous
world revolution.'' It is said to have had no more than 300 members
at its peak and in recent years has operated mainly with Arab
leftists in the Middle East.
</TEXT>
