<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Spence     06-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spence,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Suffering Pneumonia, Rejection of New Lungs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Floyd Spence has taken a turn for
the worse and is suffering pneumonia and an attempt by his body to
reject the lungs he received in a May 7 transplant, doctors say.
   ``It's a definite setback. No question about it. His condition is
pretty serious,'' Dr. Seshadri Raju, who led the University of
Mississippi Medical Center transplant team, said Monday.
   The 60-year-old South Carolina Republican, who suffered from
emphysema, overcame earlier episodes of infection and rejection and
had been doing well enough in a private room to walk with assistance
and ride a stationary cycle.
   He was moved out of his private room and into coronary care
Sunday night because he was having difficulty breathing, perhaps
because of the pneumonia, Raju said.
   ``It will take 24 to 36 hours to sort things out. We think he may
be having a rejection on top of an infection,'' he added, saying he
suspects a rejection episode because of the deterioration in
Spence's condition.
   Spence is being treated with Gentamicin and Vancomycin, two of
the most powerful antibiotics available, and is being fed
intravenously while receiving supplemental oxygen, Raju said.
   His blood pressure, heart and kidneys continue to be normal, Raju
said.
   Spence, whose condition has been downgraded from stable to
serious, was alert and talking until he was heavily sedated, Raju
added.
   The six-term incumbent has announced plans to seek re-election.
He is being challenged by Democrat Jim Leventis.
</TEXT>
