<HEAD>Customs Commissioner Appoints Ombudsman to Help Innocent Victims
of
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Customs Service's controversial ``zero
tolerance'' program will have an ombudsman to advise people who
become entangled in the federal anti-drug effort.
   ``We are concerned about the small number of innocent people who
are unfortunate to be unwittingly associated with criminal
activity,'' U.S. Customs Commissioner William von Raab said Monday
in announcing the appointment.
   ``I want to emphasize that this appointment does not mean we are
backing off zero tolerance one bit,'' von Raab said in making the
announcement.
   He said Janet L. Labunda has been assigned to help boat owners
and others to avoid unnecessary legal expenses if their property is
seized as part of the effort against drug trafficking.
   Boat owners and civil libertarians last month angrily criticized
the policy when the owner of the $2.5 million yacht Ark Royal had to
pay $1,600 in fines and fees after the service seized the vessel
because a small amount of marijuana was found. The marijuana
allegedly was taken aboard by a crewman.
