<HEAD>Pentagon Seeks To Sell Air Defense System to Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration wants to sell the
U.S. Navy's most sophisticated shipboard air defense system to Japan
as part of a $468 million sales package.
   The Pentagon, in a series of announcements, also notified
Congress on Monday of additional plans to sell arms to South Korea,
Greece and Turkey. Those deals will total about $200 million.
   The proposed sale of the Aegis Combat System to Japan generated
opposition in the House earlier this year, but that opposition has
evaporated and the deal is now expected to win congressional
blessing.
   ``Installation of Aegis on a ship of the Japanese Maritime
Self-Defense Force will enhance Japanese capability to protect its
sea lines of communication,'' the Pentagon said.
   ``It is in U.S. national interests to assist Japan in meeting
these goals.''
