<HEAD>Officer Escorting Kennedy Family to RFK Service Struck By Driver</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kennedy Remembrance Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANGLEY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Park Police officer was in critical
condition today after being struck by a speeding driver while he was
escorting the Kennedy family to a memorial service for Robert F.
Kennedy.
   Sgt. Paul Johnson, 37, fractured his skull in the collision
Monday, which happened as he was directing traffic on a suburban
Washington, D.C., roadway the Kennedy motorcade was taking to
Arlington National Cemetery, officials said.
   A man standing next to the officer suffered minor abrasions, but
none of the Kennedy family members was injured, said Fairfax County
Police spokeswoman Debbie Godwin.
   Paul D. Addington, 18, of McLean, Va., was charged with reckless
driving in the accident, said Godwin.
   The police spokeswoman said Addington was speeding when he came
over the crest of a hill, hit his brakes and skidded into two police
motorcycles, said Godwin. The collision threw Johnson's motorcycle
against him, Godwin said.
   Johnson, a 12-year veteran of the U.S. Park Police, was in
intensive care early today at Fairfax Hospital.
   About 5,000 people attended the memorial service Monday at
Kennedy's grave. The ceremony marked the 20th anniversary of his
assassination.
