<HEAD>Tokyo Exchange Falls After Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell slightly at
the end of trading Tuesday after a record high closing the previous
day, and the U.S. dollar weakened against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues declined by a
light 28.92 points, or 0.1 percent, to finish the day's trading at
27,967.32.
   On Monday, the stock market's key barometer closed at 27,996.24
points to hit its highest closing level on record.
   After opening the day at 125.75 yen, the dollar edged up slightly
and ended the day at 125.77 yen, down 0.30 yen from Monday's close.
   ``The dollar is moving in tight range in the absence of
incentives to direct the market,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at
a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. currency was stable against the yen despite weakening
against the West German mark, he said. Bundesbank President Karl
Otto Poehl confirmed his opposition to a higher dollar against the
mark in comments over the weekend.
   Stock prices rose on the strength of a rally Monday on Wall
Street, although traders were cautious in the wake of recent sharp
rises in the Nikkei index.
   The market's main barometer topped the 28,000-mark for the first
time Monday and closed at a record high 27,996.24 points.
