<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-SovietProtest     06-07 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Soviet Protest,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightist Groups Protest Arrival Of Soviet Fishing Ships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing groups today protested the arrival of two
Soviet fishing vessels by blasting anti-Soviet slogans at them from
110 cars and trucks rigged with loudspeakers.
   More than 1,700 police officers were mobilized to protect 53
sailors aboard the ships in Shiogama, a port city about 190 miles
northeast of Tokyo, said a Miyagi Prefectural Police spokesman who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   There were no reports of injuries or scuffles between police and
the 410 rightists representing 60 fringe groups, the spokesman said.
Police blocked roads and fenced off the port area.
   The 738-ton Komissorovo and the 448-ton Belinskoe called on
Shiogama to replenish food and water supplies and were scheduled to
depart Wednesday afternoon. Crew members were allowed off the ships
today for shopping, the spokesman said.
   Soviet fishing ships are allowed to dock at designated ports in
Japan under a bilateral fisheries treaty. The two vessels, the first
to call at Shiogama under the pact this year, represented only the
second port call since 1985.
   Fiercely anti-communist right-wing groups in Japan often deploy
specially equipped vehicles with loudspeakers to protest the Soviet
presence in several northern islands claimed by Japan but occupied
by the Soviet Union since the end of World War II.
</TEXT>
