<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0455 06-07 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0455,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega In Firm Control One Year After Allegations Fueled
Opposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to fix punctuation. Picks up 3rd graf, `Diaz
Herrera ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after a former top aide
accused him of rigging elections, drug trafficking and corruption,
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega still firmly controls the government and
may well run for president next year.
   The accusations were made by Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera last June
after he was demoted from second-in-command. They emboldened
thousands of Panamanians to take to the streets to demand Noriega's
ouster.
   Diaz Herrera was arrested and sent into exile in Venezuela.
   A similar fate befell Eric Arturo Delvalle, who as president
tried to fire Noriega as Defense Forces chief in February after two
U.S. grand juries indicted the general on drug trafficking charges.
   Noriega ousted Delvalle, who went into hiding in Panama.
   On Monday, opposition leaders called on Latin American
governments to mediate efforts to remove the general from power, a
goal Washington has failed to achieve through economic sanctions and
negotiations.
   But Noriega has indicated he will not permit any mediation that
would ease him out of office and the government already is making
plans to hold elections in May 1989 with or without the opposition.
   Pro-government groups are mentioning Noriega as a likely
candidate of the government's Democratic Revolutionary Party in next
year's presidential elections.
   A source close to Noriega told The Associated Press Monday night
that any discussions with Latin American leaders would amount to
``talks with the United States by proxy.''
   ``And the general is not leaving,'' said the source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``The United States and the opposition must
understand that.''
   The Reagan administration announced last month that its effort to
remove Noriega through negotiations had failed. The widespread,
mostly nonviolent opposition demonstrations that began one year ago
also failed to loosen the general's grip on power.
   A Foreign Ministry statement released Monday night assailed the
opposition call to ``Latin Americanize the Panamanian crisis'' as an
effort ``to hide ... the deliberate execution of a vast plan of
internal destabilization'' against the government.
   Noriega has strengthened his position by forming the Strategic
Military Council, a group of 20 of his closest collaborators. They
include the commander of the elite Year 2000 Battalion, another
troop commander and key officers in other sections of the
15,000-strong Defense Forces.
   ``They supersede the Chiefs of Staff,'' said an opposition
leader, also speaking privately. ``They are younger than the chiefs
of staff and are the ones making all decisions with Noriega.''
   Dr. Ricardo Arias Calderon, head of the Christian Democrat Party,
said the council may have promoted the breakdown in talks with the
United States.
   ``They probably want Noriega to stay on longer and get rid of the
older members'' of the Defense Forces command, he said.
   Chief of Staff Col. Marcos Justines, who negotiated with U.S.
representatives, is not a member of the council.
   On Monday night Noriega and his generals, dressed in civilian
clothes, accompanied president Manuel Solis Palma and other top
military officers to attend a play depicting U.S. interventions in
Panama. The sketch was performed by members of the Defense Forces'
elite anti-terrorist unit.
   Hundreds of people chanted anti-American slogans and applauded
Noriega as he shook hands with civilians and military recruits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
