<DOCNO> AP880607-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Raines     06-07 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Raines,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1940s-Era Film Star Ella Raines Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ella Raines, who starred opposite John Wayne
and Charles Laughton and who traveled the world as the wife of a
World War II flying ace, has died of throat cancer. She was 67.
   Private family servies were held for the 1940s-era star whose
screen image was described as sultry and mysterious. She died last
week at her home in suburban Sherman Oaks.
   Ms. Raines, born in Snoqualmie Falls, Wash., achieved almost
overnight stardom in 1943 when she was made the sole contract star
of a $1 million production company founded by actor Charles Boyer
and director Howard Hanks.
   Her first movie was ``Corvette K-255,'' but she was probably best
known for her role in the 1944 thriller ``Phantom Lady.''
   She made 20 films, including ``Tall in the Saddle'' with Wayne
and ``The Suspect'' with Laughton, and also starred in the 1950s
television series ``Janet Dean R.N.''
   Ms. Raines, whose first marriage to a childhood sweetheart ended
in divorce shortly after World War II, married flying ace Maj. Robin
Olds in 1947.
   The union led to international travel as her husband was
transferred to various bases around the world.
   Olds, who eventually became a brigadier general, was commander of
the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs in the late 1960s, where
the couple was well known for their entertaining.
   The couple divorced in 1975, and Ms. Raines returned to Southern
California.
   She made guest appearances on a few TV shows in recent years,
including ``Matt Houston'' and ``Police Story.''
   She is survived by two daughters, Christina Newman and Susan Olds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
