<HEAD>Goode, Coleman Angry at Pennsylvania Delegate Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the city's top Democrats are
complaining about rules that gave all of Pennsylvania's 62 pledged
party and at-large delegates to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode and City Council President Joseph Coleman
reaffirmed their support for Jesse Jackson in a statement issued
late Monday.
   ``It's unfortunate that the political leadership of one of the
largest cities in the nation find themselves in the position of
having to attend the Democratic National Convention as Dukakis
delegates in spite of their continued support of Rev. Jackson's
candidacy,'' the statement said.
   The state committee awarded the delegates to Dukakis during a
weekend meeting.
   Jackson got only 7 percent of the delegates even though he won 28
percent of the popular vote in the April 26 primary.
   Democratic state chairman Larry Yatch agreed the rules need to be
changed at the Atlanta convention.
</TEXT>
