<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka     06-07 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Soldier, Wounds Four as Indians Begin Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separatist Tamil rebels blew up an
Indian army jeep today, killing one soldier and wounding four just
hours before hundreds of Indian troops began boarding nearby ships
to return home.
   One Sri Lankan officer called the attack ``a show of strength''
by the rebels, who have fought a five-year war for greater autonomy.
Indian officials said their at least partial troop withdrawal would
go on as scheduled.
   Sri Lankan military officers said the jeep was patrolling about
six miles south of the port city of Trincomalee when the rebels
detonated a mine under it. Just a few hours later, Indian sodliers
began pulling out as scheduled in Trincomalee, 140 miles northeast
of Colombo.
   ``It was a show of strength by the rebels,'' said the Sri Lankan
officer, who cannot be identified under briefing rules. ``It's a
slap in the face.''
   The Indian High Commission, or embassy, confirmed the attack but
gave no details. But Deputy High Commissioner Nirupam Sen said the
attack did not affect the pullout of the first contingent of Indian
peacekeeping soldiers and weapons, including Soviet-made T-72 tanks
and 105mm and 120mm artillery.
   At least 3,000 of the estimated 50,000 Indian soldiers in Sri
Lanka were scheduled to depart for home today by ship from
Trincomalee.
   Indian Defense Minister K.C. Pant said last week that ``excess
troops and armor'' would be sent home but announced no firm
timetable for a complete withdrawal.
   India began sending in soldiers last July to enforce a peace
accord aimed at ending the civil war on this island off its southern
coast. The deployment increased in October after rebels renounced
the peace plan, refused to surrender their weapons and resumed
fighting.
   The Indian troops, stationed only in the north and east where
Tamils are in the majority, had been ordered to disarm the rebel
fighters.
   Predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people and claim they are discriminated against by the
mostly Buddhist Sinhalese, who constitute 75 percent of the
population and control the government and military.
   The peace accord reached by the India and the Sri Lankan
government of President Junius Jayewardene calls for election of
district councils to give the nation's nine provinces greater
autonomy.
   Elections have been held in six provinces so far, and voting is
scheduled for Thursday in the predominantly Sinhalese Southern
Province.
   Balloting has been postponed in the Tamil-dominated Northern and
Eastern provinces because of the fighting.
   India, a major regional power, negotiated the peace accord and
agreed to police it partly for fear of sympathies that its own 60
million Tamils feel for the rebel cause.
   Though the Indians have been unable to stem the fighting, a
string of recent victories led them to agree with Sri Lanka on at
least a partial pullout.
   The Indian presence has been criticized by many Sinhalese, who
view it as a threat to Sri Lankan independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilLeasing     06-07 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Leasing,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Halt Offshore Oil Lease Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the Reagan administration's
proposal for extensive oil leasing off the Northern California coast
claimed credit for the decision to suspend the plan, but said they
remain wary it won't be scuttled.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel late Monday made the announcement
to halt work on the proposal to lease 1.1 million offshore acres.
The decision effectively pushes the sale back at least until to
August 1989.
   Hodel's action came on the eve of the California primary and a
day after Vice President George Bush softened his pro-drilling
stance and called for the offshore plan to be delayed.
   ``I take that as good news,'' Bush, a one-time Texas oilman who
previously had expressed unconditional support for drilling, said
when informed of Hodel's decision while campaigning in Southern
California.
   Democratic presidential hopefuls Michael Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson have advocated stopping all offshore drilling.
   ``This is an attempt to try to get Bush off the hook,'' said
Richard Charter, a Washington lobbyist who represents California
coastal communties in their fight against the drilling.
   He said the announcement also could be an effort to prevent
Congress from imposing a one-year moratorium on the sale. The House
Appropriations Committee is scheduled on Wednesday to consider such
a plan to delay leasing until 1990.
   Anmother critic, Humboldt County Supervisor Wesley Chesbro, said,
``We've succeeded beyond our wildest dreams in making this an issue
of importance to the national campaign.''
   However, he added, ``Temporary political delays are great, but
they're not what we're looking for.''
   Hodel said in a statement that ``it appears that no valid public
purpose would be served by preparation and publication of a final
environmental impact statement containing a proposed course of
action for Lease Sale 91.''
   The department estimates that the area proposed for the lease
could contain up to 790 million barrels of oil _ a two-month supply
for the United States _ and between 820 billion and 1.5 trillion
cubic feet of natural gas. It says there is a 50-50 chance of
finding the petroleum.
   The proposed lease sale of tracts off Mendocino and Humboldt
counties had been tentatively scheduled for February 1989, pending a
decision by the next administration.
   At least six months is needed between the report's conclusion and
a sale, due to hearings and other preparatory work. Department
spokesman David Prosperi said the environmental report could have
been prepared as early as August.
   Hodel indicated he was reluctant to take the action.
   ``I believe we do not have to choose between development of
offshore oil or protection of the California coast,'' he said.
``Experience shows we can have both.''
   Dukakis had criticized Bush earlier Monday for ``coming around''
to his latest position ``kind of late.''
   And, the Democratic front-runner said: ``It's easy to say, `We'll
delay it until after the election.' What does that mean?''
   Bush's aides acknowledged that his statement on Sunday
represented a major concession to strong bipartisan environmental
sentiments in the state.
   ``George Bush recognizes the importance of environmental and
quality-of-life issues in California,'' said chief of staff Craig
Fuller.
   Charter said that if Bush becomes president, Hodel's action
represents ``only a six-month reprieve for Lease Sale 91.'' The
lobbyist said the vice president has not made a clear commitment to
do away with the sale, noting that ``There are a lot of qualifiers
in his statement.''
   The Western Oil and Gas Association said it supported Hodel's
decision for ``a reasonable delay.''
   ``We're political realists,'' said Craig Hume, a spokesman for
the industry group. ``Right now, it is clear that the people of
California _ especially the people of Northern California _ are not
comfortable with the environmental studies that now exist.''
</TEXT>
