<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Migrants-Playground     06-07 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Migrants-Playground,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World of Play Can Be Harsh for Migrant Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIMAUMA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most kids spend their time playing
with toy trucks and tractors, migrant children often play in the
hot, dusty strawberry fields of Florida with the real thing.
   The harsh world of heavy equipment and soil-cutting tools can
mean deep gashing wounds, burns, severed limbs and sometimes, loss
of life.
   It was in one of those strawberry patches on an April day last
year that 7-year-old Karla Polanco nearly lost her leg as she
dangled it over the rear of a truck while her parents picked
strawberries nearby.
   Somebody wanted the truck moved, so her 12-year-old playmate
hopped in the front seat, shifted into reverse and slammed Karla's
leg between the rig and a trailer.
   And last week, 5-year-old Fidencio Jaurequi's right arm was
ripped off at a Dade City farm when he accidentally stuck it in a
tomato sorting machine while his mother worked nearby. Doctors were
unable to reattach the limb because the injury was so severe. The
boy was listed in good condition Monday at Tampa General Hospital.
   With their parents working in the fields from sunrise to sunset
and few available day-care services, hundreds of migrant children
are left to fend for themselves in empty homes or busy fields.
   ``We see the evidence all the time _ cut fingers because the
children stuck them in a fan, burns because the children were hungry
and tried to cook something to eat while their parents were off at
work,'' said Lourdes Villanueva, a former migrant who runs a
day-care program in Plant City.
   In the camps where migrants live, stories abound of children
maimed or killed in accidents in the fields. Many accidents go
unreported to authorities as families move on to other states,
migrants say.
   ``I remember this one woman some years back who brought a
6-month-old baby out into the fields,'' said Concha Calderon, who
has four children. ``The baby got too hot out there and died. She
didn't have anybody to watch it.''
   There is no reliable estimate of the largely undocumented migrant
farmworker population in southern Hillsborough County, but social
workers guess there are between 25,000 and 45,000 people.
   The Redlands Christian Migrant Association, the county's primary
provider of migrant day care, has only 668 available spots for
migrant children and a waiting list of 575.
   There are many more out there, but they don't qualify for
programs like Migrant Headstart because they didn't travel as
farmworkers during the year, experts say.
   ``Even a few years ago I would say there were a lot of workers
still traveling back and forth, from state to state,'' Ms.
Villanueva said. ``But now I think more are just staying here and
working odd jobs during the summer because you just can't make as
much money traveling any more.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
