<HEAD>Lousiana House Approves Bill to Clean Up Dirty Bumper Stickers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists would need binoculars to read
bumper stickers with obscene messages under a bill approved by the
House.
   The bill, which would require that the letters in obscene
messages be no higher than [ inch, was approved 84-14 on Monday and
sent to the Senate.
   Under the measure, which lists about a dozen four-letter words
and combinations, violators would face fines ranging from $200 for a
first offense to $500 for more than two violations.
   Rep. V.J. Bella, a Republican, said he introduced the bill
because he was concerned a measure approved earlier in the session
banning the display of obscene bumper stickers would violate
constitutional protection of free speech. The Senate did not act on
the earlier bill.
