<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shamir     06-07 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shamir,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir: No Concessions to Soviets for Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who meets
with the Soviet foreign minister this week, chided Moscow for
seeking a political deal to improve relations but referred to
Mikhail Gorbachev as a ``great leader.''
   ``The Soviets keep hinting that they will renew diplomatic
relations with us if we agree to their proposal for an international
conference on the Middle East,'' Shamir said in a speech here Monday.
   ``I don't believe we should pay for the resumption of diplomatic
relations. They broke them and they should renew them.''
   In an interview published in The New York Times, Shamir praised
Gorbachev, who has instituted reforms in the Soviet Union.
   ``My observation is, to bring a new message, a new idea to such a
great country, it could be done only by a great leader,'' Shamir
told the Times.
   Less than two years ago, the leader of the hard-line Likud party
described the Soviet Union under Gorbachev as ``old wine in new
bottles.''
   In his speech, Shamir reiterated his opposition to an
international conference, which also was included in a United States
peace plan put forth by Secretary of State George Shultz in a visit
to the Middle East this week.
   Shamir, who met with Shultz in Israel on Sunday, said it is an
``illusion ... that an outside power can successfully offer its own
plan before negotiations begin.'' Indeed, he said, that ``seems only
to retard the movement towards direct negotiations, without
preconditions, which is the only way to settle disputes between
sovereign nations.''
   Israel seeks direct talks with Jordan and with Palestinian Arab
representatives who are not members of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which, Shamir said, cites Israel's destruction as a
goal in its charter.
   Shamir plans to meet Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze at the United Nations this week. There have been
several recent contacts between the countries, although they do not
have formal diplomatic relations.
   Shamir's speech to the Conference of Presidents of Major Jewish
Organizations included a pointed reference to Soviet support of Arab
opponents of Israel. While the Soviet Union has ``important
interests and connections in the region,'' he said, ``we would have
been much happier had it not supported elements who want to destroy
us.
   ``But there is no reason we should help enhance the Soviet
position among our enemies at the expense of our interests. That is
one of the reasons we oppose an international conference.''
   On the issue of political concessions in exchange for diplomatic
relations with the Soviet Union, Shamir said: ``In no other case
does the Soviet Union condition its diplomatic relations on
political concessions. There is no reason why Israel should be
treated differently from any other nation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     06-07 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Decline to File Further Charges Against Mecham</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial resumes at 12:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state decided not to prosecute former
Gov. Evan Mecham for urging supporters to hide their support for him
if called for jury duty in his criminal trial, as prosecutors
prepared to rest their case.
   ``We do not believe it is a prosecutable case,'' Attorney General
Bob Corbin said Monday, referring to Mecham's comments in April.
``Some say it was a joke. Some say it wasn't a joke. It is a case we
do not wish to pursue.''
   Assistant Attorney General Barnett Lotstein said he expects to
rest his case today after testimony by accountant Leroy Johnson, who
told jurors Monday the Mecham campaign was badly overdrawn when it
received a $350,000 loan in October 1986.
   Mecham and Willard Mecham, his brother and 1986 campaign
treasurer, are charged with concealing the loan on financial reports
required by the state. They have denied the charges.
   ``They haven't proved anything,'' the ousted Republican governor
told reporters Monday. Prosecutors have failed to present anything
``that hasn't been public information for seven months.''
   Mecham says he was joking when he said at an April 18 Republican
legislative district meeting that supporters, if called for jury
duty in his trial, should ``have a lapse of memory'' regarding their
support for him.
   Four days later, Corbin began an investigation into whether
Mecham violated any law, including one that prohibits asking
somebody to commit a crime or help commit a crime.
   ``I don't know why he opened the investigation in the first
place,'' Mecham defense attorney Michael Scott said after being told
of Corbin's decision. ``Anyone who knows anything about the
statement knows it was said tongue-in-cheek at a private meeting.''
   On Monday, former top gubernatorial aide Donna Carlson testified
that she warned Mecham during the campaign to distance himself from
the man who loaned him the money, Tempe developer Barry Wolfson.
   Also, former Mecham Finance Committee member Vern Gasser read the
jury a set of notes he took during a committee meeting in the fall
of 1986. The notes say ``show Evan borrowed money'' and ``don't show
borrowed money,'' and some say they appear to reflect a discussion
on whether to disclose the loan.
   However, Gasser said he couldn't recall the conversation or what
the notes meant. Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan
allowed Gasser to read the notes despite defense objections.
   Mecham is charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in
prison if convicted on all counts. Willard Mecham faces three
similar counts and up to 9{ years in prison if convicted.
   Mecham took office in January 1987. He was removed from office
April 4 when the Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment
counts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
