<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TimberStrike     06-07 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Timber Strike,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showdown Over Restoration of Lost Wages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,500 wood mill workers went on
strike in three states in a showdown over efforts to restore wages
and benefits lost two years ago.
   ``We're prepared to stay out till doomsday, and the way things
are going that may not be very long,'' Sam Moore, a union local
president in Sweet Home, said as the strike began Monday.
   The strike shut down 18 wood products operations in the Oregon,
Washington and Montana, affecting Willamette Industries Inc. of
Portland, Champion International Corp. of Stamford, Conn., and DAW
Forest Products Co. of Lake Oswego.
   The walkout followed the collapse last week of negotiations with
the International Woodworkers of America-U.S. and the Western
Council of Industrial Workers.
   The Portland-based unions have vowed to restore wages and
benefits lost in 1986 after a series of unsuccessful strikes.
   ``We already took a 17 percent wage cut and two-year freeze,''
Ken Reynolds said as he walked a picket line outside a Willamette
sawmill in Lebanon. ``We'd have another two-year freeze if we accept
(Willamette's last offer). That doesn't cut it.''
   The first step toward restoration was taken last week when the
unions announced a tentative agreement with Bohemia Inc. of Eugene.
The four-year pact largely restored wages lost two years ago, union
officials said.
   The unions want to use the Bohemia agreement as an industry
standard, but other companies have rejected it.
   The International Woodworkers bargains for 450 workers at
Champion's Roseburg plywood plant. The other union represents about
200 Champion workers at a Klickitat, Wash., sawmill, and 1,800
Champion workers at sawmills and plywood plants at Missoula, Bonner
and Libby, Mont.
   The two unions also represent about 1,300 Oregon workers at five
lumber mills, four plywood mills, two wood products plants, a
machine shop and a logging shop operated by Willamette in Lebanon,
Sweet Home, Dallas and Albany.
   The International Woodworkers also represents a DAW sawmill in
Bend and the other union represents a DAW plywood plant in Redmond.
Each mill has about 400 union workers.
   Willamette spokeswoman said the company's three-year offer
included bonuses the first two years and a 3.5 percent wage increase
the third year. The average plywood worker makes $9.77 per hour, she
said.
   Union leaders oppose bonuses because the base wage rate remains
the same, although annual wages are boosted.
   Industry sources say Bohemia offered increases of 5 percent the
first year and 4 percent in each of the next three years.
   In 1986, the International Woodworkers and the Lumber, Production
and Industrial Workers, which later became the WCIW, staged a
5{-week strike against Weyerhaeuser, affecting 7,500 workers in the
biggest regional timber walkout in the last 25 years.
   That year, 1,100 other workers walked off their jobs at
Willamette Industries and other job actions struck DAW, WI Forest
Products of Lake Oswego and Champion International.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
