<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Palme     06-07 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Palme,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Resigns in Palme Probe Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Anna-Greta Leijon
resigned today after disclosures she authorized an unsupervised
freelance investigation into the 1986 assassination of Prime
Minister Olof Palme.
   Her resignation was intended to head off a vote of no-confidence
in Parliament that could have toppled the minority government of
Palme's successor, Ingvar Carlsson.
   Carlsson said he regretted Mrs. Leijon's departure and would
likely appoint her to a new Cabinet if his Social Democratic Party
is returned to office after elections next September.
   Opposition leaders accused her of overstepping her authority by
bypassing the official investigation into the Palme killing and
approving a secret probe by publisher Ebbe Carlsson, who is not
related to the prime minister.
   Public furor grew over reports the publisher's
government-assigned bodyguard was caught smuggling illegal
wiretapping equipment into Sweden and that the probe was funded by a
$343,000 contribution from a banker.
   Bengt Westerberg, the Liberal Party leader, said questions
remained about the role in the unauthorized probe of the Security
Police, which supplied Ebbe Carlsson with a bodyguard and unofficial
support.
   The publisher was investigating possible Iranian involvement in
Palme's murder. Under the theory, Palme was killed because he
uncovered and tried to halt illegal arms sales to Iran by a private
weapons manufacturer.
   Conservative Party leader Carl Bildt welcomed Mrs. Leijon's
resignation. ``If people want to remain confident in their faith in
Sweden as a society of justice, this was the only possible
decision,'' he said.
   The prime minister said Industry Minister Thage G. Peterson would
be acting justice minister until the next election.
   Mrs. Leijon, 49, was the third justice minister to resign since
the Social Democrats took office in 1982.
   In October, Sten Wickbom quit after a convicted spy escaped while
on an unguarded conjugal furlough from prison. In 1983, Ove Rainer
resigned for allegedly taking advantage of tax loopholes.
   Analysts said the Leijon affair threatened to hurt the Social
Democrats in balloting next September.
   An opinion survey published last weekend showed the Social
Democrats polling 44.7 percent against a combined 43.5 percent for
the three non-socialist opposition parties.
   The balance of power is held by the small Communist Party.
   The Social Democrats, who have been in office for all but six
years since World War II, have 159 seats in the 349-member
legislature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
