<1ST_LINE>r p PM-JacksonBrother     06-07 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson Brother,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Federal Agents Seize Cash from Robinson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized $21,000 in cash from the
Chicago apartment and business office of Noah Robinson, Democratic
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson's half-brother, newspapers
reported today.
   Robinson, 45, was arrested Saturday in Greenville, S.C., on
charges of hiring someone to attack a witness in the slaying of a
former employee.
   Robinson has denied the charges and accused officials of
targeting him because of Jackson's high profile and of trying to
turn him into ``the Billy Carter of the Jesse Jackson campaign.''
   Robinson's Chicago attorney, Jerome Rotenburg, said cash seized
was from Robinson's chain of fast food restaurants, according to
today's editions of the Chicago Tribune and Chicago Sun-Times.
   Rotenburg's office telephones went unanswered Monday night, and
FBI spokesman Jim Kuntzelman said no information could be released.
   The Tribune also said federal authorities had seized the records
of Robinson's businesses in Chicago and were examining them.
   Robinson on Monday posted $50,000 on a $500,000 bond on charges
of accessory to a felony, intimidation of a witness, obstruction of
justice and conspiracy.
   ``I have never been involved in criminal anything,'' he told
courtroom observers and reporters while awaiting his bond hearing.
   Police arrested another man at Robinson's Chicago residence on
Sunday and charged him with being an accessory to the stabbing of
the witness, Janice Denise Rosemond, who survived the attack in her
Greenville apartment in December 1987.
   Ms. Rosemond was a witness to the murder of Leroy ``Hambone''
Barber, a former employee of Robinson who was shot outside a
building owned by Robinson in downtown Greenville, authorities said.
   The man arrested in the Chicago apartment, Holandus ``Jake''
Oliver, 41, was named as a co-conspirator in one of the warrants
filed against Robinson, but authorities declined to elaborate on
what role Oliver allegedly played in the stabbing.
   Robinson said Oliver worked for him in 1974 and recently watched
Robinson's apartment in Chicago when he was out of town.
   Bond for Oliver was set Monday at $100,000.
   Ms. Rosemond was stabbed after testifying before a grand jury
about Barber's death. She later recanted her testimony.
   Robinson said he believes the charges against him stem from his
attempts to help ex-convicts and others in need and from political
forces trying to derail Jackson's bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Greenville Police Chief Mike Bridges said Robinson's arrest ``has
nothing to do with political motivations. When we felt we had enough
to charge him and arrest him that's what we did. We treated this
case like any other case.''
</TEXT>
