<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sikhs     06-07 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sikhs,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Block Demolition of Buildings Around Golden Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 1,000 demonstrators today blocked
the government from wrecking buildings around the Golden Temple to
create a security corridor free of hiding places for Sikh militants,
authorities said.
   The crowd gathered on a road and prevented construction vehicles
from moving in to demolish the buildings within 30 yards of the
holiest shrine of the Sikh religion.
   Sikh militants have used the temple as a base in their battle for
an independent homeland.
   Militants shot and killed a Sikh couple at a village near
Amritsar on Monday, the United News of India said.
   The killings raised to 1,259 the number of people killed this
year in attacks blamed on Sikh radicals. Many of the victims have
been members of the majority Hindu community, but the militants have
also targeted moderate Sikhs.
   Most of the demonstrators in Amritsar were tenants of the
affected buildings, an Amritsar district government official said.
The demonstrators were demanding that they be provided alternate
housing before they were evicted, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said senior government officials were negotiating with the
demonstrators. ``The demolitions will not begin until the problem is
resolved,'' he said.
   Plans for the security corridor were launched after a 10-day
police siege of the temple ended on May 18. More than 200 militants
surrendered to police during the siege that left 46 people dead,
including 41 suspected radicals and five civilians caught in
crossfire..
   Police found it difficult to maintain a cordon around the shrine
because the maze of alleys, shops and houses next to the complex
provided cover for radicals.
   Sarbjeet Singh, the top government officer in the district, said
workers would demolish 522 properties by the end of the year and
create a corridor 1.7 miles in circumference.
   The entire project, scheduled to be completed within two years,
was expected to cost $115 million, which would include expenses to
buy the land and relocate families and businesses, he said.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are in a
majority in northern Punjab state, where Amritsar is.
   Sikh militants have been agitating since 1982 for an independent
homeland in Punjab. They say they are discriminated against by
Hindus, who comprise 80 percent of the country's population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
