<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower in Slack Trading, Gold Falls Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf to CORRECT dollar figure. Picks up 15th graf,
`Gold opened ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in slack European trading this
morning, though many dealers said they expected little fluctuation
before release of U.S. trade figures in a week.
   Gold prices also were slightly lower.
   Dealers in Frankfurt said the market continued to react to the
West German Bundesbank's recent sales of the U.S. currency and
opposition to a further dollar increase signaled by central bank
president Karl Otto Poehl.
   But in Milan and Frankfurt, traders predicted there won't be much
movement in the dollar until the U.S. trade figures for April are
released next Tuesday.
   One Milan trader said he expected the April trade deficit to be
around $10 billion, little changed from the $9.75 billion shortfall
in March.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.30 yen to a closing 125.77 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted slightly lower at 125.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates:
   _ 1.7114 West German marks, down from 1.7190
   _ 1.4263 Swiss francs, down from 1.4357
   _ 5.7855 French francs, down from 5.8122
   _ 1.9219 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9303
   _ 1,272.50 Italian lire, down from 1,277.65
   _ 1.2315 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.8107 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.8025 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $463.30 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $463.40. Both were slightly lower than Monday's
late bid of $463.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $463.40, down from $464.50 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 36 cents to close at $464.03.
   Silver also fell in London, where it was selling at a bid price
of $7.28 a troy ounce compared with late Monday's $7.34.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
