<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlightAborted     06-07 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flight Aborted,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jetliner Returns To Airport After Control Tower Notices Leaking
Fuel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jetliner carrying 105
people returned safely to Los Angeles International Airport after an
air traffic controller noticed fuel leaking from a wing.
   American Flight 2223, a Boeing 737 loaded with 16,000 pounds of
fuel, took off at 10:37 a.m. Monday on a flight to San Jose when an
air traffic controller notified the pilot he noticed fuel leaking
from the right wing.
   The pilot then declared an emergency and returned to the airport
20 minutes later, said Elly Brekke, a spokeswoman for the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   Firefighters stood by, but the passengers and crew left the
aircraft without having to use emergency chutes, Ms. Brekke said.
   The leak was caused by a faulty fuel cap, according to Steve
McGregor, an American Airlines spokesman in Fort Worth, Texas. The
plane carried a full load of 100 passengers, plus two pilots and
three flight attendants, he said.
   The FAA, Brekke said, sent inspectors to investigate the incident.
</TEXT>
