<DOCNO> AP880607-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-07 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Writers Schedule More Contract Talks With Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters ended a 12-hour
negotiating session with television producers early today,
scheduling a fifth straight day of talks as the walkout enters its
14th week.
   ``We're not characterizing how the meeting went,'' Writers Guild
of America spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said early today when asked if
the continuing talks meant some hope for a breakthrough.
   The latest session, at the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers headquarters, ended at 2 a.m. today, Ms. Rhoden
said. The next round of talks was scheduled for 1:30 this afternoon,
she added.
   The two sides began meeting Friday.
   Ms. Rhoden declined to comment on the issues discussed.
   The writers walked out March 7 in a dispute centering on payments
or residuals for reruns of one-hour television shows. Demand for
such programs in rerun, or syndication, is declining, and the
producers want to tie payments to a show's success in the rerun
market.
   The two sides also have been at odds over writers' demands for
more creative control over changes made in scripts during filming
and more on- and off-screen credit.
   The guild has signed full-term contracts with about 80
independent producers, but the alliance contends none of its large
members has signed and the producers who did defect employ only a
fraction of the writers.
</TEXT>
