<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Students     06-07 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Students,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Posters Criticize Government, Demand Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political discontent among Beijing University
students broke into the open today as students put up illegal
posters demanding democracy and criticizing government corruption.
   Dozens of anonymous posters blanketed bulletin boards on campus
and spilled onto nearby buildings, some with large characters
scrawled in black paint on sheets of newspaper and others written in
tiny characters on notebook pages.
   ``China faces an all-out crisis,'' said one poster. ``The most
basic human rights are imperiled.''
   Several posters demanded a more open press, complaining that
Chinese often learn about events in their own country through the
foreign media. One quoted the preamble to the U.S. Declaration of
Independence, with its defense of ``life, liberty and the pursuit of
happiness.''
   Students said they planned to march Wednesday from campus to
Tiananmen Square, the symbolic center of power in Beijing, to
dramatize their demands. Street marches are illegal without police
permission.
   A graduate student at Beijing University slain last week in a
brawl outside a liquor store. On Friday, about 1,000 students
marched to Tiananmen Square and met with officials to demand
improved security and the arrest of the killers. Police arrested six
suspects within 48 hours of the killing.
   Since Friday, hundreds of students have gathered nightly around
campus bulletin boards, holding debates and encouraging each other
to draw a larger lesson from the killing.
   ``People are concerned about more than just this incident,'' said
one girl. ``They want to do something for the living.''
   Several times in recent months university students have put up
posters criticizing government bureaucracy and demanding more state
funds for education. The new posters repeated those themes, but also
demanded democracy and freedom for the first time since
pro-democracy protests swept China in the winter of 1986-87.
   Those protests, in which thousands of students marched through
Beijing and other major cities, led to a government crackdown on
liberalism and the ouster of Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang for
his alleged tolerance toward the students.
   Students since have been careful not to raise the themes of
democracy and freedom.
   A Beijing University freshman said today that students are
divided over whether agitation now will help or hurt the cause of
democracy.
   ``The 7th National People's Congress was the most democratic
ever,'' he said, referring to the national legislative session held
in March and April, at which delegates were encouraged for the first
time to debate selected issues.
   ``We see democracy moving forward slowly. But if conditions
become upset, the government will again rule with a firm hand,'' he
said. ``Perhaps the steps we take will not lead us to our goals _
perhaps just the opposite.''
   Other students acknowledged that they lack the support of wider
groups in society. Most urban workers are more concerned with the 11
percent inflation rate than such abstract issues as democracy.
   One poster urged the students to join in the planned march
Wednesday to ``propagate among the masses the necessity of democracy
and rule of law.''
   Another claimed, ``A small breeze at Beijing University can raise
up a storm nationwide.''
   One poster accused the government of paying more attention to
crushing student protests than stamping out official corruption.
   ``Even a dog that is wronged gives a few barks. But we Beijing
University students aren't even as good as a dog,'' it taunted,
challeging students to speak out.
</TEXT>
