<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FireDeaths 3rdLd-Writethru a0561 06-07 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Deaths, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0561,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Dead in Apartment Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with inoperable smoke detector,
identities of victims, raise details on building and tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out early today in two
apartments above a used furniture store, killing seven people,
including five children ranging in age from 2 to 6, authorities said.
   Six victims _ one woman and all five children _ were found
beneath a boarded-up window, said Hamilton Fire Chief Don Lickert.
   In addition, he said, the three-story, wooden-frame building had
no fire escapes and a door on the ground-floor that was the exit for
the two apartments was locked on the outside.
   Fire officials said they found one smoke detector that had no
batteries.
   The seventh victim, a man, was found in a second-floor hallway,
Lickert said. Three adults were injured, officials said.
   The fire in the building was reported at 3:48 a.m., said Fire Lt.
Joseph Stamper. Officials didn't know what caused the fire or where
it started and arson investigators were at the scene this morning.
   There were three apartments on the second floor, said the
building's owner, Elizabeth Blackburn.
   The door to the two apartments was padlocked on the outside,
apparently by residents who reached through a window to lock it at
night for security, he said. Mrs. Blackburn said she was unaware of
the padlock.
   Two windows in the building were boarded, one to keep pigeons out
of the attic, Mrs. Blackburn said. There was no indication why the
other window, where the victims were found, was boarded.
   The victims died of apparent smoke inhalation, Coroner's
Investigator Thomas Marsh said.
   Butler County Coroner Dr. Richard Burkhardt identified the
victims as Faye Dunham Reeseman and her 2-year-old son Christopher;
Lee Cooper, 30; Mary Smith, 6; Jennifer Miller, 4; and twins Wesley
and James Miller, 2.
   ``I was very close to them. I used to take them to the store,''
Mrs. Blackburn, who did not live in the building, said of the
children. ``That's the only thing I cared about, was those babies.''
   She said the Smith girl and the Millers were the children of
Karen Miller, 30, who was listed in serious condition at Fort
Hamilton-Hughes Hospital. There was no indication how Cooper was
related to the other victims.
   The other two injured adults were listed in fair condition with
burns, officials said.
   Hamilton, about 20 miles north of Cincinnati, is a city of about
60,000.
</TEXT>
