<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Space 1stAdd a0567 06-07 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Space, 1st Add, a0567,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: after launch.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Alexandrov and Soviet cosmonauts Anatoly Solovyov and Victor
Savinykh were making the second joint flight between the two
countries in nine years. On their 10-day mission to the Mir space
station, the cosmonauts took a blooming orchid grown on Earth from
seeds planted in space, the official Soviet new agency Tass reported.
   On the Mir, they will join cosmonauts Vladimir Titov and Musa
Manarov, who have been aboard the station since Dec. 23, 1987 on a
mission that Soviet scientists say is to last more than a year.
   Tass said the joint mission is code-named ``Shipka'' after a
mountain pass in Bulgaria. It will involve about 40 experiments
involving space physics, the remote sensing of Earth, space biology
and medicine.
   The first joint Soviet-Bulgarian space mission took place in 1979
when Georgy Ivanov joined a Soviet crew. Alexandrov was Ivanov's
backup for that mission.
</TEXT>
