<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Pope-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0568 06-07 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0568,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede VATICAN CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Catholic Diocese of Knoxville, Tenn., Created</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES with new details throughout. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Roman Catholic diocese of Knoxville
was established today by Pope John Paul II, who named an Irish-born
priest as the first bishop to the post.
   The Knoxville Diocese, comprised largely of rural counties, will
include the cities of Chattanooga, Johnson City and Kingsport and
will have a Catholic population of about 36,000, said Gary Honnert,
director of communications for the Memphis Diocese.
   The Vatican said the diocese was created from territory taken
from the diocese of Nashville.
   Appointed as bishop was the Rev. Anthony O'Connell, 50, a native
of Lisheen, County Clare, who immigrated to the United States 30
years ago, the Vatican said. He has been serving as rector of St.
Thomas Seminary in Hannibal, Mo.
   The Nashville Diocese, comprised of 95 counties in Tennessee, was
established in 1837, and was the state's only Roman Catholic diocese
until 1971 when Pope Paul VI established the Memphis Diocese,
Honnert said.
   There are about 130,000 Catholics in Tennessee; the Memphis
Diocese has more than 50,000 Catholics.
</TEXT>
