<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bowling-Booze     06-07 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bowling-Booze,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bowling League Says Shut Out Cause Members Didn't Eat And Drink
Enough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a 60-woman
bowling league reinstated at a country club that allegedly took away
the league's time slot because its members didn't spend enough on
food and drinks.
   But a lawyer for the Fern Hill Golf and Country Club said it was
a matter of a lack of a contract and that there wouldn't be any
lanes to spare for the Wednesday Night Ladies House League when the
order takes effect Sept. 7.
   Macomb County Circuit Judge Michael D. Schwartz issued a
preliminary injunction Monday restoring the women's time slot, said
Sharon Lutz, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``We were real pleased,'' said Carol Blossey, president of the
women's league. ``We've said all along we liked bowling at Fern Hill
and we wanted to stay there.''
   The ACLU entered the case last month after the women complained
that Fern Hill management kicked them out because they didn't spend
enough money on food and drink.
   But later, club owner Fred Severini Jr. said the women were not
invited back for their March league because they hadn't signed a
contract. ``Drinking has nothing to do with it,'' he said.
   Lutz said it was the first time in four years that Fern Hill had
required them to sign a contract. She maintained that none of the
other leagues bowling at the country club have contracts.
   Fern Hill attorney David Heyboer said he hopes to overturn the
order.
   ``We're not pleased. We're probably going to end up having a
trial this summer; at this point it's just an injunction,'' Heyboer
said. ``The place only has 12 lanes and those lanes are gone.
   ``We've been under contract with the men's league since Feb. 18.
There's going to be a lot of bowling balls coming down the alley,
I'm afraid.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
