<1ST_LINE>u n PM-GeraldFord     06-07 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gerald Ford,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Officials Should Resign If Staying in Office Harms President,
Ford Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This expands 3rd item in PM-Washington in Brief, a0479, to
include remarks in response to question on Meese. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any Cabinet-level federal official should
resign if continuing in office harms the president or the
presidency, former President Gerald Ford said in response to a
question about Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Ford, in an appearance Monday before the National Press Club, was
asked what advice he would give Meese regarding resignation from
office. An independent counsel has been investigating
conflict-of-interest allegations regarding Meese's financial
dealings.
   ``I strongly believe that when a person in the Cabinet or in some
comparable post in the federal government, if he is challenged for
alleged misdeeds, if his staying in office in any way undercuts or
jeopardizes the president or the presidency, that individual should
walk into the Oval Office and offer his resignation,'' Ford said.
   He did not mention Meese by name, nor did he say Meese's
continuation in office undercuts or jeopardizes the president.
   Ford said in his speech that the deficit-saddled federal budget
process ``is in total shambles'' and Congress should restore power
to the White House to straighten out the mess.
   Ford called for Congress to reinstate the president's power to
impound appropriated money, a device Congress removed when it
streamlined the budget process in 1974.
   ``The anti-impoundment provisions, in my opinion, have been a
disaster,'' Ford said. The present system is ``no substitute for
strong action by the president of the United States,'' he said.
   Ford's speech came after he unveiled his portrait at the
Smithsonian Institution's Hall of the Presidents, the first
presidential portrait painted explicitly for the collection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
