<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CourthouseSuicide     06-07 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Courthouse Suicide,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Commits Suicide With Shotgun Outside Colorado Courthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stable owner fatally shot himself with
a shotgun after inviting family and friends to a property settlement
hearing that would end his 44-year marriage.
   The courthouse in Arapahoe County, southeast of Denver, has been
the scene of several violent family breakups prompting authorities
to install metal detectors at the door.
   Deputies, who had been alerted by the wife's attorney about the
invitations, watched from atop the courthouse Monday as the stable
owner, Everett Allen, 63, drove by.
   Allen had sent the notes to people who knew him and his wife,
Gracie Maxine, so they could witness ``Gracie's moment of glory,''
said Arapahoe County Sheriff Pat Sullivan.
   Deputies ringed the parking lot and entrance to the courthouse,
planning to escort Allen to the courtroom. As they watched him with
binoculars he drove to park on a dead-end street; then they lost
sight of him.
   Deputies later found him slumped in his seat, with a shotgun
wound in his chest.
   Many of the couple's relatives had shown up for the scheduled
hearing.
   ``We had our hands full trying to keep them away from each
other,'' Sullivan said.
   Bob Cooper, attorney for Mrs. Allen, said the shooting emphasized
that courthouse ``security is essential.''
   He said Mrs. Allen, who is confined to a wheelchair, ``has been
in hiding out of the state for a year and a half.''
   Cooper said he has feared for his life and that of Mrs. Allen.
   ``He sent threats to both of us through friends, relatives and in
letters,'' the attorney said.
   Allen, owner of Stable Inc. in the Aurora area, was charged with
cruelty to animals in 1974, 1979 and 1983 but was acquitted each
time.
   People entering the courthouse have been scanned by metal
detectors since January when Chanh Van Duong fatally shot his
estranged wife outside a courtroom where they were scheduled for a
child custody hearing.
   Two years earlier, Gerald Utesch, an Aurora police officer at the
time, shot his wife's divorce lawyer, crippling her.
</TEXT>
