<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Space 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 06-07 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Space, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bulgarian Cosmonaut On First Manned Space Mission of Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9 grafs, beginning ``I feel excellent...'' for last 4
grafs pvs to provide additional detail on launch. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bulgarian cosmonaut rocketed into a clear blue
sky today along with two Soviets in the first manned space mission
of 1988, a launch televised live and featuring broadcasts from
inside the capsule.
   Alexander Alexandrov, 36, of the Bulgarian town of Omurtag, and
the two Soviets blasted off at 6:03 p.m. (10:03 a.m. EDT) aboard a
Soyuz TM-5 capsule from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Soviet Central
Asia.
   Soviet television gave unusually extensive coverage of the
liftoff, showing live pictures of Alexandrov's family in Omurtag and
black-and-white shots of the cosmonauts in the moments before and
after launch.
   ``I feel excellent,'' Alexandrov said on the live broadcast
seconds after the launch.
   The broadcast, which lasted more than an hour, showed
Alexandrov's mother and other members of his family watching the
launch on television in Bulgaria. Bulgaria's defense minister was
among the dignitaries viewing the liftoff at the Baikonur Cosmodrome
in the republic of Kazakhstan. The broadcast showed cheering, waving
crowds gathered on Bulgarian streets.
   Only a few clouds were visible in television shots of Baikonur.
Orange flames coming from the Vostok booster rocket contrasted with
the blue sky in the background.
   The mission comes while the American manned space program is
grounded. The last launch, in January 1986, ended in disaster. Seven
astronauts were killed when the space shuttle Challenger exploded.
   Alexandrov and cosmonauts Viktor P. Savinykh and Anatoly Y.
Solovyov are scheduled to dock Thursday with the Soviet space
station Mir. Already aboard Mir are cosmonauts Vladimir Titov and
Musa Manarov, who were the last men to enter space. They boarded Mir
on Dec. 23, 1987.
   During a 10-day mission, Alexandrov and his four Soviet
colleagues are to conduct about 40 experiments, some using Bulgarian
equipment. The expermiments involve space physics, remote sensing of
Earth, space biology and medicine, the news agency Tass has said.
   The cosmonauts are taking with them an orchid grown on Earth from
seeds originally planted on the Mir station, Tass said.
   The last Bulgarian-Soviet flight, in April 1979, was marred by a
failed attempt to dock with the Salyut space station.
   The Soviets plan several other manned missions this year,
including crews from France and Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0086 </DOCNO>
