<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TankerExplosion     06-07 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tanker Explosion,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gasoline Truck Fire Closes Scenic Coastal Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL CAPITAN STATE BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck towing two tankers
of gasoline overturned and exploded early today, pouring flames
across coast-hugging U.S. 101 and spilling fuel down a canyon to the
beach, officials said.
   There were no structures in the fire's path and campers about 200
yards away were not evacuated, officials said.
   The driver of the tanker-truck, carrying up to about 8,800
gallons of gasoline, may have fallen asleep at the wheel before the
accident in the northbound lanes about 20 miles up the coast from
Santa Barbara, said Santa Barbara County Fire spokesman Keith Cullom.
   The driver suffered severe burns over 100 percent of his body and
was in critical condition at the Sherman Oaks Burn Center in Los
Angeles, Cullom said.
   ``He was apparently pinned underneath the truck by a door prior
to the explosion. He freed himself and was burned while running from
the wreckage,'' he said.
   Both sides of the freeway became engulfed in flames and were
closed for several hours, said California Highway Patrol dispatcher
Ed Clark.
   Gasoline entered a drainage culvert under the freeway and flowed
to the ocean, Cullom said.
   ``It burned about five acres of brush before reaching the
ocean,'' he said. ``We don't know yet how much fuel flowed into the
ocean.''
   The driver was identified only as a 42-year-old man from Acton.
</TEXT>
