<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ArabSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0534 06-07 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab Summit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0534,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Leaders Ask for Open Access to Attack Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: EDITS thruout to UPDATE with Gadhafi arrival and comments,
arrival of other leaders, PLO spokesman comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underground leaders of the 6-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories today
called on Arab leaders to open their borders to guerrilla attacks on
Israel.
   The appeal, carried by the Palestinian news agency Wafa, was made
to the Arab chiefs of state who begin a three-day emergency summit
meeting in Algiers tonight.
   The summit was to be devoted to solidifying support for the
Palestinian uprising among the 21 Arab League members.
   The underground leaders of the uprising _ which involves mainly
Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza _ said all
the Arab nations surrounding Israel should ``open their borders to
Palestinian combatants.''
   The appeal was directed mainly at Lebanon, Jordan and Syria, the
three nations represented at the summit that have a common border
with Israel. All three, fearing Israeli reprisals, have taken action
to prevent guerrilla attacks on Israel across their borders.
   Algeria prepared a spectacular welcome for King Hassan II of
Morocco, who arrived on a luxury liner in the Bay of Algiers. His
visit marks the two North African Arab neighbors' reconciliation
after 12 years of hostility.
   Algeria and Morocco resumed diplomatic relations May 16 after
deciding to put aside their dispute over the Western Sahara, at
least for now.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi arrived this afternoon, escorted by
female bodyguards and wearing a gold-embroidered white kaftan. A
black-and-white Palestinian khafia in the colors of the Palestine
Liberation Organization was draped around his neck.
   In a statement distributed by Libya's official news agency JANA
on the eve of the summit, Gadhafi accused unidentified Arab leaders
of ``acting under specific instructions from the U.S. State
Department.''
   ``The possibility of denouncing these leaders before the
Palestinian people and the Arab nation will perhaps be the only
positive point of this summit,'' Gadhafi declared.
   President Hafez Assad of Syria and President Amin Gemayel of
Lebanon were among the last to arrive. PLO chairman Yasser Arafat,
King Hussein of Jordan and King Fahd of Saudi Arabia flew in Monday.
   The underground leaders ``exhorted the Arab chiefs of state to
allow Palestinians living in the Arab countries to take part in the
struggle against the Zionist enemy,'' Wafa said.
   The uprising's leadership also demanded joint Arab action to give
``international protection'' to the Palestinian people and to
demolish all ``suspect peace plans,'' such as that of Secretary of
State George P. Shultz. Today, he ended a four-day tour of the
region to promote the plan.
   An international peace conference with full representation of the
PLO remains the only way to ``a durable, just and global peace,''
the underground leaders declared.
   The United States and Israel officially regard the PLO as a
terrorist organization and seek to bar it from any role in the peace
process.
   PLO spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif said Monday in Algiers that the
Shultz plan was ``born dead.''
   He said the PLO was not only demanding money to compensate for
loss of income due to protest strikes in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, but other forms of support such as food shipments.
   He said political support for the rioting should include a
unified stand by the conferees, rejecting the latest U.S. peace
initiative and reiterating ``their endorsement of the PLO as the
sole, legitimate representative of the Palestinian people, inside
and outside the occupied terroritories.''
   Arab League officials and diplomats said the summit will also
touch on other key problems facing the Arab world, such as the
Iran-Iraq war and the conflict in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
