<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KennedyCandidate     06-07 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Candidate,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patrick Kennedy Sizes Up State Legislature</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Kennedy, the 20-year-old son of
U.S. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, says he may run for the Legislature
against a five-term incumbent.
   The Providence College student said he has commissioned a
political pool to assess the strength of Rep. John Skeffington Jr.,
D-Providence, a funeral director who has longtime family ties in the
ethnic, blue-collar district.
   ``I'm taking it seriously, one step at a time,'' said Kennedy,
who added that he will make a final decision whether to file for the
Sept. 14 primary within three weeks.
   The 50-year-old Skeffington had a difficult primary in 1986 and
won renomination by only 185 votes over a 22-year-old political
newcomer.
   The 9th District is strongly Democratic; for decades, winning the
Democratic primary has virtually assured winning the seat.
   ``I think you've got to wait your turn,'' said Skeffington.
``Sure I wanted to run when I was 20, but I talked it over with
(former Providence Mayor) Joe Doorley and he told me I had to pay my
dues.''
   ``I can't believe the Kennedys are going to try to knock out a
true Democrat,'' he said.
   Kennedy served as a page at the Statehouse last year and was a
researcher for the Legislative Council, the research arm of the
General Assembly.
   President of the Providence College Young Democrats, Kennedy said
he was encouraged by his showing when he was elected as a national
convention delegate in the March primary. He is pledged to
Democratic presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   Kennedy spent $12,000 and finished second among all the delegate
candidates pledged to the Massachusetts governor. Only Providence
Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr., drew more votes.
   ``The response from people in Rhode Island was very positive,''
Kennedy said.
   Kennedy said his father has encouraged his son's political career.
   ``He is happy that I enjoy politics,'' the young Kennedy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
