<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-Soviet-INF     06-07 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet-INF,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INF Verification Teams Meeting For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Soviet commission verifying compliance with
the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty signed by the two
superpowers is meeting in Geneva today for the first time.
   Under the treaty, signed in December by President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the United States and the Soviet
Union must eliminate all missiles with ranges between 300 miles and
3,400 miles.
   The Special Verification Commission is to discuss any problems
that may arise in verifying the elimination of an entire class of
missiles.
   The treaty says that within 30 days ``after entry into force,''
each party must provide the other side with updated data on the
number and location of its missiles. The treaty entered into force
June 1, when Reagan and Gorbachev exchanged the documents of
ratification at their Moscow summit.
   The treaty also says that either side can request a meeting of
the commission to resolve questions relating to compliance with the
accord or to ``agree on such measures as may be necessary to improve
the viability and effectiveness'' of the treaty.
   The U.S. side is headed by Steven Steiner, of the National
Security Council, and the Soviet side by Mikhail Streltsov, who was
a member of the INF treaty negotiating team.
   U.S. officials said they anticipated that the session would last
about two weeks.
</TEXT>
