<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0437 06-07 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Cool To Latin Bid to Negotiate Solution</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts one graf after 4th graf bgng: In an ... to UPDATE with
Fitzwater saying no change in US policy. Picks up 5th graf pvs bgng:
Meanwhile, two ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Latin American effort to negotiate a
settlement to the political crisis in Panama got off to an
unpromising start last week when military leader Manuel Antonio
Noriega showed no inclination to surrender power, according a senior
administration official.
   The official, insisting on anonymity, said Noriega showed ``an
unwillngness to compromise and no give'' in his meeting with former
presidents Caros Andres Perez of Venezuela and Daniel Oduber of
Costa Rica.
   The meeting was held a week after a U.S. negotiating effort
collapsed when Noriega unexpectedly rejected a package deal at the
last minute that would have required him to resign his post as
Defense Force commander in August and temporarily leave the country.
   In an interview Monday, Assistant Secretary of State Elliott
Abrams said Perez, who is seeking another term as Venezuelan
president in elections in December, is expected to report on his
Panama initiative to Secretary of State George P. Shultz later this
month. Abrams refused comment on Noriega's meeting with the two
presidents.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked today if the United
States planned to lift its economic sanctions against Panama, said,
``There has been no change in our policy. We are proceeding on the
same course and don't anticipate any change at this point.''
   Meanwhile, two State Department envoys were dispatched to Panama
last week to assess the situation, but no meetings were held with
Noriega or other government officials.
   Abrams said Morton Abramowitz, head of the Bureau of Intelligence
and Research, explored the possibility of new U.S. options for
dealing with Panama in the wake of the failed negotiating effort.
   Paul Taylor, a deputy assistant secretary who accompanied
Abramowitz, examined the U.S. sanctions against Panama and concluded
that ``the economic pressures on Panama are very great,'' Abrams
said.
   Among other measures, the administration has frozen Panamanian
assets in the United States and is withholding payments to Panama
for services related to the operation of the Panama Canal.
   A separate Latin American initiative on Panama involves an offer
by Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo for his country to be used as
a site for negotiations between Noriega and his political opponents.
   Abrams appeared to hold out little hope that any Latin American
negotiation could reach a settlement that would meet the U.S. goal
of restoring democracy in Panama.
   Abrams noted that the deal U.S. negotiators had worked out was
opposed by an overwhelming majority in the Senate and by Vice
President George Bush. The objections were based largely on the
administration offer to drop federal drug smuggling indictments
against Noriega as part of the package deal.
   Abrams expressed doubt that the Latin negotiators would be able
get a better deal than the one Noriega rejected because they lack
leverage.
   ``The Latins don't have as much clout as we do because they can't
play with the indictments or the sanctions,'' Abrams said. ``How are
they going to get a better deal? If they get a worse deal, how is
that going to be acceptable to the American people?
   ``So the Latin role is both promising and potentially quite
difficult.''
</TEXT>
