<HEAD>`Crocodile' Bites The Competition; `Big' Bigger Than `Rambo'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT `Good Morning, Vietnam' to $120.36
million, sted $12.36 million.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian adventurer Mick Dundee left his
competitors down under as ```Crocodile' Dundee II'' bit off 50
percent more of the weekend box-office gross than its nearest rival,
the Tom Hanks comedy ``Big.''
   Sylvester Stallone's blood-and-blast-filled ``Rambo III'' slipped
to third place, while the Chevy Chase comedy ``Funny Farm''
cultivated enough money to harvest the No. 4 spot, plowing the
George Lucas-produced, Ron Howard-directed fantasy ``Willow'' into
fifth place.
   ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' the comedy sequel starring Australia's
Paul Hogan, hunted up $12.72 million, compared with $8.22 million
for ``Big,'' in which Hanks portrays a boy who gets his wish to
become a grownup.
   ``Rambo III,'' in which Stallone's John Rambo shoots, bombs,
stabs and otherwise maims numerous Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan,
ranked third, grossing $7.69 million for the weekend.
   Chase's portrayal of a sportswriter seeking country-style
relaxation in ``Funny Farm'' reaped nearly $5.66 million.
   The medieval fatnasy ``Willow,'' which cost $35 million to
produce plus $20 million to make prints and for advertising, drooped
two place to fifth, grossing just over $5 million for the weekend.
   ``That's not bad,'' insisted John Krier, president of Exhibitor
Relations Co., which compiles the box office takes. ``It shows
possibilities of holding well.''
   After the top five films, weekend grosses dropped sharply.
   ``Colors,'' the Sean Penn-Robert Duvall, cops-versus-street gangs
drama, brought in $1.45 million, while Michael Keaton's ghostly
comedy ``Beetlejuice,'' scared up $1.42 million.
   ``Friday the 13th Part VII'' slashed another $900,156 out of
filmgoers' wallets.
   Oscar-winning ``Moonstruck'' and the Robin Williams' comedy
``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' showed staying power, grossing $612,475
and $540,891, respectively, after more than two dozen weeks in
release.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in release
and estimated production costs when available:
   1. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' Paramount, $12.72 million, 2,837
screens, $4,482 per screen, $47.64 million, two weeks, n-a.
   2. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $8.22 million, 1,132 screens,
$7,258 per screen, $8.22 million, one week, n-a.
   3. ``Rambo III,'' Tri-Star, $7.69 million, 2,478 screens, $3,105
per screen, $32.33 million, two weeks, $60 million.
   4. ``Funny Farm,'' Warner Bros., $5.66 million, 1,557 screens,
$3,632 per screen, $5.66 million, one week, n-a.
   5. ``Willow,'' MGM-UA, $5 million, 1,035 screens, $4,834 per
screen, $25.33 million, three weeks, $35 million.
   6. ``Colors,'' Orion, $1.45 million, 1,151 screens, $1,263 per
screen, $40.01 million, eight weeks, $12 million.
   7. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $1.42 million, 1,307 screens,
$1,084 per screen, $63.87 million, 10 weeks, $20 million.
   8. ``Friday the 13th Part VII _ The New Blood,'' Paramount,
$900,156, 868 screens, $1,037 per screen, $17.18 million, four
weeks, $3.5 million.
   9. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $612,475, 631 screens, $971 per
screen, $76.37 million, 25 weeks, $17 million.
   10. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney, $540,891, 621 screens,
$871 per screen, $120.36 million, 24 weeks, $21 million.
