<HEAD>Robert Latta Reluctantly Concedes Defeat To Gillmor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0603 to CORRECT cyclc designator.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of retiring Rep. Delbert Latta has
conceded defeat in a close Republican primary race for the
congressional seat the elder Latta has held since 1958.
   Robert Latta said in an interview Monday that he will not pursue
his right to have the validity of a number of ballots from the May 3
primary decided by the Ohio Supreme Court, leaving state Senate
President Paul Gillmor the GOP nominee by just 27 votes.
   ``This decision will mean that the Republican nominee for
Congress from the 5th District will have been nominated by a margin
of 27 votes, the narrowest margin ever recorded in an Ohio
congressional race. Notwithstanding the narrow margin, I
congratulate the winner,'' said Latta, 32, a Bowling Green attorney.
   An official recount of the May 3 primary ballots in the 13-county
northwest Ohio district gave Gillmor 28,694 votes to 28,667 for
Latta. A third candidate, Rex Damschroder of Fremont, received 5,769
votes.
   The closest election suffered by the elder Latta, a member of the
House budget and rules committees, was 55 percent in 1982. He
rebounded to 63 percent in 1984 and did as well in 1986.
   The congressman's son said Friday there was some concern over
several disputed ballots. On Monday, he declined to disclose how
many ballots were in question.
   But one Republican official, who spoke on the condition his name
not be used, said there were fewer than 27 disputed ballots and
suggested that might have been a factor in Latta's decision against
a legal challenge.
   Gillmor, 49, of Port Clinton, said Monday he was glad the primary
was finally over.
   ``This has been the longest election night I have ever been in.
It was an election night that lasted 30 days,'' he joked.
</TEXT>
