<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Hijacker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Seizes Terror Suspect, But Delays Extradition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, A report with 3 new grafs, bgng: In Athens xxx
with Greek comment, new details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is pressing reluctant Greek
officials to permit extradition of a Palestinian suspected of
involvement in the bombings of a Pan Am jumbo jet in 1982 and of a
TWA airliner in 1986, U.S. officials say.
   Greek officials told the United States they did not think the
evidence against Mohammed Rashid was sufficient and asked for
additional information to justify extradition proceedings, a U.S.
official said Monday, speaking only on condition of anonymity.
   He said Rashid was arrested in Greece at the request of the
United States.
   In Athens today, government spokesman Telemachos Hitiris refused
to comment directly, saying only: ``Greece always cooperates for the
eradication of terrorism and is dedicated to the struggle against
it. It imposes the strictest possible penalties against terrorists
according to Greek law.''
   A report about Rashid's arrest and U.S. annoyance over Greece's
hesitancy to extradite him appeared Monday in Eleftherotypia, a
left-wing Greek daily newspaper. The paper said Rashid was seized
Thursday at Athens airport on a tip from an official in the U.S.
embassy.
   ``A police source said yesterday (Sunday) that there are no
charges against Rashid, except maybe the use of a forged passport,''
Eleftherotypia wrote.
   U.S. intelligence information on Rashid indicates he was involved
in a 1986 blast aboard a Trans World Airlines airliner over Greece,
in which four people, including a baby, were killed, the U.S.
official said.
   Rashid also is suspected of playing a role in planting the bomb
that exploded as a Pan American Airways jet was heading toward
Honolulu in August 1982 on a flight from Tokyo. A Japanese teen-ager
was killed and 15 people were injured, none seriously.
   A second source told the Associated Press Greece has not yet made
a decision on the extradition request.
   The first official said Ambassador L. Paul Bremer, the State
Department's top anti-terrorism official, flew to Athens last week
to press the Greek government to permit the extradition of Rashid to
the United States.
   Robert Keeley, the U.S. Ambassador to Greece, also asked for
Rashid's extradition during a meeting last Thursday with Greek
Premier Andreas Papandreou, said a third source, also speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The extradition request comes at a sensitive time in U.S.-Greek
relations. The two countries are negotiating the extension of the
leases on four American bases in Greece. The leases expire Dec. 31.
   Papandreou, under pressure from leftist groups, is seeking to
negotiate favorable terms for extending the leases, including an
increase in U.S. aid.
   The Socialist leader is also on good terms with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, and earlier this year he met in Athens with
PLO chief Yasser Arafat. Greek newspapers reported at the time that
Arafat had promised Papandreou to refrain from terror attacks on
Greek soil.
   U.S. officials have in the past accused Greece of being lax on
terrorism. Relations with Athens were strained in 1984, after Greece
freed a suspected Jordanian hijacker who reportedly was arrested on
the basis of U.S. intelligence information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
