<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Hostages 1stld-Writethru a0584 06-07 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hostages, 1st ld-Writethru, a0584,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Britain and West Germans In Contact With Iran Over Hostages,
Paper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with White House comment. Picks
up x graf pvs ``So widely....''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, Britain and West Germany have
initiated direct contacts with the Iranians in an effort to free
foreign hostages in Lebanon, The Times of London reported today.
   In a front-page story, the conservative daily quoted Shiite and
Sunni Moslem sources in Beirut as saying the United States opened
talks with Iranian officials almost two months ago in the hope of
finding a ``legal'' formula to secure the release of the American
hostages.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
he was not aware of any such contacts and said he had not seen the
Times story.
   ``As you know, we're always talking to people at various levels
about the hostage situation,'' he said. ``These stories come up
frequently and usually aren't correct, and I don't think this one is
either.''
   Asked if President Reagan would be bothered by having his term
end without the liberation of the American hostages in Lebanon,
Fitzwater said, ``Well, he'll be very disappointed, of course. The
hostage situation has been one of enormous concern and frustration
to the president.''
   Times correspondent Robert Fisk, writing from west Beirut, said
separate contacts by the three countries with the Iranians are all
reported to have taken place in Europe.
   ``So widely are the reports now believed in Beirut that the
American Embassy here has been approached by several organizations
representing kidnapped Lebanese in the hope that Washington might
include other hostages in its bargaining with Tehran,'' Fisk said.
   Eighteen foreigners are missing in Lebanon including nine
Americans, three Britons and one West German. Terry Anderson, 40,
the chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985, is the longest-held hostage.
   The Shiite and Sunni sources were quoted as saying that ``legal''
methods of freeing the hostages would involve the paying of
compensation to Iran and the release of Iranian assets which were
frozen after the 1979 revolution that overthrew Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi.
   Iran has repeatedly demanded that the United States deliver large
quantities of American weapons and armor paid for by the shah, the
paper said.
   ``What has emerged only too clearly in west Beirut is that Iran
controls all the foreign hostages still alive here and that even
incidents like the Kuwait Airlines hijacking ultimately have their
roots in Tehran,'' Fisk said.
   ``This is why the increasing reports here of contacts between
London, Washington, Bonn and Tehran are met with so little
incredulity,'' he said.
   Fisk reported new details on several hostage-takings.
   For example, he said, Terry Waite, the Archbishop of Canterbury's
special envoy, is now believed to have been detained in January 1987
by relatives of Mohammed Ali Hamadi, who was arrested in West
Germany four days earlier and is a suspect in the 1985 hijacking of
a TWA jet. Waite went to Beirut to meet with the kidnappers of
Anderson and another American.
   Fisk quoted sources close to the Shiite Moslem Amal militia as
saying Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, the American officer who
commanded a United Nations observer group and was kidnapped in south
Lebanon in February, was targeted for abduction by the Iranian
Embassy in Beirut.
</TEXT>
