<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Film     06-07 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Film,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Premiere of `Last Emperor' Delayed Two Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese premiere of the Academy Award-winning
movie ``The Last Emperor,'' which was to have opened this month,
will be delayed until August, an official said Tuesday.
   The spokesman for the Film Bureau, which must approve all foreign
films shown in China, said Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci's
epic was still being dubbed into Chinese.
   Reports in April said the film would open in a matter of weeks.
   There has been speculation that the Chinese release of the film,
which captured nine Oscars, including best picture and best
director, had run into conservative opposition and would be censored
by Chinese officials.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, denied that.
   The movie was cut by censors in Thailand, Japan and Taiwan.
   Criticisms of ``The Last Emperor'' have appeared in the official
press, including charges that it had ``taken too many liberties with
historical facts and leaned too much toward vulgarity in order to
please moviegoers.''
   The movie depicts the life of the last Chinese ruler, Pu Yi, from
child emperor, to puppet ruler under the Japanese, to prisoner of
the Communists and finally a gardener in China.
   During the annual session of China's legislature in April,
delegates charged that favoritism was shown toward the foreign movie
crew, which was allowed to shoot interior scenes in the Imperial
Palace in violation of Chinese law.
</TEXT>
