<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tito'sWidow     06-07 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tito's Widow,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claims She Was Deprived Of Security After Tito's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of the late president,
Josip Broz Tito, claims the government has taken away her rights and
security since her husband's death eight years ago, a newspaper said
Tuesday.
   Jovanka Broz was involved in a dispute with the government over
her inheritance and has lived in virtual seclusion since Tito,
Yugoslavia's leader for 35 years, died on May 4, 1980.
   The state-run Danas weekly quoted Mrs. Broz as saying that she
was evicted from Tito's palatial residence in an exclusive Belgrade
suburb on June 30, 1980, and was allowed to take along only the most
essential personal effects.
   ``Jovanka Broz claims that, eight years after Tito's death, she
lives deprived of her ... existential security and elementary human
rights,'' the report said.
   One night, she was removed from the residence she shared with
Tito and was taken out through a side door, taking only three little
dogs with her, the report said.
   Mrs. Broz filed suit in 1985 to gain some of Tito's estate,
mostly paintings, furs, jewelry and furniture. The government
quashed the move in December 1986 by ruling the goods were state
property.
   The government has built a new house for her in the vicinity of
her former residence, but Mrs. Broz has refused to move in until the
authorities settle her financial status and inheritance.
