<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     06-07 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Demanding Talks With North Korea Battle Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce fighting broke out at a Seoul
university Tuesday when masked students attacked riot police with
rocks and firebombs and shouted anti-government and anti-U.S.
slogans.
   Student leaders at other universities organized peaceful rallies
and vowed to march to the border with North Korea in an attempt to
force reunification of the North and South.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship!'' and ``Yankee go home!''
students at Soongshil University yelled as they dashed out to hurl
firebombs that exploded in flames around police in front of the
school.
   The violence erupted during mourning for a student from the
university who died Monday after setting himself afire during an
anti-government protest.
   Police fired hundreds of rounds of tear gas but were forced back
several times by groups of protesters who barricaded a road with two
basketball backboards and wielded clubs under cover of firebombs and
rocks flying from the rooftop of a school building.
   The fighting involved about 1,000 students and continued for
several hours, often carrying into nearby alleys, as students chased
squadrons of police huddling behind shields.
   Both students and policemen were seen being hit by rocks and
other missiles, but police had no overall injury figures.
   The front of the campus was draped in black mourning banners as
students inside the school stood watch over the coffin of Park
Rae-chun. Park was the third student to commit suicide in a month.
   Violent clashes erupted at several provincial campuses, but
students held peaceful rallies at many other schools across the
country to prepare for a planned march Friday to the border truce
village of Panmunjom.
   Despite repeated government warnings, radical student leaders vow
to go ahead with their march to the border to force unification of
the peninsula, divided in 1945 into Communist North Korea and
pro-Western South Korea.
   ``Drive out Yankees who forced the partition of our land!'' a
speaker shouted at a campus rally.
   Police vowed to arrest all students marching to the heavily
militarized border. Opposition parties also opposed the march,
urging students to leave contacts with the North to official
channels.
   The protesters contend that the presence of 42,000 U.S. troops in
South Korea _ based here under a mutual defense pact _ hinders
reunification of the two Koreas.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said Tuesday that U.S.
troops would stay in South Korea ``as long as the Korean people want
us to stay.''
   ``The threat from the North has not abated, and the North Koreans
continue to modernize their armed forces and deploy them forward in
a threatening manner,'' Carlucci said after arriving in Seoul.
   Carlucci and many other American officers are here for annual
U.S.-South Korean security consultations, which will include U.S.
security help to ensure a successful Olympics. The Games begin Sept.
19 in Seoul.
</TEXT>
