<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-AIDSCommission     06-07 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House AIDS Commission Takes Up Watkins Recommendations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House AIDS commission opened debate
today on its chairman's 579 proposed recommendations, amid
indications there will be a lot of talk but little real controversy
over most of them.
   ``There is no controversy in the first 11 chapters,'' William B.
Walsh told fellow commissioners.
   Those chapters contain all of the recommendations _ except those
calling for granting the surgeon general sweeping powers to deal
with the epidemic.
   Walsh made clear to the panel chairman, retired Navy Adm. James
D. Watkins, that he does not agree with his recommendations for
essentially turning the AIDS fight over to Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop.
   Watkins said he was determined that the commission make some
recommendation to President Reagan on the best way to structure the
federal health bureaucracy to deal with AIDS.
   ``It is not well done today,'' said Watkins.
   Government bureaucracies usually work, except when they have to
move quickly in emergencies, said Watkins, a former member of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff. And AIDS, he said, is a national health
emergency.
   While saying he was not necessarily determined to stick to his
recommendation that the surgeon general head the fight, Watkins said
the commission has a responsibility to reach a consensus because
``we're in the best position to do it.''
   A cornerstone of the recommendations Watkins made last Thursday
was a call for federal legislation to protect from discrimination
people who have the AIDS virus.
   Although somewhat controversial because it runs counter to the
Reagan administration's stated position, there was clear consensus
on the commission to retain that in the final report due at the
White House June 24.
   Walsh expressed slight reservation about whether Congress should
be getting into that area, but made clear that he favors some kind
of anti-discrimination protection.
   ``If we're going to make it, we should expand it to cover not
just AIDS, but all diseases,'' he said.
   After brief opening remarks, the commission began a page-by-page
discussion of the 269-page report.
   It plans at least two more days of meetings next Thursday and
Friday to vote on the final version, running into the weekend if
necessary to complete deliberations.
</TEXT>
