<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mother-Teresa-Cloth     06-07 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mother-Teresa-Cloth,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Counting Their Blessings After Mother Teresa's Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Mass (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two state prison inmates hope to profit from
Mother Teresa's recent visit by cutting up a seat cloth the Catholic
nun used and selling the 50 pieces for $1,000 a square.
   Ralph Woodward, who is serving 11 to 20 years for breaking and
entering, said he and another inmate claimed a cloth that covered a
place where Mother Teresa sat during a special Mass at the Concord
prison Saturday.
   Woodward said they will use the money for such things as
education after they leave prison.
   ``We just feel that this is a blessing bestowed upon us,''
Woodward told The Boston Globe. ``The fact that she came here is a
miracle and now we have the cloth _ well, it's just phenomenal. And
the fact that other people will have the pieces will just spread the
blessing around.''
   Mother Teresa, who founded a charitable order in India, visited
three Massachusetts prisons Saturday during a national tour.
