<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     06-07 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Votes Switch Or Trade Bill Is Doomed, Senate Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional efforts to make the omnibus trade
bill law over President Reagan's veto are doomed unless sponsors can
switch a handful of votes before Wednesday's showdown on the Senate
floor, leaders said Tuesday.
   ``I hope enough senators will change their minds tomorrow ... and
override the president's veto,'' Senate Majority Leader Robert C.
Byrd, D-W.Va., told reporters.
   Byrd said he could not change the votes and could only hope that
last-minute home-state pressure would cause three senators to relent
and provide the two-thirds margin needed to override Reagan's veto
of the 1,000-page bill, designed to strengthen the U.S. position in
the international marketplace.
   Centerpiece provisions would overhaul the system under which the
government imposes import curbs as a means of aiding U.S. industries
and punishing international trade violations by other countries.
   A wide array of other provisions range from hefty agricultural
subsidies to repeal of the 1980 windfall profits tax on oil-industry
earnings.
   The president vetoed the bill May 24, focusing heavily on
opposition to a provision that would require companies with 100
employees or more to provide notice to their workers of impending
plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   In short order, the House voted 308-113 to override the veto and
approve the bill. But supporters of the measure have found the
Senate tougher going.
   ``We're winning,'' Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., a
critic of the measure, told reporters. ``We've got 36'' votes.
   Even if one senator, Democrat Joseph Biden of Delaware, were not
at home recuperating from surgery, opponents would be able to put an
override out of reach if they could muster 34 votes in the
100-member Senate.
   The administration has said it wants a more moderate version of
the trade bill once the Senate sustains the veto.
   There has been cloakroom talk that some senators looking at their
re-election campaigns feel more comfortable about supporting the
veto if they are assured that there will be another chance to vote
on the trade issue before Congress adjourns in October.
   But it remains uncertain whether there will be such a second
bill. Byrd has repeatedly raised the possibility that a raft of
potential amendments that already have been taken care of over the
last three years would reappear and stall the measure amid lengthy
debate.
   ``There will have to be some agreement between the ledership and
the committee to hold off amendments,'' Dole said. He said there was
scant precedent for such a procedure.
   Failure to approve a trade bill ``would be an issue'' in fall
campaigns, ``but I don't think an overriding issue,'' Dole said.
   Byrd said Reagan ``made a serious mistake on this veto'' because
in disregarding the appeal of the plant-closings provision, ``the
president has written off an issue that involves decency and right.''
   ``The president was poorly advised on it,'' Byrd said.
</TEXT>
