<HEAD>Precede SAN JOSE, Calif.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Expects To Clinch Democratic Nomination Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Dukakis comments today, Simon, Gephardt
endorsements, Kitty Dukakis; pick up 7th graf pvs bgng ``Dukakis
campaigning...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, on the verge of claiming the
majority he needs to wrap up the Democratic presidential nomination,
said today he and Jesse Jackson ``talked in general terms'' about a
future role for Jackson.
   As voters went to the polls in California and three other final
primary states, Dukakis talked positively about the primary season
and the months to come.
   He said he discussed a role for Jackson in a Dukakis
administration when the two met late last night and early this
morning.
   ``We talked in general terms about that,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis said they did not discuss the vice presidential spot.
   ``Tomorrow's another day and I'll be thinking about running mates
providing today is a good day,'' he told reporters.
   The Massachusetts governor was also poised to finally gain the
endorsement of banished rivals Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and
Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois on Wednesday.
   His wife, Kitty, said she was confident the final primaries would
put her husband over the top in his march toward the 2,081 delegates
needed to clinch the nomination.
   ``I think Michael will do well and I'm hoping by the eighth of
June that he will have sewn up the convention,'' Mrs. Dukakis said
in a telephone interview from her hospital bed in Boston.
   Going into today's final round, Dukakis held 1,900 of the 2,081
delegates needed to win the nomination.
   Dukakis, campaigning at a high school in the San Fernando Valley
around Los Angeles, said he hoped to clinch that magic number of
delegates tonight. The campaign was clearly confident he would
secure what was needed from the more than 450 delegates up for grabs
on Tuesday, most of them in California and the remainder in New
Jersey, New Mexico and Montana.
   The Dukakis campaign would like to declare it has gone over the
top in the delegate race tonight or Wednesday morning, before the
candidate flies back to Massachusetts.
   Dukakis' wife Kitty, who is recuperating from spinal surgery at a
Boston hospital, said she planned to watch the California returns
from her hospital bed. ``I'm excited about tomorrow,'' she said.
   Spokesman Martin Bander of Massachusetts General Hospital said
Mrs. Dukakis could be discharged within a week.
   A Dukakis campaign official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Dukakis would stop in Missouri on his way home Wednesday and
pick up an endorsement from former rival Rep. Richard Gephardt. The
official also said Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who has suspended his
Democratic campaign, would endorse Dukakis in Washington on
Wednesday.
   Throughout his last day of primary campaigning, Dukakis looked
back on his long quest for his party's nomination _ one that began
publicly with a trip in early February 1987 to Osceola, Iowa, a
small town in the state where the first caucuses were held a year
later.
   ``It's by no means the end tomorrow,'' he told a lunchtime crowd
at a San Diego plaza. ``It's the beginning, the beginning of a
Democratic victory in the fall.''
   Dukakis jabbed briefly at his likely Republican opponent for the
fall, George Bush, over the issue of drilling for oil off the
California coast, and spoke of Democratic unity when asked about
Jackson.
   ``If the tables were reversed, and he was on his way to the
nomination and I was the runner up, I'd expect to be deeply involved
... I'd try to bring my people into this. I'd be as much service to
the ticket as I possibly could,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I'm confident he will be that kind of person,'' he added.
   ``We'll be reaching out to supporters of Jesse, and the other
Democratic candidates, as we have already,'' Dukakis said. ``The
response has been terrific. I'm really overwhelmed by the good
feeling, the spirit, the confidence. A sense of victory is in the
air.''
   Dukakis aides sought to minimize the impact of Jackson's remarks
the same day, in which he suggested he would go to the Democratic
National Convention floor to fight over the platform on South Africa
if Dukakis did not alter his position to meet Jackson's. Jackson has
pressed Dukakis to say he was willing to brand South Africa a
terrorist state.
   Dukakis issues director Jim Steinberg said, ``There is a broad
basis for agreement here.
   ``Gov. Dukakis and Rev. Jackson share the same fundamental
commitment on issues relating to South Africa,'' Steinberg said.
``They both want to see an end to apartheid and to take strong and
effective steps both by the United States and by the international
community.''
