<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GraduationParty     06-07 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Graduation Party,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seniors to Attend Night-to-Morning Graduation Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY AMANA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of high school students will
celebrate graduation until the sun comes up at a $35,000 party
Saturday, provided they get their parents' OK and promise to abstain
from drugs and alcohol.
   ``If the alcohol industry is not above bribing them into thinking
they can only have a good time if they're drinking, I'm not above
bribing them into letting them know they can have a good time
without drinking,'' said Anne Barnes, statewide coordinator for
``Project Graduation.''
   Saturday night's party is sponsored by the Wake County PTA
Council, with support from Students Against Drunk Driving, Mothers
Against Drunk Driving and some businesses.
   Teen-agers and local officials held similar affairs at a theme
park outside Charlotte last weekend. Statewide, at least 10
communities are involved in ``Project Graduation,'' officials say.
   Wake County's party, for up to 3,000 students, is scheduled from
8 p.m to 5 a.m. and features three bands, food, a 14-foot-wide
television screen, video games, and a casino. There are prizes of a
new car and trips to Paris, Florida, the Bahamas and across the
continental United States, as well as stereo systems and color
televisions.
   ``They (the students) pledge to stay for the entire time, and not
to use alcohol or drugs,'' said JoAnne Smith, a teacher and
counselor at Broughton High School in Raleigh. ``Without both forms
they don't receive an invitation, and without an invitation, they
don't get in.''
   The hours, she said, are based on drunken driving statistics.
   ``More deaths among people 16 to 20 years old occur in the months
of May and June between the hours of 10 p.m. and 4 a.m.,'' she said.
``Most of these are kids coming back from graduation parties or high
school proms.''
   Organizers have 300 volunteer chaperones, and 40 off-duty police
officers will handle security.
</TEXT>
