<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Beech-Nut-Jail     06-07 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beech-Nut-Jail,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Beech-Nut President Seeks Probation as Alternative to Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for the former president of Beech-Nut
Nutrition Corp., who was convicted of distributing phony apple
juice, want their client to speak to students about his mistakes as
an alternative to prison.
   Niels Hoyvald was found guilty Feb. 17 of 351 counts of violating
the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carries a
possible three-year prison term and a $10,000 fine.
   Hoyvald and a co-defendant, former Beech-Nut Vice President John
Lavery, are to be sentenced Friday in U.S. District Court. Lavery
was found guilty of 429 counts of violating the same act, along with
18 counts of mail fraud and one count of conspiracy.
   Hoyvald's attorneys, Brendan Sullivan Jr. and Barry Simon, said
in a presentencing memorandum that the impact of ethics lessons on
business students ``would be far clearer coming from Niels Hoyvald,
whose career has been shattered because he did not heed it, than it
could ever be coming from a textbook or a professor.''
   Thomas Roche, the executive assistant U.S. attorney who was the
lead prosecutor in the case, said the government's sentencing
recommendations would be made public at the hearing. He declined
comment on the memorandum.
   Hoyvald, president and chief executive officer of Beech-Nut from
April 1981 until shortly before his indictment in November 1986,
said during the trial that he did not know about the distribution of
flavored sugar water as juice until June 25, 1982.
   After that date, Hoyvald said, he relied on the advice of
attorneys in allowing continued distribution of the phony juice.
According to the government, the product contained little or no
apple juice.
   Beech-Nut, based in Fort Washington, Pa., is a subsidiary of
Nestle S.A. of Switzerland.
</TEXT>
