<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Hearing, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0634,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mother To Seek Sanctuary In Church</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with lawyers saying Mrs. Brawley
will seek sanctuary in church and not testify before grand jury;
picks up 8th graf pvs, `No court ... Edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tawana Brawley's mother will seek asylum in a
black church rather than submit to arrest for her refusal to testify
before a grand jury investigating her daughter's disappearance, her
attorneys said today.
   ``Glenda Brawley will not be appearing before a Dutchess County
grand jury tomorrow,'' her attorney, Alton Maddox Jr., told
reporters. ``Glenda Brawley will be seeking relief before a higher
authority, she will be putting her life in God's hands.''
   Mrs. Brawley was sentenced to 30 days in jail Monday for defying
a grand jury subpoena to testify in the case, but state Attorney
General Robert Abrams urged authorities to give her one more chance
to explain her refusal to cooperate to a judge on Wednesday.
   Brawley's family has claimed investigators and state officials
are engaged in a racially motivated cover-up. Mrs. Brawley, 33, was
not in the Dutchess County courtroom when state Supreme Court
Justice Angelo Ingrassia sentenced her to jail and fined her $250.
   Maddox was flanked by attorney C. Vernon Mason and the Rev. Al
Sharpton as he spoke to reporters on the steps of Queens state
Supreme Court, where they attended a hearing in connection with
demonstrations they led in New York City last winter.
   The three men refused to say what church would offer Mrs. Brawley
asylum. But they insisted that the government does not have the
right to violate the sanctuary of a church to arrest her for
contempt of a grand jury.
   Abrams said Monday that unless the family of Tawana Brawley
starts cooperating soon, ``we'll have to start winding down the
investigation.''
   The grand jury will hold its next session Wednesday.
   Tawana Brawley, 16, was found Nov. 28 lying in a plastic bag in
Wappingers Falls, about 10 miles north of here and 95 miles north of
New York City. Her hair was cut, animal excrement was smeared on her
and racial epithets were scrawled on her body. She said she had been
attacked by six white men, including one who flashed a police-like
badge.
   In one of several testy exchanges Monday with Judge Angelo
Ingrassia, Maddox said the hearing was a ``futile exercise'' and
that Mrs. Brawley would not get justice in a system that has been
opressing blacks for hundreds of years.
   Ingrassia said that since the only reasons for the refusal to
testify were political, he had no choice but to hold her in contempt.
   About an hour before the judge's order, Mrs. Brawley left the
courthouse with the Rev. Al Sharpton, a family adviser, and Nation
of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan. She did not appear in the courtroom.
   Following the proceedings, Maddox and roughly 300 supporters who
came by bus from New York City marched down a street. They were
surrounded by a dozen bodyguards with linked arms and did not
respond to reporters' questions.
   During the hearing, Brawley attorneys twice asked Ingrassia to
disqualify himself, saying he had a connection to Gov. Mario Cuomo
and that he had not taken a leadership role in preventing news leaks
about the investigation.
   Ingrassia said he never met Cuomo, and refused to disqualify
himself.
   Brawley attorneys had sought to subpoena several officials,
including Cuomo, but Ingrassia rejected the requests.
</TEXT>
