<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sweden-Palme 1stLd-writethru a0644 06-07 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Palme, 1st Ld-writethru, a0644,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Resigns Over Secret Probe of Palme Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS spelling of Palme in lede; subs 5th graf, `The
resignation...' to fix typo. Picks up 6th graf, `A majority...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Anna-Greta Leijon
resigned Tuesday over a secret investigation she authorized in the
Olof Palme murder case, averting a confidence vote that threatened
to bring down the government.
   Mrs. Leijon, 49, was the highest-ranking woman in Swedish
politics and a ranking figure in the Social Democratic Party.
Critics accused her of overstepping her authority by approving the
secret probe of Prime Minister Palme's assassination, which has
stumped police.
   Palme was shot to death on a downtown street the night of Feb.
28, 1986, while walking home from a movie with his wife. The killer
has not been found and no motive has been established.
   Sweden has offered a reward of 50 million kronor ($8.4 million)
for information leading to the killer.
   The resignation forestalled a no-confidence motion in Parliament
that Ingvar Carlsson, Palme's successor, appeared certain to lose.
It was an embarrassing setback for the Social Democrats, who lead a
minority government, three months before general elections.
   ``A majority in the Riksdag (parliament) has decided that I
should resign, and that leaves me no option,'' Mrs. Leijon told a
news conference.
   She authorized a friend to look into allegations that Iran
ordered the killing because Palme had stopped illegal Swedish arms
sales to Iran.
   Bypassing official investigators, she arranged for publisher Ebbe
Carlsson to reopen the probe of the alleged Iranian connection. He
is not related to the current prime minister.
   No results of his efforts have been disclosed.
   Press reports say his investigation began in April. A letter
written by Mrs. Leijon, for Carlsson to carry to Britain, was dated
in May.
   Police had spent a year looking into the alleged Iranian
connection and the possibility that Kurdish exiles were involved.
Hans Holmer, a close friend of the publisher, was fired as police
commissioner when he refused to give up on the theory.
   The outcry about the unofficial project increased after
disclosures of irregularities _ including that the publisher's
bodyguard smuggled forbidden eavesdropping equipment into Sweden.
The secret operation was financed by a contribution of 2 million
kronor ($343,000) from a banker.
   Prime Minister Carlsson said he will give Mrs. Leijon a prominent
post in the next Cabinet if his party wins the September elections.
   ``She's been a great minister, one of the best, but she has made
one mistake and the opposition could not overlook that,'' he said.
``She is resigning today from the government but she has a lot left
to do in politics.'' He appointed Industry Minister Thage G.
Peterson to act as justice minister until the election.
   Mrs. Leijon was forced to quit when the small Communist Party,
which normally supports Carlsson's minority government, decided
Monday it would join the opposition in a no-confidence vote.
   Center Party leader Olof Johannson said: ``She hasn't followed
the rules of the game in our democracy. That's why she had to go.
It's clear that she broke the code of procedure and went beyond the
constitution.''
   She was the third justice minister to resign under a cloud since
the Social Democrats took office in 1982.
   Sten Wickbom quit in October after a convicted spy escaped while
on an unguarded conjugal furlough from prison. In 1983, Ove Rainer
resigned for allegedly taking advantage of tax loopholes.
   Mrs. Leijon was the first justice minister who was not a lawyer
by training, and the first woman to hold the job. She favored
tougher punishments for criminals and took a strong stand against
terrorism.
</TEXT>
