<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Religion 1stLd-Writethru a0633 06-07 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Religion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Demand Church Condemn Past Praise of Stalin</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Deletes extraneous grafs 19-20. Picks up 21st pvs, `There
was...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious dissidents demanded Tuesday that Russian
Orthodox Church leaders renounce the church's adulation of Josef V.
Stalin, who brutally repressed believers during his rule.
   ``It's the responsibility of the church to announce which side it
is on _ the side of perestroika or the side of Stalinism,'' Father
Gleb Yakunin told reporters in a Moscow apartment.
   ``A person cannot be renewed in his personal life unless he
repents. This is true of the church, too,'' he said.
   Yakunin and other religious activists met with reporters on the
second day of the Russian Orthodox Church local council in Zagorsk,
northeast of Moscow, The council is at the center of celebrations of
the faith's 1,000th anniversary.
   Soviet society is reevaluating Stalin's role in history, and
Soviets from Communist Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev on down have
sharply criticized the purges in which millions of people were
killed or exiled.
   The church has kept silent, and dissidents demanded that the
hierarchy join in the criticism of Stalin.
   Almost 100 believers from around the Soviet Union crowded in a
few small rooms in a Moscow apartment for the beginning of an
unofficial three-day seminar on religious problems in the Soviet
Union.
   Yakunin and other church activists released copies of an appeal
they sent to Patriarch Pimen, the Russian Orthodox Church leader,
asking that the church council condemn a 1949 letter the council
sent to Stalin for his 70th birthday, ``basically canonizing'' the
dictator.
   The church wrote Stalin that it was ``forever grateful to you for
your attentiveness to its needs.''
   Yakunin several months ago called on the ailing 77-year-old Pimen
to resign to allow a younger, more energetic church leader to take
advantage of Gorbachev's reforms.
   Yakunin was barred from performing religious rites from 1966
until last year because of his criticism of church officials, and he
is a former political prisoner. In August, the church gave him a
small parish near Moscow.
   Thousands of priests were exiled or killed during repression
following the Bolshevik revolution in 1917. After Stalin took power,
a law was passed in 1929 sharply restricting church activities. The
church faced its severest repression in the 1930s.
   The dissidents criticized the selection of delegates for the
church council in Zagorsk and the amount of money being spent on the
millennium celebration.
   Ceremonies scheduled at Moscow's Bolshoi Theater threaten to turn
the event in a ``pompous, theatrical action,'' Yakunin said.
   Each day of the weeklong celebration costs about $1.6 million, he
said.
   Another dissident priest, Georgy Edelshtein of Kostroma,
northeast of Moscow, said representatives to the council were chosen
by bishops rather than by meetings of lay people, priests and
deacons.
   Dissidents said priests and believers were kept in the dark about
the selection of nine candidates for sainthood.
   In Rome, a Vatican source said Vatican Secretary of State
Agostino Casaroli, who arrives Wednesday as Pope John Paul II's
representative at millennium celebrations, will carry a letter from
the Polish-born pontiff to Gorbachev.
   There was no information on whether John Paul's message to
Gorbachev would touch on the situation of the Ukrainian Catholic
Church, which is not officially recognized but operates underground
in the western Ukraine.
   The Russian Orthodox Church is opposed to official recognition of
the Ukrainian Catholic Church.
   A top church official said Saturday that recognition of it would
hurt improving relations between Rome and the Russian Orthodox
Church, but that the two sides would discuss the issue in Finland
later this month.
   A priest of the underground church, Yevgeny Genrikhs, told the
news conference that the Russian church has no right to help decide
the issue.
   ``If this is the price the Russian Orthodox Church is willing to
pay, to deprive people of their church, then who needs this kind of
Christian unity?'' he said.
</TEXT>
