<HEAD>Former Sect Member Sentenced for Four Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former professional football player who pleaded
guilty to killing four men, including two drifters whose ears were
cut off, was sentenced today to 22 years in prison.
   Robert Rosier, 31, who had been a member of the Yahweh sect, must
serve at least three years in prison. He could have been sentenced
to up to 27 years in prison.
   Dade Circuit Judge Ellen Morphonious' sentence was agreed upon as
part of Rosier's guilty pleas to four counts of second-degree
murder, said his attorney, Jeffrey Weinkle.
   Security was tight during the sentencing. Rosier, who played
defensive end briefly in 1979 for the St. Louis Cardinals of the
National Football League, wore the robe of the Yahweh sect even
though he was excommunicated in June 1987.
   Members of the virtually all-black sect have claimed to be the
true Jews and said their leader was the Messiah. They now downplay
those ideas, seeking a more moderate image, but the group has been
tainted by allegations of violence.
   Federal authorities have questioned Rosier about the sect's
alleged links to as many as 12 killings. The sect says it has about
8,000 members in Dade County.
   Rosier pleaded guilty to the October 1986 shooting deaths of
Anthony Brown and Rudolph Broussard, both of Opa-locka, and the
September 1986 stabbing deaths of drifters Raymond Kelley and Cecil
Branch.
   Brown and Broussard were killed when sect members tried to evict
them from a crime-ridden apartment building as part of the sect's
effort to fight drug trafficking.
