<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Jackson-veep comment; pick up pvs bgng
``Jackson and...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today he has not decided
whether he would accept the Democratic vice presidential nomination,
if it is offered, but he said ``It is an option my constituency has
earned.''
   On the final primary day of the season, Jackson carefully
outlined his position on the vice presidency in an interview with
ABC-TV.
   Asked whether Dukakis should offer him the vice presidency,
Jackson said, ``If he were to win, extending the invitation to me is
his option.'' He said he did not know whether he would accept, but
then added, ``It is an option my constituency has earned.''
   Jackson and Dukakis met Monday night and again today. Jackson
said they talked about a wide range of concerns, from his call on
Dukakis to term South Africa a terrorist state to his criticisms of
the delegate selection process.
   ``He's sensitive on these matters and we're going to have some
followup meetings, necessarily to discuss matters of platform,
credentials, rules, the convention itself, and beyond that, our
strategy for winning in November,'' Jackson said.
   ``As we increase our own security level, one with the other ...
we accept our responsibility to guide our party to victory.''
   Jackson concluded his primary campaign on a rough note, arriving
late to his half-hour television program Monday night as it was
broadcast in California's major markets. He had fallen behind
schedule in earlier campaign appearances in San Francisco.
   As Jackson raced from the airport, disc jockey Casey Kasem, a
longtime supporter, filled the gap by interviewing Jackson's state
campaign manager, Chris Hammond.
   The show, costing the campaign $150,000, also featured footage of
Jackson speaking to crowds in a video montage with a song about
Jackson and the issues he has addressed in the campaign.
   When Jackson arrived, he and Kasem spent the rest of the program
discussing his campaign issues.
   ``I want to address our youth,'' Jackson said in closing,
``revive their spirit, renew their faith, keep hope alive.... I
offer authentic leadership.''
   Jackson earlier put Dukakis on notice that he will wage a
convention floor fight over the Massachusetts governor's refusal to
say South Africa should be declared a terrorist state.
   ``Mr. Dukakis has proceeded rather cautiously and
conservatively,'' Jackson said in a radio news conference during
which he also criticized Dukakis' leadership.
   ``He has not been willing to declare South Africa a terrorist
state. By any definition of a terrorist state, South Africa
qualifies,'' Jackson said.
   In the strongest terms he has used to date to indicate his
priorities for the party convention in Atlanta, Jackson said, ``If
he will not bend on that matter, we'll simply meet on the floor in
Atlanta.''
   Speaking on the eve of today's primaries in California, New
Jersey, Montana and New Mexico, Jackson indicated he will fight to
bend the convention to his concerns, but will do it within the
structure of the party rules.
   ``It's not just what I want. I represent a constituency,'' he
told a rally in Richmond, Calif. ``What do my constituents want? ...
What renews their faith, what makes their hope alive?'' he said. He
then listed a litany of his campaign issues over such things as
comparable pay for women, affordable housing and health care and
fair prices for farmers.
   Jackson also said he plans to ``use the rules to have fair
rules'' regarding delegate selection procedures that he considers
unfair.
   Jackson has been after Dukakis to join him in calling for
designation of South Africa as a terrorist state because of
Pretoria's backing for the brutal rebels in Mozambique and its
policies of apartheid, press censorship and civil liberties
restrictions.
   Countries on the U.S. list of terrorist nations, such as Libya,
North Korea and Cuba, are subject to trade and political sanctions.
   Jackson said he is ``convinced the ticket will take a strong
position against apartheid and declare South Africa to be a
terrorist state.''
   And Dukakis ``either ... will offer leadership on these basic
issues or be following the wave of a convention taking him out to
sea.''
   Asked how he could support the likely nominee if Dukakis, as
Jackson contends, lacks leadership, Jackson replied, ``It's not a
question of integrity, it's a question of judgement and priorities.
And the governor like all of us will keep expanding and keep
growing.''
   He also said Dukakis' willingness to use nuclear weapons in a
first strike showed ``very bad judgment.''
