<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty In Sale Of Daughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Michal in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of trying to sell his
5-year-old daughter for $100,000 says he hopes his guilty plea in
the case will end a dark episode in his life.
   Joseph Waltman, 24, faces a maximum of five years in prison and a
$75,000 fine on his guilty plea to a charge of endangering the
welfare of a child.
   After entering the plea Monday in Superior Court, Waltman said he
hoped to start a new life, but ``whether I'm going to be left alone
or not by other folks remains to be seen.''
   Waltman, of the southern New Jersey township of Alloway, was
arrested March 19, 1987, in the Giants Stadium parking lot in East
Rutherford when he allegedly tried to sell his daughter, Rachel
Rauser, to the girl's uncle, Gary Stern.
   Waltman had approached Stern previously with the offer, and the
uncle then informed authorities and cooperated in the arrest.
   Stern and his wife, Deborah, of Sunrise, Fla., were granted
custody last December in a three-way custody fight with other
relatives, and they adopted the girl last month.
   Rachel's mother, Michal Rauser, died in a car accident in 1984,
and a judge awarded the girl a $3 million settlement. Rachel will
receive a lump-sum payment when she reaches 18 and monthly payments
of $1,500 for life.
   Waltman, who is free on $10,000 bond, will be sentenced July 13.
Charges of conspiracy and illegally placing a child for adoption
were dropped as part of a plea bargain.
