<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Colombia,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Regrets Cancellation of Colombian Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed regret Tuesday
that the kidnaping of a prominent Colombian opposition leader has
forced cancellation of a planned three-day visit here this week by
President Virgilio Barco.
   ``We understand the reasons behind the cancellation and
sympathize with the Colombian government,'' spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said.
   The cancellation was precipitated by the kidnaping on May 29 of
Alvaro Gomez Hurtado, a former ambassador to Washington who ran
against Barco in the 1986 elections as the Conservative Party
candidate.
   He was kidnapped by armed gunmen as he was leaving church
services.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States deplores ``the violent acts of
individuals and groups in Colombia and continues to hope that
Ambassador Gomez will be returned to his family.''
   Under questioning, Mrs. Oakley disagreed with the suggestion that
the cancellation demonstrates that drug traffickers and terrorists
control Colombia's political life.
   Rather, she said, it reflects Barco's concern over the situation
created by Gomez's kidnapping and does not demonstrate anything ``of
a political nature.''
