<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TireFire     06-07 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tire Fire,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burning Tires Cause Environmental Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENUP, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intake valves were ordered turned off from
this northeastern Kentucky town's water supply source early Tuesday
as sludge from an underground tire fire poured into the Little Sandy
River.
   The blaze, which started Monday and involved possibly 200,000
discarded auto tires in a dump the size of a football field, was
producing a runoff of ``extremely contaminated and toxic oil,''
according to Don Armstrong, a spokesman for the state Division of
Disaster and Emergency Services.
   ``This has rather serious environmental implications because one
tire can produce as much as three gallons of oil,'' Armstrong said.
   The owner of the property, Charles Blythe, and his family were
evacuated, Armstrong said. He said Blythe owned a home, a hobby shop
and a storage unit on the property.
   ``It doesn't appear it (the fire) will be real easy to get put
out, so we're looking at alternatives to decide which way to go,''
said William C. Burger, environmental response coordinator for the
Natural Resources and Environmental Protection Cabinet.
   Burger said two booms were placed across the river, and water
company officials downstream were notified.
   Water intake valves on the river were shut off at 3 a.m.,
according to John Kinner, mayor of the town of 1,400 people.
   Greenup has just 38,000 gallons of reserve water for emergencies,
Armstrong said. Kinner said residents have been asked to conserve,
and tanker trucks may be brought in to supply drinking water.
   Kinner said the valves could be closed for 24 hours.
</TEXT>
