<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SpaceShuttleTest Bjt   06-07 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle Test, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Successful Space Shuttle Launch Test Ends with Mock Emergency
Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three space shuttle astronauts made a
tricky mock emergency landing Tuesday during a comprehensive launch
rehearsal that tested hundreds of changes resulting from the
Challenger disaster.
   The practice for the nation's first shuttle mission in 2{ years,
scheduled Aug. 31, exercised the launch team here and flight
controllers in Houston through the final three hours of a countdown
and the harrowing minutes of a failure requiring split-second
decisions.
   Astronaut Bob Crippen, deputy director of shuttle operations who
will make the final decision on whether a shuttle should be
launched, said the test pointed up a few areas in problem-solving
that needed to be improved, but ``all in all, it was an excellent
exercise.''
   Challenger's seven astronauts died when a faulty booster rocket
caused their spaceship to explode Jan. 28, 1986. With the two
boosters still attached and burning, the crew had no chance to
escape; that is still the case.
   The simulated failure Tuesday of two of the three main engines
occurred seconds after the boosters ``burned out'' normally and were
jettisoned, enabling the three astronauts, operating in a Houston
simulator, to execute an abort maneuver called ``return to launch
site,'' or RTLS.
   ``We think we've lost the left engine,'' astronaut Loren Shriver,
the simulator commander, told mission control slightly more than two
minutes after the pretend liftoff.
   ``Discovery, we confirm the left engine is down. Abort RTLS,''
the control center radioed.
   Shriver and his crew members, James Wetherbee and Franklin
Chang-Diaz, ``flew'' the simulator to an altitude of about 75 miles
and 400 miles out over the Atlantic Ocean to exhaust hundreds of
thousands of gallons of fuel.
   With a second engine now ``locked up and useless,'' the
astronauts pitched around, went through the motions of jettisoning
their huge external fuel tank into the ocean and, battling hydraulic
and other difficulties, glided to the make-believe touchdown on a
runway three miles from the launch pad. Landing occurred 21 minutes
after the abort maneuver began.
   Observing in Houston were commander Rick Hauck and the four
members of his crew who will fly the four-day Discovery mission in
August.
   Because of the Challenger accident, NASA has introduced hundreds
of changes, most aimed at safety, into the launch process. The
changes include new procedures, management responsibilities and
ground and flight hardware and software.
   The simulation Tuesday was the only opportunity to check them out
with the launch-day team before the actual countdown.
   Under the new management structure, one man, Crippen, will make
the final go-no go decision on a shuttle launch. His main adviser is
launch director Bob Sieck. Both have scores of experts to call on.
   Crippen, a veteran of four shuttle missions, and Sieck exercised
their roles Tuesday as intentional electrical, communications and
other problems were built into the count to give controllers
experience in resolving them. A simulated high fuel pressure reading
31 seconds before liftoff would have scrubbed a real launch, but it
was bypassed so the test could continue. The trouble-shooting
delayed the simulated launch 55 minutes.
   The remaining three shuttles have been grounded since the
Challenger accident, with the major roadblock to flight being the
testing of the redesigned booster rocket. Two more full-scale firing
tests are scheduled June 10 and July 26.
   Discovery is undergoing final checks after a major overhaul and
is scheduled to be moved to the launch pad June 27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stld-Writethru a0463 06-07 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st ld-Writethru, a0463,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, Rebels Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs, talks resume. Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``The
Sandinistas...'' SUBS 11th graf pvs ``Alfredo Cesar...'' to remove
redundant full first ference to Cesar. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government and
rebel negotiators resumed talks today, and sources on both sides
said they were close to agreeing on a definitive end to hostilities.
   As the talks began, Contra delegation leader Alfredo Cesar said:
``The Nicaraguan Resistance is here with a political decision to
sign a definite agreement for permanent and lasting peace in
Nicaragua if the government shows its political commitment to make
the democratic reforms in this country to achieve that lasting
peace.''
   A major stumbling block in the fourth round of the negotiations
on achieving a lasting peace is a timetable for disarming the
U.S.-backed rebels, sources said Monday.
   The Sandinistas want the rebels, known as Contras, to disarm by
September. The rebels want to do it by the end of January.
   At the last parley May 26-28, the Sandinistas made concessions on
what the rebels call the democratization of Nicaragua and pledged to
enact political reforms the Contras demand.
   But rebel representatives speaking privately to The Associated
Press said the reforms remained too ill-defined.
   They include freedom of the press, lifting of all political
restrictions, ending the ruling Sandinista National Liberation
Front's control of the army and government, the right to strike and
electoral reforms.
   The government also said it was willing to negotiate reforms
within the framework of its dialogue with the internal opposition.
   The Contras reluctantly agreed at the last negotiating session to
extend a 60-day cease-fire that would have expired May 31. But they
said they would not observe the truce past the end of this week's
talks.
   The government had announced a unilateral 30-day extension of the
truce.
   Since the talks last month, each side has accused the other of
violating the truce. At least one Sandinista army soldier and 10
rebels have been killed, according to the Defense Ministry.
   Cesar said Monday that the rebels were prepared to resume
fighting if the talks failed.
   ``The Nicaraguan Resistance does not want to reinitiate the war,
but if the Sandinista government suspends the conversations, our
forces will be ready,'' Cesar said in San Jose, Costa Rica.
   The Resistance is the Contras' umbrella organization.
   On Monday night, Vice President Sergio Ramirez told reporters an
accord with the rebels was ``a matter of moments because at best
within a month they will not have the capacity to negotiate more.''
   Ramirez also said negotiations only became possible because the
Reagan administration has been unable to win Congressional support
for continued military aid to the rebels.
   Despite their posturing, the government and rebels appear to be
closer to a permanent agreement than at any time since they signed
their historic peace outline on March 23 in the southern border town
of Sopoa.
   The Sandinista government needs to end the war, now in its
seventh year, to reconstruct an economy badly ravaged by the
fighting that has claimed more than 26,000 lives and to enact the
social programs it promised when it came to power in a 1979
revolution.
   At the same time, the Contras are experiencing deep divisions
among their ranks and were cut off from U.S. military assistance at
the end of February.
</TEXT>
