<DOCNO> AP880607-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Anti-GayViolence Bjt   06-07 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Gay Violence, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attacks On Homosexuals Up Sharply as AIDS Makes Gays More Visible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS epidemic has made America's homosexual
community more vulnerable to attack, according to a study released
Tuesday that said reported incidents of anti-gay violence rose 42
percent last year.
   A record 7,008 incidents, ranging from verbal abuse to murder,
were reported in 1987 to the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force,
said Kevin Berrill, director of the group's Anti-Violence Project.
   The statistics were included in the report ``Anti-Gay Violence,
Victimization & Defamation in 1987,'' the third such annual study by
the gay-rights advocacy group.
   ``We are a community under siege,'' Berrill said at a news
conference. ``We are battling AIDS and we're battling violence.''
   AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ has made the gay
community more visible, Berrill said, and ``the downside of lesbian
and gay visibility is once you're more visible, you're more of a
target.''
   Fifteen percent of all incidents reported last year and 5 percent
of the physical assaults involved verbal reference to AIDS by the
perpetrators or were directed against people with the disease, the
study found.
   As in 1986, nearly two-thirds of the local groups reporting
anti-gay incidents last year believed that ``fear and hatred
associated with AIDS has fostered anti-gay violence in their
communities,'' according to the report.
   The overall statistics represented a small percentage of the
actual number of anti-gay incidents occurring last year, Berrill
said.
   ``Gay and lesbian victims are probably the least likely to report
of any hate crime victims,'' he said. ``Gay and lesbian people, by
reporting crimes against them to the police, risk losing their jobs,
their homes, and in some cases children.''
   Nevertheless, ``available data clearly demonstrate that the
problem continues to be severe,'' he said.
   Berrill called for federal and state legislation aimed at curbing
anti-gay violence and better education of the public.
   Another reason for the increase in incidents reported may have
been that the task force received more complete data than in the
prior studies, Berrill noted. The 7,008 incidents in 1987 were
reported by 64 groups in 32 states and the District of Columbia,
compared with 4,946 incidents from 41 groups in 27 states a year
earlier.
   The report was compiled by sending one-page questionnaires to
more than 150 groups in all 50 states requesting any available local
data on harassment or violence that occurred in 1987. Groups were
chosen based on the likelihood of knowledge about local incidents.
   Among those groups documenting greater violence last year were
San Francisco's Community United Against Violence, a gay
victim-assistance agency, which saw 11 percent more violence victims
in 1987 than in 1986. The New York City Gay and Lesbian
Anti-Violence Project said it served 14 percent more clients in
1987, and the Philadelphia Lesbian and Gay Task Force reported a 39
percent increase in violent incidents.
   The greatest increases came in acts of verbal harassment and
threats of violence, according to the report.
   ``Not only were there 1,990 more such incidents reported in 1987
than the previous year, but harassment and threats also constituted
a greater percentage of 1987's total (78 percent of all episodes in
1987 as compared to 70 percent in 1986),'' it said.
   Acts of vandalism also increased: 338 in 1987, up from 191 in
1986.
   While 835 physical assaults were reported in 1987, compared with
732 in 1986, they represented a slightly smaller percentage of total
incidents: 12 percent in 1987, down from 15 percent in 1986.
   Reports of police-related incidents declined from 410 to 217.
Other declines were in reports of arson, bombings, bomb threats and
homicides.
   North Carolina had more reported incidents than any other state _
a total of 1,985, of which 1,913 were harassment or threats, the
report found. Berrill attributed this to the fact that organized
hate groups are active in the state.
   New York state led all others in the number of anti-gay
homicides, the report found. Of a total of 408 incidents reported in
New York, 20 were homicides. Sixty-four murders were reported
nationwide.
   The study also highlighted federal, state and local initiatives
to combat such violence, including passage of a hate crimes
statistics bill by the House last month. The bill would require
federal collection of statistics on crimes motivated by race,
religion, sexual orientation or ethnicity.
   A companion bill has been introduced in the Senate by Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
