<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pope-US     06-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-US,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Creates New Diocese in Knoxville</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Tuesday established
a new Roman Catholic Diocese of Knoxville and named an Irish-born
priest as its first bishop.
   The diocese, comprised largely of rural counties, will include
Chattanooga, Johnson City and Kingsport with about 36,000 Catholics,
said Gary Honnert, director of communications for the Memphis
Diocese.
   The Vatican said the new bishopric was created from territory
taken from the Diocese of Nashville.
   Appointed bishop was the Rev. Anthony O'Connell, 50, a native of
Lisheen, County Clare, who came to the United States 30 years ago,
the Vatican said. He has been rector of St. Thomas Seminary in
Jefferson City, Mo.
   In a news conference Tuesday in Knoxville, O'Connell said the new
diocese is an answer to the prayers of Catholics in East Tennessee.
   ``I rejoice with the faithful of East Tennessee who have longed
for, prayed for and worked hard for this happy event _ the
establishment of their own diocese,'' he said. ``I know how grateful
they must feel to John Paul for his pastoral care in responding to
their pleas.''
   Honnert said the diocese in Nashville was established in 1837,
and was the state's only Roman Catholic diocese until 1971, when
Pope Paul VI established the diocese in Memphis. There are about
130,000 Roman Catholics in Tennessee.
   Bishop James D. Niedergeses of Nashville called the new diocese a
``clear witness to the growth of Catholicism in Tennessee.''
</TEXT>
