<DOCNO> AP880607-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp 1stAdd a0677 06-07 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp, 1st Add, a0677,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: with 985.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The final round of the primary season was considerably less than
an all-out struggle.
   Dukakis spent less than $250,000 on television in California and
nothing on TV advertising in New Jersey.
   Jackson's campaign said it was spending $700,000 in California,
but even that was a relative pittance in the state with the most
delegates of all.
   Bush, trying to avoid overshooting federal spending limitations,
had no commercials and little organizational effort. His California
office had one paid staff member and a handful of telephone lines.
   All this was in astonishing contrast to the primaries and
caucuses at the beginning of the campaign season, when Bush,
Dukakis, Jackson and their rivals of long ago lavished time and
money on states such as Iowa and New Hampshire.
   It was a marked contrast, as well, to Republican and Democratic
campaigns of the past, when the outcome of nominating struggles hung
in the balance to be tipped one way or another by the voters of
California or New Jersey.
   And even as one primary season was ending, Congress was debating
whether to make changes in the next one. A Senate committee heard
testimony during the day on legislation to establish a regional
primary system, with the states clustered into half a dozen
geographical categories.
   Thus ended a primary season that began with the clamor of more
than a dozen candidates but sorted out quickly.
   That was true particularly on the Republican side, where Bush
made short work of his five rivals even though he was very nearly an
early campaign casualty.
   The vice president finished third in the lead-off Iowa caucuses
behind Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and former television evangelist Pat
Robertson.
   But as his political obituaries were being prepared, Bush scored
a stunning victory in the New Hampshire primary followed by a solid
win in South Carolina. He parlayed these successes into a 16-state
sweep of Super Tuesday primaries on March 8. From then, it was a
casual stroll to clinching the Republican nomination.
   Ironically, just as he conquered the Republican field, Bush was
having trouble in the national polls. His standing plummeted as the
Reagan administration's controversies mounted, and in the final
weeks of primary campaigning, Bush began setting himself apart from
the president on dealings with Panama's Manuel Noriega and off-shore
oil drilling.
   He said more differences with the president would emerge. ``We'll
probably be dragged into more of these things rather than less, but
I will try to keep it that I don't go out and do something to tear
down or be negative about this president. It may not always be that
easy,'' he said.
   The Democratic nominating campaign was more turbulent, but even
so, it was essentially settled far earlier than seemed possible last
winter.
   With front-runner Gary Hart briefly sidelined by his Donna Rice
crisis, Dukakis was lumped with his rivals as one of the ``seven
dwarfs.'' The pack, even when Hart re-entered, was seemingly
overshadowed by speculation of a brokered national convention or a
draft candidate such as New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   Dukakis' route to the nomination mirrored the man _ steady and
methodical. He finished third in Iowa, as did Bush, then rebounded
to capture a back-yard victory in New Hampshire.
   His Super Tuesday was considerably less so than the vice
president's, but super enough. Dukakis managed to pull out Southern
victories in Florida and Texas with less than half the vote. He won
at home in New England and in Maryland the same day.
   But he stumbled the next time out, finishing third in the
Illinois primary and was embarrassed a few days later when Jackson
trounced him in the Michigan caucuses. That was the end of his
primary disappointments.
   He then began a springtime surge through the primaries that
forced all his rivals but Jackson from the field _ and left little
or no doubt that he would be the nominee.
   Leading to the final week of the campaign, he won nine of the
last 10 primaries, often by landslide margins over his sole
remaining rival, and gradually built his delegate totals toward the
nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
