<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Starvation     06-07 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Starvation,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Starvation Kills Almost 1,000 in Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost 1,000 people have died of
starvation in a parched southern town that hasn't received relief
food for about a year, and most of the deaths occurred in recent
weeks, a Sudanese official said Tuesday.
   Sultan Pio Tem, commissioner of the eastern part of Bahr
el-Ghazal region, told reporters the victims were residents of
Aweil, northwest of the regional capital Wau. He said the victims
also included people forced into the town by fierce fighting in the
5-year-old civil war.
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army holds 90 percent of the
countryside in the south. The government retains control of the
large towns and cities, and many peasants have fled to them seeking
army protection.
   Tem said the latest telegram he received from Aweil reported 786
people had died from hunger and hunger-related diseases from May 24
to June 1.
   He said 210 others perished earlier from the same causes and that
starvation deaths continue to occur there daily. He did not say how
many were dying each day.
   Tem was in Khartoum seeking relief food for the town. He said he
was to meet with Darios Beshir, Bahr el-Ghazal's regional govenor.
Tem said relief supplies had not reached Aweil since a consignment
of rice and edible oil arrived by train a year ago.
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi has not replied to an appeal for
food and medicine addressed to the government and to Western relief
organizations, Tem said, adding he was trying to meet with el-Mahdi
to urge him to declare Aweil a hunger area.
   El-Mahdi has announced that the United Nations is sponsoring a
program to transport relief food to the south, but no date has been
set for the operation.
   The SPLA took up arms against the government in 1983 to demand
more autonomy and administrative and economic reforms. The years of
fighting have corresponded with one of the worst famines in Sudan in
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Mondale-Campaigns     06-07 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mondale-Campaigns,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mondale Urges Campaign Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale on Tuesday
urged Congress to order a system of regional presidential primaries
to replace a hodgepodge that ``cries out for reform.''
   Mondale, who won the Democratic presidential nomination in 1984
but lost the general election to President Reagan, testified in
support of a bill that would require such regional primaries, with
the dates to be decided by the Federal Election Commission.
   It would also outlaw inter-party crossover voting in primaries.
   The measure is sponsored by Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., though he
told the Senate Committee on Rules and Administration that the bill
``is not my brainchild.'' He noted that similar legislation was
introduced by then-Sen. Mondale of Minnesota in 1974.
   Mondale, testifying on the final day of the 1988 campaign season,
said the present nominating system ``is the hodgepodge result of a
decades-long accretion of rules and amendments by the conventions
and national committees of the two political parties.''
   He said primaries in widely scattered parts of the nation on the
same day, such as Tuesday's schedule of contests in New Jersey,
California, Montana and New Mexico, make it impossible for
candidates to address the issues and meet the voters.
   He urged the panel to support the bill, which would allow states
to decide on a caucus or primary form of election but would require
them to hold the event on a specific date, based on their region.
   The six regional primaries, according to the bill, would begin on
the last Tuesday in March and end on the second Tuesday in June. The
FEC would decide the order, by lots, each year.
   Mondale, drawing on his own experience, also criticized the
influence of Iowa and New Hampshire, which hold the
first-in-the-nation caucus and primary, respectively.
   In comments to reporters after his testimony, he said, ``I lived
in New Hampshire for three years virtually. I could have gotten
elected mayor in most of those towns, the same in Iowa.''
   ``My theory is we ought to rotate those states so you do that in
other states. We never had a Southern state, a Western state. If
we're going to do that, let's circulate it.''
   Mondale said the present system is ``not all bad by any means,''
but ``nevertheless cries out for reform.'' He called on Congress to
act now rather than drop the issue until the next
presidential-election year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimarySignals Bjt   06-07 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Signals, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Struggles to Define Race; Dukakis Benefits From Long Primary
Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential primary season was kind to
Democrat Michael Dukakis but disquieting to Republican George Bush,
who struggles to define the race in his terms despite clinching the
nomination two months ago.
   The primary election results and the current polls could be
likened to the electorate's first impressions of the candidates,
impressions likely to change as they get to know the contenders
better in the fall.
   Right now, Dukakis is riding a wave of public desire for change.
After nearly eight years of Ronald Reagan, the public may be looking
for something different, a change of direction.
   Democratic and Republican pollsters alike report Americans are
uneasy with the economy and concerned that the country is headed in
the wrong direction.
   Bush is suffering from an inability to define the race in his
terms. Peace and prosperity is a theme that has worked well for
Republicans in the past, but, so far, Bush hasn't been able to
convince voters that it applies today.
   ``I can't wait for this primary season to end,'' the vice
president tells rallies.
   From the Bush viewpoint, Dukakis has had the best of all worlds
the past three months.
   The contest for the Republican presidential nomination
effectively ended on March 8, Super Tuesday, when Bush swept 16
primaries and sent Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas staggering back to the
Midwest in search of a miracle. Any lingering doubts about the
outcome ended a week later with another Bush landslide in Illinois;
he mathematically locked up the nomination in Pennsylvania on April
26.
   The GOP race was over, a footnote to news accounts of the
struggle among the Democrats.
   Dukakis ran poorly in Illinois where the big Democratic winners
were two home state favorites, Sen. Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson.
   When the scene shifted to Michigan, things looked even worse for
the Massachusetts governor. He was beaten again, this time by
Jackson.
   ``Where's Mario?'' came the cry from Democrats nervously looking
for a winner. But Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York preferred the role of
kibitzer to that of candidate.
   The nervousness among Democrats proved unfounded. When the
contest came down to a choice between Dukakis and Jackson, the
Massachusetts governor ran off with a string of victories.
   Nearly every Wednesday morning for two months, Americans learned
of yet another Dukakis victory. As one Republican strategist put it:
``With every victory he grew another inch.''
   The Bush campaign chafed under another reality of the Democratic
race: In a Dukakis-Jackson contest, the Massachusetts governor came
off as the moderate.
   Bush lamented that one national poll found two-thirds of the
respondents considered Dukakis more conservative than the vice
president.
   ``There's something weird about that,'' said Bush.
   There also is the prospect that things will get worse for Bush
before they get better.
   The Democratic convention is in July, and if Dukakis succeeds in
resolving some potential pitfalls and presents a festival of unity
for four days on national television, he is almost certain to get
another boost in the polls.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater concedes that the vice
president could be trailing by as much as 20 points in surveys
before the Republican convention in August.
   But before Dukakis can send out invitations to his inauguration,
he has some problems to resolve.
   The biggest one is Jackson.
   The former civil rights leader has a hold on the Democratic
Party's most loyal constituency and many of his followers think
Jackson must be offered the vice presidential nomination _ an offer
Dukakis isn't likely to make unless he is certain it would be turned
down.
   Jackson also is threatening to wage convention fights for
platform planks he favors.
   There are no foreseeable conflicts for the GOP convention,
allowing Bush to gain maximum benefits from the GOP coronation.
   And as Bush reads the current polls showing him trailing Dukakis,
he also can take comfort in the fact that when voters start focusing
on presidential campaigns in the fall, the race inevitably tightens,
often dramatically.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
