<1ST_LINE>r p AM-KittyDukakis     06-07 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kitty Dukakis,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis to Leave Hospital Less than a Week After Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis plans to leave Massachusetts General
Hospital on Thursday, less than a week after undergoing neck surgery
to eliminate a condition that could have caused paralysis.
   The wife of Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis
said Tuesday in a telephone interview that doctors at the hospital
told her she could leave later this week.
   ``My neck is fine. I'm walking without help. I have just a little
pain in my hip,'' Mrs. Dukakis said. Her hip pain is the result of
Friday's surgery in which doctors removed two small bone fragments
and used them to replace two herniated discs in her neck.
   Mrs. Dukakis was alert and sitting up in bed, but sounded
slightly hoarse in the interview.
   She said she longed to be with her husband for Tuesday's
California primary, the last event in the long pre-convention
season. ``I wish I was somewhere else,'' she said shortly after
speaking to her husband at 6:30 a.m., California time. ``He sounded
a little weary.''
   In the meantime, Mrs. Dukakis sorted through piles of gifts and
cards and walked the hallways of the hospital, visiting other
patients.
   She said she received ``lots of candy, fruit and flowers'' from
friends, relatives and some of her husband's Democratic rivals, but
nothing, so far, from President Reagan or the certain Republican
nominee, Vice President George Bush.
   Doctors have prescribed rest at home for Mrs. Dukakis when she
leaves the hospital and a curtailed campaign schedule until the
Democratic National Convention, which opens July 18 in Atlanta.
   Dr. Nicholas T. Zervas, chief of neurology at the hospital, told
Mrs. Dukakis that she would have to wear a neck brace for, at most,
eight weeks _ a period that could include the convention.
   ``If I have to, big deal,'' she said of the possibility of
joining her husband at the podium in a brace.
   Doctors plan to take X-rays next month to make sure her neck is
healing properly, she said.
   Zervas, a longtime family friend, led a team of surgeons in the
operation on the 51-year-old Mrs. Dukakis. Doctors said that if the
ailment had gone undetected much longer, she faced the risk of
paralysis.
   Mrs. Dukakis said she began to feel the warnings signs that
something was wrong a month before she was diagnosed last week.
   ``I didn't have much time to think about it,'' she said. ``One
tends to slough things off in a campaign atmosphere.''
   Early in Dukakis' presidential campaign, Mrs. Dukakis
acknowledged that she had kicked an addiction to diet pills that had
lasted more than two decades. She said Tuesday she is trying to
limit the number of pain killers she takes to help her through her
recovery.
</TEXT>
