<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Long-TermCare     06-07 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Long-Term Care,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepper Rallies His Forces for Floor Fight on Long-Term Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Claude Pepper marshaled an array of
influential lawmakers Tuesday as he prepared for a do-or-die effort
in the House to pass a costly new home health care program.
   Pepper's plan, scheduled for floor action Wednesday, would expand
Medicare to include long-term home care benefits for anyone of any
age who is chronically ill or can't perform tasks of daily living.
   With opponents mobilizing to prevent a vote on the bill, Pepper
rallied his own forces Tuesday at a news conference: Sens. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee; Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., the Senate sponsor of the bill;
and Reps. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who holds the No. 4 leadership
position in the House; and Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce health subcommittee.
   ``We have a total vacuum'' when it comes to long-term care,''
Pepper, D-Fla., said. ``A million people a year become destitute
trying to pay for catastrophic care.''
   The Pepper bill has provoked criticism on several counts, among
them its high cost, its lack of a nursing home component and the
unorthodox manner in which it bypassed committee scrutiny and sped
to the House floor.
   ``We should not allow the rules of the House to be manipulated to
satisfy the popular issue of the moment,'' House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said Tuesday in a
letter to his colleagues. He said the committee system ``protects
members from being forced to vote on popular-appearing proposals
that may ultimately prove to be embarrassing.''
   The Pepper bill is putting House members, particularly Democrats,
in a bind because withiout their support there is no chance Congress
will pass the bill before adjourning this year.
   There is overwhelming public sentiment in favor of a long-term
care program. There also is an election in six months, and the
87-year-old Pepper, who is popular with elderly voters, has made
campaign appearances on behalf of many lawmakers in the past.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates the home care program
would cost nearly $28 billion over five years. It would be paid for
by imposing the Medicare payroll tax on income above $45,000, which
is currently exempt.
   Supporters of the plan also backed a new catastrophic care
benefit bill to help the elderly cope with acute illness. That
Medicare expansion, more than a year in the making, has passed the
House and is expected to pass the Senate this week.
   But Waxman called that measure ``only half the roof that people
need to shield them from health care catastrophes. ... I always feel
guilty calling this other bill the catastrophic bill.''
   Pepper initially tried to attach his plan to the catastrophic
bill, but withdrew it when lawmakers said it would sink that
legislation. In return, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, agreed to
let Pepper have a separate floor vote on his plan.
   Pepper, chairman of the rules committee that schedules floor
action, scheduled his own bill last year, effectively bypassing
Rostenkowski's committee and the Energy and Commerce Committee
headed by John Dingell, D-Mich., which ordinarily would have
considered the Pepper bill.
   Rostenkowski complained in his ``Dear Colleague'' letter that the
bill was brought to the floor via ``an extremely unusual and
troubling procedure.''
   He also said the agencies necessary to administer the Pepper plan
do not exist and ``history has demonstrated that such a big program
cannot be put in place quickly without encouraging inept or
fraudulent management.'' And he said CBO estimates show the program
would face an annual deficit within five years.
   Pepper dismissed the notion that he was abusing the committee
process, saying what happened with his bill was unique and would not
become routine.
   ``The rules committee is not going to run rampant over anybody,''
Pepper said Tuesday. ``All they want to do is kill the bill and use
the money for something else.''
   In a ``Dear Colleague'' letter of their own, dated June 8, Pepper
and his co-sponsor, Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., called cost and
procedure issues ``bogus'' reasons to oppose the bill.
   They said the bill contains a cap on costs and does not violate
any procedural rules of the House.
   They also said outside opposition groups such as the insurance
industry would oppose any long-term care bill because ``they serve
their own narrow self-interest, not the American people's interest.''
</TEXT>
