<2ND_LINE>AM-Math Goof, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Math Testers Sometimes Don't Get Their Own Answers Straight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Math Assessment Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: The correct, to CORRECT spelling of
`foreword'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Question: Is 26.9 percent ``fully a third''?
   The correct answer is no, but 26.9 percent is described as
equaling a third in a foreword to the federal mathematics study
released Tuesday by the National Assessment of Educational Progress.
   Gregory Anrig, president of the Educational Testing Service,
which runs the government-sponsored testing program, wrote in a
preface that, ``Fully a third of our 13-year-olds haven't mastered
skills universally taught in elementary school.''
   The executive summary of the report also said it was ``alarming
that one-third of these students'' didn't score 250 on the 500-point
test, a level indicating they can perform basic operations and begin
to solve problems.
   But a chart accompanying the test indicated that in 1986, 73.1
percent of the 13-year-olds actually reached that level, up from
64.9 percent in 1978.
   The full text of the report, ``The Mathematics Report Card: Are
We Measuring Up,'' referring to the same statistics, says: ``It is
alarming that one-quarter of the seventh and eighth graders _
amounting to more than three-quarters of a million students _ may
not possess the skills ... necessary to perform many everyday
tasks.''
   Kent Ashworth, a spokesman for the National Assessment,
acknowledged that ``fully a third'' was a mistake, and expressed
surprise that it had gotten past the report's proofreaders.
</TEXT>
