<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Medical Labs,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislation Seeks Tighter Regulation of Medical Labs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical testing labs would come under strict
federal regulation under a bill introduced Tuesday by Sens. Carl
Levin, D-Mich., and William Cohen, R-Maine.
   The bill would affect the 80,000 to 100,000 medical laboratories
not now under federal regulation. Most are in doctors' offices,
Levin said.
   ``Our legislation changes the focus of lab testing to emphasize
quality over quantity,'' said Levin. ``That difference can have
life-or-death consequences.''
   The legislation would establish maximum workload limits for lab
workers who examine Pap smears, strengthen federal enforcement
authority over labs and set standards for the laboratories.
   ``From the patient's point of view, there should be just as much
assurance that tests conducted in a doctor's office are as
accurate'' as those conducted in a hospital or commercial lab, Levin
said.
</TEXT>
