<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Islam     06-07 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Islam,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Declares Islam State Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Parliament passed a constitutional
amendment Tuesday making Islam the state religion. Thousands of
opponents took to the streets in protest, blocking traffic and
damaging vehicles.
   The 300-member Parliament, dominated by President Hussain
Muhammad Ershad's Jatiya Party, passed the controversial bill 254-0.
Fifteen members of minor opposition parties walked out before the
vote. Two independents joined the Jatiya Party to enact the bill,
which was proposed May 11.
   The amendment makes an Islamic republic out of this once-secular
state created after a 1971 war of independence from Pakistan.
   Shortly after the legislation was passed, several thousand
members of 21 non-voting opposition groups streamed into the
streets. These parties have no representatives in Parliament because
they boycotted March elections in which Ershad won a 252-seat
parliamentary majority.
   Witnesses said the mobs stopped traffic at several intersections
in downtown Dhaka and damaged seven state-run buses and a police
jeep.
   Riot police were on duty, but no clashes were reported.
   The proposed bill drew especially strong criticism from women's
groups, opposition parties and minority religions in a country whose
105 million people are 85 percent Moslem. There are an estimated
250,000 Christians in Bangladesh, as well as Hindu and Buddhist
minorities.
   The bill amends the Bangladesh Constitution to insert the
sentence: ``The religion of the republic is Islam, but other
religions may be practiced in peace and harmony.'' The government
says the bill does not change the legal system to one that would
follow the Koran, the Moslem holy book.
   Women's rights groups, however, fear that Moslem fundamentalists
may use the amendment to pressure the state to pass more rigid laws
following Islamic traditions, such as those requiring women to hide
their faces behind veils.
   But observers say there is little possibility that the amendment
would pull Bangladesh into a social system resembling the Islamic
fundamentalism of Iran.
   About 3,000 demonstrators _ including teachers, journalists and
doctors _ marched through the streets of Dhaka on Saturday to
protest the change, shouting anti-government slogans.
   Christian leaders had appealed to Ershad to withdraw the
legislation.
   Among those who signed the statement was the Rev. Michael
Rozario, the Roman Catholic archibishop of Dhaka, and
representatives of other Christian denominations.
   Before the legislation was passed, Prime Minister Maudud Ahmed
assured minority groups that they should not fear the amendment and
told the Parliament that the bill was ``to free Islam from the hands
of fundamentalists and the traders of religion.''
   But political analysts in Dhaka have said they believe Ershad's
main reason for launching Islam as the official religion was to woo
Islamic fundamentalists, some of whom are campaigning against his
regime for being too lax in supporting Moslem traditions.
   Ershad, a former army general, came to power in a bloodless coup
in March 1982 and was elected president in October 1986. The major
opposition groups contend the elections were rigged.
   They boycotted the March elections, saying they also would be
rigged, and vowed not to participate in elections until Ershad
leaves office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
