<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugDispute     06-07 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Dispute,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CLU To Defend Child's Right To Be Educated Without Medication</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Hampshire Civil Liberties Union said
Tuesday it will help with an appeal on behalf of a 9-year-old boy
and his parents, who refuse to medicate him to control his
hyperactivity in school.
   The group agreed to assist Casey Jesson's lawyer in appealing a
state hearing officer's decision that the boy must take Ritalin or
an alternative drug to calm hyperactive children if he continues to
attend regular public school classes next year.
   School officials in Derry said Casey was manageable on Ritalin
and that without it he has temper tantrums and is disruptive.
   His parents, Valerie and Michael, said Ritalin made Casey act
like a drug addict with facial twitches, little appetite and
insomnia. They stopped giving him Ritalin in April 1987 after he
spent 18 months on the drug.
   The appeal likely will be filed in federal court, where precedent
exists for such matters, Claire Ebel, the CLU's executive director,
said Tuesday.
   The first line of defense will be to assert Casey's
constitutional right to privacy when medical treatment is involved,
she said.
   ``For any government agency, such as the state Education
Department, to violate that privacy, there must exist a compelling
state interest and we don't believe that has been proven,'' she said.
   The group's lawyers also believe Casey's rights as an
educationally handicapped child have been violated, Ebel said.
   Hearing officer Eric Falkenham ruled last month that returning
Casey to class without medication would harm his education and that
of his classmates.
   Falkehham also said the Jessons would have to pay to have Casey
placed in a more restrictive, specialized class if they refuse to
medicate him.
   In an agreement between the state and Casey's parents, he is
being tutored until the school year ends later this month.
</TEXT>
