<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GeorgiaDrought     06-07 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia Drought,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Drying Up Water Supplies, Patience Of Residents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought that has gripped north Georgia is
causing a new kind of battle among lawn-conscious suburbanites, some
of whom are reporting their neighbors for ignoring tight
restrictions on outdoor water use.
   Fulton County's Public Works Department has been swamped with
water calls, said operator Evelyn Smith, who estimated that 90
percent of the department's recent calls have been about outdoor
watering.
   ``They say, `Their lawn's so pretty and green, how come they get
to water and I don't,''' she said.
   ``They're calling in on their neighbors, basically,'' said Cobb
County Police radio operator Nina Reber.
   ``Some are pretty mad,'' said Gus Monroe, deputy director of
DeKalb County's Water Department. ``Some just want to complain. Lots
are just teed off at their neighbors.''
   Gwinnett County Water Department Director Gary Beaufait said his
department received nearly 230 calls over the weekend. ``When a
resident sees somebody else watering, I would imagine he would be
irritated,'' Beaufait said.
   Almost every government in the Atlanta area has restrictions on
when lawns can be watered and cars washed.
   The city of Roswell, in northern Fulton County, announced that it
would ban outdoor watering 24 hours a day beginning at midnight
Tuesday.
   Atlanta has banned outdoor watering from 7 a.m. to 11 a.m. since
November, and its water bureau is recommending that residents use
water outdoors on odd or even days, depending on their address.
   Despite the bans, faucets in about 1,000 north Fulton County
homes went dry from about 9 p.m. Monday until 1 a.m. Tuesday, said
county water supervisor Hershel Barrett. He said the area, which
bans outdoor watering from noon until 9 p.m., ran out of water
because many residents ``just dragged out the water hoses and went
to town'' when the ban expired Monday night.
   ``We were, for all practical purposes, out of water last night,''
he said Tuesday.
   About 200 homes in southern Forsyth County, where water was
purchased from Fulton County, also lost water for three to four
hours Monday night, said Forsyth water department director Tom Heard.
   Georgia state climatologist Gayther Plummer said there have been
only 210 inches of rain in most parts of north Georgia in the last
five years. The region averages 50 inches of rainfall per year, or
250 inches in five years.
   Lake Lanier, the metropolitan area's primary water source, was at
1,062.7 feet above sea level Tuesday, 10 feet above its record low
of 1,052.7 feet, set Dec. 24, 1981.
   ``All indications are that this is going to be a very critical
drought in the northern part of the state,'' said David Word, chief
of water resource management for the Georgia Department of Natural
Resources. ``It is going to be worse than '86.''
   However, Word said the driest weather this year is confined to
north Georgia, unlike the statewide drought in 1986.
   The water situation in the northeast Georgia town of Clayton _
which was without water for 36 hours during the summer of 1986 _
will be critical if the town doesn't receive significant rainfall
soon, Mayor Tom Ramey said Tuesday.
   But Ramey said the experience of running out of water taught
residents the importance of conservation.
   ``It was a lesson well learned, because when they turned that tap
on and nothing came out they knew we weren't fooling,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
