<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NMPrimary     06-07 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NM Primary,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Selecting Candidate To Face Bingaman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 10 p.m. EDT; material below the dash will
stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Mexico Republicans chose from among
four candidates Tuesday to try to unseat first-term Democratic Sen.
Jeff Bingaman.
   State Sens. Bill Valentine and Joe Carraro, party activist Corky
Morris and former U.S. Interior Department official Rick Montoya
each argued that he was the right candidate to mount a successful
challenge to the man Republicans believe is too liberal for New
Mexico.
   In the presidential primary, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
was favored over Jesse Jackson in the race for 24 Democratic
delegates. Vice President George Bush was unopposed for 26
Republican delegates.
   In the state's 1st Congressional District, Republican Rep. Manuel
Lujan Jr. was retiring after 20 years. Three Republicans sought the
nomination, including Lujan's younger brother Edward, the former
state GOP chairman. Eight Democrats sought their party's nomination,
including former state Land Commissioner Jim Baca.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bingaman, 44, was unopposed in the Democratic primary, but he
said in January when he announced for re-election that as one of
only two first-term Democrats running this year _ the other is New
Jersey Sen. Frank Lautenberg _ he expected his race to be targeted
by the national Republican Party.
   A former New Mexico attorney general, Bingaman was elected to the
Senate in 1982 when he defeated first-term Republican Sen. Harrison
``Jack'' Schmitt, a former astronaut.
   Valentine, 44, the first Republican to announce his candidacy,
stressed his track record of 12 years in the state Senate.
   Carraro, 43, was the last to jump into the race, waiting until
early this year.
   Morris, 52, stressed his experience in business and as a former
Bernalillo County commissioner and cited his work as state chairman
of the Reagan-Bush campaign in 1984.
   Montoya, 41, said he was the only Republican who knew the ropes
in Washington. He left the Reagan administration as assistant
secretary of interior for terriorities and international affairs to
seek elective office.
   A poll published in the Albuquerque Journal on Sunday showed
Valentine the choice of 29.5 percent, with 38.9 percent undecided.
</TEXT>
