<1ST_LINE>d a AM-Sequoyah     06-07 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sequoyah,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sequoyah Unit 2 Shuts Down Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Unit 2 reactor at Sequoyah Nuclear
Plant automatically shut down Monday afternoon for the third time
since it was restarted last month, said a Tennessee Valley Authority
official.
   The reason for the 2:15 p.m. EDT shutdown was not immediately
known, said Janice Brady, a spokeswoman for Plant Manager Steve
Smith.
   It occurred less than a week after the reactor reached 100
percent power for the first time since it was restarted following a
33-month shutdown.
   TVA brought Unit 2 back on line May 13, the agency's first
reactor to be restarted since its nuclear system was shut down in
August 1985 to correct safety and management problems.
   Although two automatic shutdowns delayed the restart process,
Unit 2 at the plant outside Chattanooga reached full generating
capacity May 31.
   Sequoyah Unit 2 began commercial operation in June 1982; the
following year, it set a TVA record by operating 195 consecutive
days without a shutdown. That record was later broken by a 197-day
streak by Unit 1 in 1984 and 1985.
   TVA tentatively plans to restart Sequoyah Unit 1 in August or
September, with Unit 2 at the three-reactor Browns Ferry Nuclear
Plant near Athens, Ala., to follow by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
