<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-07 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worshipers at Trinity Episcopal Cathedral in
search of the biblical land of milk and honey need only look to the
rafters.
   At least that's where the honey _ along with an estimated 50,000
bees _ is hiding.
   The Rev. John Fricke said the bees took up residence in the
cathedral's rain gutters and under the roof about 10 years ago. They
never caused a problem, he said, except for the occasional dripping
of honey down an inside pillar.
   But when a contractor said he wouldn't do some needed painting
because of the bees, Fricke found himself a beekeeper.
   Working on a 40-foot scaffolding Monday, Roger Miller of Bellevue
estimated there is a colony of 50,000 bees and the honeycomb
contains as much as 1,000 pounds of honey.
   The church had hoped to save the honeycomb and bees, Miller said,
but the large size and location, extending under the roof, made it
impossible.
   A scraper pole will be used to break the honeycomb into pieces,
remove it and collect the honey. The worker bees will be killed
using aerosol spray after Miller locates and removes the queen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inside the large green and white striped
tent, an orange-haired clown with a bulbous nose and a British
accent told his audience how he keeps the kiddies laughing at
birthday parties back home.
   Kooky, alias Andrew Stevens of Devizes, England, is one of four
clown instructors from England at the clown camp being held this
week and next at the University of Wisconsin-La Crosse.
   The event is in its eighth year, said Snowflake, the clown who
started it all. Snowflake is Richard Snowberg, 46, administrator of
the audiovisual center at the university.
   The 390 student clowns, whose average age is close to 50, come
from 35 states, Bermuda, Canada and England. They paid $295 each,
per week, to sleep in dormitories without air conditioning, eat
their meals on campus and pick up tips about clowning during
lectures, workshops, performances and discussions.
   Classes are scheduled on such topics as how to walk on stilts,
paint a clown face, make balloon animals and develop a costume and
character.
   There are also classes on clowning at hospitals and nursing
homes, writing clown gospel skits, juggling, the use of props,
unicycle riding, magic acts and how to conduct a clown ministry.
   Before Kooky began his demonstration of the nonsense that kids
have come to love, he shared his first rule: ``Never unload the car
first. Check that you've got the right house.''
</TEXT>
