<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SubmarineRocks     06-07 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarine Rocks,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Mistakes Rocks for Submarines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy crews mistook undersea rocks for
alien submarines and dropped depth charges on them during recent
anti-sub operations, a defense staff spokesman said Tuesday.
   On Tuesday, the navy, using sonar and other tracking gear,
attacked a suspicious-looking object off the southwestern port of
Goteborg. Sailors fired charges at another object Sunday off
Oxelosund, on the Baltic east coast, said spokesman H.G. Wessberg.
   Later checks by frogmen showed that the ``intruders'' were rocks
that resembled submarines, he said. Blast damage to the rocks showed
that the navy was on target.
   ``But investigations of the sea bottoms in six other areas where
we have used weapons indicate no other explanation than foreign
underwater activity there,'' Wessberg said.
   Since May 30, Sweden has carried out eight operations with mines
and live ammunition against suspected foreign submarines.
   Military authorities of this neutral country have reported
snooping by foreign submarines regularly since a Soviet sub ran
aground outside a naval base in southern Sweden in 1981.
   No intruders have been caught since then, although a government
commission identified 1982 intruders as Soviet submarines, and the
government lodged a diplomatic protest.
</TEXT>
