<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-07 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Begin Withdrawal From Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRINCOMALEE, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Indian soldiers were
withdrawn from Sri Lanka on Tuesday since India sent more than
50,000 peacekeeping troops to the island 10 months ago.
   About 400 soldiers sat cross-legged on a dock in this port city
waiting to sail home to Madras in southern India.
   Indian officials had said earlier that as many as 3,000 Indian
soldiers would be withdrawn this week. But, citing security reasons,
they declined Tuesday to give specific figures.
   Indian army musicians played martial music on bagpipes as about a
dozen armored personnel carriers and several jeeps and trucks were
hoisted aboard an Indian freighter.
   ``Do not call this a withdrawal, but a thinning out of troops,''
said Sri Lankan Gen. Sepala Attygalle, who attended the ceremony in
Trincomalee, 150 miles northeast of the capital of Colombo.
   The Indians first began arriving on July 30, a day after Sri
Lanka signed an Indian-brokered peace accord aimed at ending the
civil war in the northeast of the island between Tamil rebels and
the Sinhalese Buddhists.
   Many among the Sinhalese have opposed the presence of the Indian
troops, who they fear may stay on the island.
   ``This is the beginning of the end of suspicions and
apprehensions about India's intentions on Sri Lanka,'' said Indian
High Commissioner J.N. Dixit _ the equivalent of ambassador _ who
spoke to a news conference in Colombo after the ceremony.
   Lt. Gen. A.S. Kalkat, the Indian commanding officer in Sri lanka,
praised his departing men for their sacrifice in helping Sri Lanka
restore order in the areas dominated by Tamil guerrillas. At least
480 Indian soldiers have been killed fighting the rebels.
   The latest victim was an Indian soldier who died only hours
before the departure ceremony, when a bomb set by the rebels
exploded as his jeep passed. Four others were injured.
   A Sri Lankan officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the attack six miles south of Trincomalee was intended as ``a slap
in the face'' of the departing Indians.
   ``All Sri Lankans should thank (the Indians) for their services
and fighting to preserve the independence and unity of this
country,'' Sri Lankan President Junius R. Jayewardene told
Parliament on Tuesday.
   Jayewardene said he expected the fighting to end soon in the
northeast so that elections could be held there for new provincial
councils.
   The peace accord called for the Tamils to lay down their arms in
exchange for the creation of district councils, which would allow
the Tamils to take control of their local schools and social
services.
   But elections to choose the councils have not been scheduled in
the Tamil-dominated areas because of the continued fighting.
Government officials have said they hope to hold them by July.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, claim they are discriminated against by
the Sinhalese Buddhists.
   India became involved because its own 60 million Tamils are
sympathetic to their Sri Lankan brethren, who launched an
independence campaign on the island in 1983.
   The largest and most extreme of the rebel groups, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, rejected the peace accord and continued
fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
