<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbuseShooting Bjt   06-07 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abuse Shooting, Bjt,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney: Son Shot Police Officer Father Because of Repeated Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 18 years, police ignored complaints that one
of their own regularly beat his wife and children, and now his
oldest child stands accused of shooting his father in revenge, an
attorney said Tuesday.
   Authorities charged Henry Taylor III, 18, with attempted murder
in the shooting Saturday of policeman Henry Taylor Jr., whom a judge
labeled ``a time bomb'' after hearing allegations of abuse.
   The teen-ager woke his father sleeping on a couch and said,
``This is for you'' before blasting him six times with a .25-caliber
pistol, authorities said.
   Taylor's wife, Paula, contends that over the last 18 years she
called the police more than 100 times to complain that her husband
was abusing her or their four children, said Chester Blair, the
younger Taylor's attorney.
   ``It was just a regular procedure of her calling the police,
complaining that he was beating her or beating the kids or
threatening her with a weapon,'' Blair alleged.
   Police did little, Blair said, because ``there is a tendency for
them to protect their own.''
   Police have begun an internal investigation into the allegations
by Blair and Mrs. Taylor, said department spokeswoman Tina Vicini.
She said she couldn't respond directly to the allegations.
   Blair said Mrs. Taylor never went through with filing a formal
complaint against her husband. Once, when she tried to press
charges, her husband said he would swear out countercharges against
his wife and their children, he said.
   ``So she dropped the charges because she didn't want to put her
children through being charged for something they didn't have
anything to do with,'' Blair said.
   In a domestic dispute, the injured party may sign a criminal
complaint and a court date will be set. If the crime is a
misdemeanor, the defendant is held until posting bond; if it is a
felony, a state's attorney is summoned to interview the complainant,
witnesses and the accused, and decide whether to file charges.
   Taylor, 55, was in fair condition Tuesday with two gunshot wounds
in the head and four in the neck, said hospital spokeswoman Holly
Rea.
   Police records show that Taylor has received psychiatric
treatment and has been on disability leave because of emotional
problems, Blair said. Ms. Vicini confirmed that Taylor has been on
disability but said she didn't know why.
   ``The shooting was caused, I believe, by a battered-son
syndrome,'' Blair said. ``The father would beat up the mother, and
the son, who was the oldest of their four children, would intercede
on behalf of the mother.
   ``The father would taunt him and say he was the mother's
bodyguard and then beat the son.''
   During a bond hearing Monday for the younger Taylor, Blair filed
a motion in Cook County Circuit Court with examples of the alleged
abuse by the elder Taylor, a 32-year veteran of the department.
   After listening to the allegations, Associate Circuit Judge
Michael Bolan reduced the son's bond from $500,000 to $10,000 and
called the elder Taylor ``an absolute menace to his immediate
family.''
   ``He's a time bomb who goes off and repeatedly goes off,'' the
judge said.
   In the most recent incident, Blair said Taylor threatened to kill
his wife May 24 with a pistol and then chased his son around the
yard, threatening to kill him, after he tried to help his mother.
   Police took the elder Taylor's gun but didn't arrest him because
they considered it a domestic dispute, Blair said.
   ``When a policeman is called to the home of a fellow officer, he
treats him as a fellow officer and he treats everyone else as an
outsider,'' Blair said. ``So if the officer is accused, they listen
to him instead of the person making the complaint.''
</TEXT>
