<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FAA-AgingPlanes     06-07 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-Aging Planes,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Inspectors Told to Keep Closer Eye on Checks of Older Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration had told
its inspectors to become more heavily involved in the ``hands-on''
surveillance of maintenance on older jetliners, agency officials
said Tuesday.
   The directive is among a variety of actions planned within the
agency as a result of a three-day industry conference concluded last
week on how to assure that aging jetliners are kept in safe
condition.
   The conference grew out of the April 28 accident in which a
19-year-old Aloha Airlines Boeing 737 tore apart during a flight,
causing a 20-foot section of the cabin wall and ceiling to separate.
A flight attendant was killed when she was swept from the plane.
   FAA spokesman Bob Buckhorn said that among other steps resulting
from last week's conference on aging aircraft, the agency would:
   _Develop ways to improve the sharing within the industry of
technical information about aging aircraft.
   _Establish additional testing techniques to determine the life of
a jetliner.
   _Place increased emphasis within the FAA on ``human factor
aspects'' of aircraft maintenance and inspection to reduce the
likelihood that such work is not being done properly.
   The FAA also plans at some point to examine some commuter
aircraft for signs of aging, Buckhorn said.
</TEXT>
