<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WaterProjects     06-07 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Projects,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs No-New-Starts Water Projects Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee, following the lead of
the House, approved an energy and water development spending bill
Tuesday that provides no money to begin construction of new water
projects next year.
   The appropriations legislation for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct.
1, contains $18.05 billion but nothing for new starts by the Army
Corps of Engineers or the Interior Department's Bureau of
Reclamation.
   Chairman Bennett Johnston, D-La., said the Appropriations energy
and water development subcommittee had requests for nearly three
dozen new dams, irrigation systems and harbor improvements but was
able to hold the line.
   ``If we make any exceptions, the dam is broken and the flood
starts,'' said Johnston as his panel voiced its approval of a
modified version of the $17.8 billion, no-new-starts spending
package voted by the House last month.
   The subcommittee also followed the House line on funding for the
superconducting super collider, the multibillion-dollar high-energy
physics project recommended by the Reagan administration.
   The panel approved spending $100 million on preliminary research
for the project, but like the House it decreed that non be used to
begin construction.
   ``We're going to buck this decision to the next president,''
Johnston said. ``If he finds the (construction) money, we'll go
ahead with it.''
   Nearly half the Senate package _ $8.1 billion _ is earmarked for
the Department of Energy for defense-related nuclear activities.
Much of the remaining money would go to continue construction work
on dozens of water projects and to pay for operation and maintenance
on hundreds more.
</TEXT>
