<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Meese-GOPConvention     06-07 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-GOP Convention,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Considering Attending GOP Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III is considering
going to the Republican National Convention, despite the political
embarrassment some Republicans say his legal problems are causing
Vice President George Bush.
   ``Cabinet officers traditionally attend these events and the
attorney general is prepared to do so,'' Justice Department
spokesman Patrick Korten said Tuesday.
   Korten said Meese's tentative schedule calls for him to be
present for part of the convention, with the precise dates of any
appearance still to be determined.
   Meese would not stay through the whole GOP convention, which runs
from Aug. 15-18 in New Orleans.
   The attorney general has been the subject of a criminal
investigation for nearly 13 months. The probe focusing on Meese's
involvement with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a $1 billion
Iraqi oil pipeline project is about to end, and a report to be
issued soon is expected to raise questions about Meese's conduct.
   At the attorney general's request, Meese and Bush met privately
in May and Meese promised not to do anything that would jeopardize
Bush's candidacy. White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker has said
that Meese's legal difficulties could hurt Republican prospects of
holding onto the White House.
   Some Bush aides have made similar public comments, although Bush
himself has not.
   Meanwhile, Meese was to meet late Tuesday afternoon with a group
of moderate Republicans from the House, known as The 92 Group. In
recent weeks, the attorney general has met with conservative
senators and congressmen, telling them he has no intention of
stepping down. At a meeting May 25, at least two conservative House
members said Meese's legal problems were causing political damage to
the Republican Party and to Bush's presidential campaign.
   In another indication that Meese plans to remain at the Justice
Department, Korten, the newly appointed director of the department's
public affairs office, has hired two aides, John Allen and Timothy
Sullivan, to assist him in promoting the attorney general's agenda.
   Allen is handling special projects for Korten while Sullivan will
handle writing duties. Both aides worked with Korten at the Office
of Personnel Management, while Sullivan, most recently a political
consultant in Manassas, Va., also has worked at the Republican
National Committee.
   The speech-writing unit at the Justice Department has been
without a director since William Schambra resigned last month, the
same day that Meese's chief spokesman, Terry Eastland, said the
attorney general had fired him for not defending Meese aggressively
enough. Sullivan will handle some speech-writing duties, but the
position of head of the unit will remain vacant.
</TEXT>
