<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Duarte     06-07 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Appeals for Unity of Military and Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
who underwent surgery for stomach cancer Tuesday in Washington, sent
a message to Salvadoran military appealing for unity and respect for
civilian government.
   The message, published Tuesday by the newspaper Prensa Grafica,
urges the high comnmand to consider ``the immense, historic
responsibility that is yours to guarantee the dynamic of the process
that we are moving forward.''
   It said the military learned ``to be historically aware of its
true role'' and ``that conduct should be promoted and maintained so
pluralistic democracy becomes irreversible in our country, and in no
circumstances is interrupted by actions of force or coups.''
   Coup rumors have circulated since March, when Duarte's Christian
Democratic Party lost to the rightist Republican Nationalist
Alliance in National Assembly and municipal elections.
   He asked the armed forces to remain united because ``much remains
to be done, in the first place to end the conflict that bleeds our
country.''
   More than eight years of war between leftist rebels and
U.S.-supported governments have devastated an economy once among the
strongest in Central America.
   A broadcast Tuesday on the rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos
said: ``The apparent unity of the armed institution is artificial''
and ``the contradictions are starting to be demonstrated publicly.''
   A statement released Tuesday by Walter Reed Army Medical Center
in Washington said Duarte, 62, underwent surgery to remove cancerous
tissue from his stomach but doctors left his diseased liver
untouched.
   Duarte went to Washington on May 31, leaving Vice President
Rodolfo Castillo Claramount in charge.
</TEXT>
