<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ExecutionAppeals     06-07 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Execution Appeals,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Office Handling Final Appeals for Death Row Inmates Out of Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The office that handles final appeals
for death row inmates told the Florida Supreme Court on Tuesday that
it's out of money until the new fiscal year July 1, although it has
three active death warrants to defend.
   ``I just said, `I'm broke,''' said Larry Spalding, Capital
Collateral Representative, in describing his arguments before the
high court.
   Spalding said he asked the court for some relief, either through
staying the three warrants until the next budget year, or by having
someone supply his office with additional funds.
   ``The question is, what relief can they give us and whose
responsibility is it?'' Spalding said.
   Carolyn Snurkowski, an assistant attorney general, argued that
the agency can get through the remaining three weeks of the fiscal
year without relief.
   The high court gave no indication on when it will rule, but
Spalding and Ms. Snurkowski expect a speedy decision.
   Of the three active warrants the office said it has no money to
defend, one is for Ernesto Suarez, whose execution is scheduled June
22 in the electric chair at Florida State Prison near Starke. The
other two inmates are Daniel Karr Johnson, scheduled to die July 7,
and Robert Ira Peede, July 8.
   The CCR's money woes, Spalding said, are the result of several
facors, including the number of death warrants signed by Gov. Bob
Martinez, moving the office into more expensive quarters and the
large number of hearings and other expenses involved in handling
death cases.
   Spalding estimates his office needs $60,000 to $70,000 to make it
through the year. Its total budget is $1.4 million.
</TEXT>
