<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CelebrityDuds     06-07 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Celebrity Duds,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actors Make Plea To Keep Costumes Of The Stars In Hollywood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nostalgia buffs and city officials are
battling over where Hollywood fashion memorabilia _ including Fred
Astaire's shoes and Rudolph Valentino's cape _ should be stored.
   Debbie Reynolds and Glenn Ford, along with other stars, say they
want the celebrity outfits in Hollywood. The city's Department of
Recreation and Parks says the costumes should stay in safe storage
at the downtown Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising, where
they were moved two weeks ago.
   Until the move, the more than 200 costumes were stored for two
decades in the dilapidated environs of the old Lincoln Heights Jail.
   In a news conference Monday at the Hollywood Studio Museum, Miss
Reynolds and Ford joined others in a plea on behalf of the Hollywood
Heritage preservationist organization.
   ``Hollywood history should stay in Hollywood, at a Hollywood
museum,'' Miss Reynolds said.
   Linda Barth of the Department of Recreation and Parks said
security at the fashion institute was appealing, including security
``from environmental factors, financial ability and the type and
number of conservators.''
   The garments were originally part of a collection owned by
Hollywood Museum Associates. But the group could not raise enough
money to establish a museum and the collection was sold to the city
for $22,000. The costumes were first stored at a Bekins building,
then moved to the old jail.
   ``I visited there (jail) in 1986 when there was a plumbing leak
and everything was under two inches of water,'' said Richard Adkins,
executive director of Hollywood Heritage. ``A cape worn by Rudolph
Valentino in `Monsieur Beaucaire' was damaged.''
   Garments in the collection include outfits worn by Norma Shearer
in ``Idiot's Delight,'' Greta Garbo in ``Inspiration'' and Charles
Laughton and Kirk Douglas in ``Spartacus.''
   Miss Reynolds said she would push for a larger Hollywood museum
to house the memorabilia ``until the day I drop dead.''
   ``Hopefully, by then, it'll be built,'' she said.
</TEXT>
