<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Media     06-07 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Media,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government-Controlled Media Continue Attacks On Voiceless
Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government-controlled media still
attack an opposition rendered voiceless by the closure of four
newspapers, a television station and three radio stations critical
of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``I do not think they will allow the news media to reopen,''
Winston Robles, director of the shuttered daily newspaper La Prensa,
said of Noriega's government. ``They cannot co-exist with a free
press.
   ``How can the government talk of elections next year when there
is no freedom of the press?'' Robles said in a recent interview.
   The government has indicated that Noriega, who was indicted on
charges of drug trafficking in the United States, may run for
president in the May 1989 election.
   The dailies El Siglo and Extra, the weekly Quiubo, Channel 5
television, and radio stations La Exitosa, KW Continente and Radio
Mundial also have been closed. All are owned by critics of the
Noriega-controlled government.
   The media controlled by the government or sympathetic to Noriega
relentlessly criticize the opposition forces who want to oust the
general, who as head of the nation's 15,000-member Defense Forces is
considered the country's de facto leader.
   The government's radio and television station and the three daily
newspapers who support Noriega constantly ridicule opposition
leaders, often describing them as lackeys of the United States.
   They also criticize the United States and its allies. Last week,
the daily La Republica said in a headline that President Jose
Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador has cancer because he once kissed an
American flag.
   Only La Estrella, the nation's oldest newspaper, sometimes gives
space to opposition comment.
   Opposition efforts to obtain court orders or get official word
about reopening have been fruitless.
   La Prensa was first closed on July 26. It was allowed to reopen
Jan. 20, shortly before President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire
Noriega as head of the Defense Forces. Delvalle, who owns Channel 5,
was instead deposed by Noriega supporters in the Legislative
Assembly.
   On Feb. 25, soldiers who said they were acting on the ``order of
a higher authority'' closed down La Prensa again. Police have since
guarded the building.
   ``We have no access to our equipment or files in the building,''
said Robles. ``We cannot find out who ordered the closing down of
the newspaper, what we are accused of or what is going to happen.''
   The newspaper filed suit against Noriega in the Supreme Court,
holding him responsible for the closure.
   But the Supreme Court rejected the petition late last month,
saying it had no jurisdiction and could not fix blame for the
closure because the soldiers who shut down La Prensa had no written
orders.
   On Monday, nine officials from the attorney general's office and
three police officers went to the La Prensa building for what they
described as an ``investigation.'' They refused to provide any
details about their inquiry.
   Ruben Dario Carles, chairman of the board of La Prensa, said the
paper will put its case before the InterAmerican Human Rights
Commission and appeal for support from the embassies of several
Latin American countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
