<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoSchools     06-07 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Schools,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Chicago's `Worst' Schools Best Place To Try Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's public schools, labeled the worst in the
nation by Education Secretary William Bennett, could be the best
place to try changes that would help students learn, Bennett said
Tuesday.
   ``There are radical proposals in the air,'' Bennett said. ``This
may be a revolutionary time.''
   Speaking to reporters after the annual meeting of the Chicago
Council on Foreign Relations, Bennett suggested the 430,000-pupil
system consider a voucher plan in which parents could choose schools
and the government would pick up the tab.
   ``If you tried it, tried it honestly and fairly, I would predict
it would improve things dramatically,'' he said.
   Bennett also said the school system's bureaucracy was ``the
blob.'' He called for redistributing power to give parents and local
school principals more say over curriculum, personnel and other
policies.
   Last November, Bennett called Chicago's public schools, plagued
by low test scores and high dropout rates, the worst in the nation
and an ``education meltdown.'' He later accused teachers' unions of
blocking reform.
   He said Tuesday that his view of Chicago's system hasn't changed
much.
   ``If it's not the worst, it's too ... close to the worst,'' he
said.
   Nearly 45 percent of the students who began school with the class
of 1985 dropped out before graduating. State figures also show that
half of Chicago's public high schools ranked in the bottom 1 percent
of U.S. schools for student scores on the American College Test.
   But Bennett said that whatever comes out of efforts to improve
the schools ``may be able to point the way for other school systems
in the country.''
   Bennett stayed out of a fight in the Illinois General Assembly
over a state income tax increase, although he said ``I am not
convinced that it takes money'' to change schools for the better.
   He said any new state money for education in Chicago must be tied
to a reform package that would shift power in the system.
   ``You must give the people who run your schools the power, the
autonomy, to run those schools,'' he said. ``Then you must hold them
accountable for the results.''
   Calling any reform that didn't redistribute power ``nonsense,''
Bennett said unions interested only in ``getting more and more for
everyone'' may be hurt in the short run. But positive changes in
schools would help unions in the long run by raising the
professional esteem of teachers.
   Bennett visited two Chicago schools in March at the request of
Chicago Teachers Union. He said afterward that ``intransigence of
special interests'' such as unions remain the biggest obstacle to
reform.
   Jacqueline Vaughn, president of the Chicago union, said then that
cutbacks in government funds were the real culprits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
