<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Drugs     06-07 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Drugs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Office Criticizes House Panel's Work On Drug Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of Management and Budget said
Tuesday that legislation under consideration by the House
Appropriations Committee would slash $686 million from funds the
Reagan administration seeks to combat drug abuse.
   ``At a time when various members of Congress are calling for
increased federal drug spending in the face of a drug crisis of
unparalleled proportions, the Commerce, Justice and State
appropriations bill ... would actually reduce'' fiscal 1989 funding,
OMB said in a statement.
   The budget office complained that the bill would provide
``essentially a freeze'' on the spending levels for anti-drug
programs administered by the Justice Department.
   It said that instead of approving the $2.67 billion that Reagan
requested in the budget for the fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1,
the committee proposes appropriating only $1.98 billion, or $686
million less than was sought.
   The bill being marked up by the House Appropriations Committee
involves money for the Drug Enforcement Administration, the Bureau
of Prisons, the U.S. Marshals office and U.S. attorneys offices
across the country.
   ``The president's FY 1989 budget requested sufficient funds to
preserve the momentum of the federal government's war on drug abuse
in the three key areas of prevention, treatment and law
enforcement,'' OMB said in a statement released at the White House.
``Should Congress provide less than the president's request,
programs to combat illegal drugs will suffer.''
   Reagan told a U.S. Coast Guard Academy graduating class last
month that he wanted to see the national drug debate depoliticized,
and he proposed creation of a joint executive-legislative task force
to recommend solutions.
   But no such joint task force has yet been constituted, although
House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and House Minority Leader Bob
Michel, R-Ill., have study groups working on legislative proposals.
   OMB said that under the legislation the House Appropriations
Committee is poised to recommend:
   _There would be no financing of 177 new drug enforcement agents
and support positions, at a cost of $44 million. Plans for expanded
intelligence capabilities and equipment, including aircraft and
computer equipment, would have to be cancelled.
   _The government would not be able to carry out a proposal to add
3,400 positions at a cost of $574 million to reinforce the federal
prison system.
   _It would be impossible to create 566 additional U.S. attorney
and support positions in the prosecution force, at a cost of $44
million, and the prosecution of major organized crime drug task
force cases would be out of the question.
   _There would be no money for the anticipated addition of 161 to
the staff of the U.S. Marshals office, at a cost of $24 million.
Prisoner transportation and the delivery of drug defendants at trial
sites would be adversely affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
