<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MortgageRates     06-07 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mortgage Rates,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest on Fixed Rate Home Mortgages Climbed Again in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 30-year, fixed-rate home
mortgages continued to climb in May, encouraging Americans to turn
to adjustable-rate mortgages, the government said Tuesday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the federal regulator of
savings institutions, said the national average for conventional,
single-family loans jumped to 10.63 percent in early May, up from
10.48 percent in early April.
   It was the second consecutive monthly increase. Since peaking at
11.42 percent just before the October stock market crash, rates had
dropped steadily, hitting 10.33 percent in early March.
   The bank board said rates on the most popular type of one-year,
adjustable-rate mortgages, those with limits on how much the rate
can increase, also rose, but not by as much. They increased to 8.68
percent in May, up from 8.61 percent a month earlier.
   James Barth, chief economist of the bank board, said the
percentage of mortgages with adjustable rates rose for the first
time in five months to 53 percent in May, up from 49 percent in
April.
   He attributed that to the widening of the spread between the two
types of loans. The gap grew for two months in a row _ from 1.69
percent in March to 1.95 in May.
   A separate weekly report by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.,
known as Freddie Mac, show continued increases in fixed-rate
mortgages through May. It said the average last week was 10.58
percent, the same as the previous week but up from 10.32 percent
four weeks before.
   Freddie Mac averages are lower than the bank board's because they
do not include add-on fees, known as points, which are paid by
borrowers.
</TEXT>
