<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Elections     06-07 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Elections,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extreme Right Offers Deal to Center In Legislative Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The extreme-right National Front said Tuesday it
will withdraw its candidates from six legislative districts in favor
of conservatives and asked the center-right coalition to reciprocate.
   Within hours, candidates from the center-right alliance of the
Union for French Democracy and Rally for the Republic withdrew in a
southern district that includes Marseille, a National Front
stronghold.
   A statement by Jean-Claude Gaudin, UDF leader in the National
Assembly, said a Socialist or Communist would be elected unless
alliance candidates withdrew.
   Conservative leaders remain divided on whether to deal with the
National Front, which is viewed as racist and xenophobic.
   The conservatives and President Francois Mitterrand's Socialists
ran almost even in the first round Sunday of voting for the
577-member National Assembly. Computer projections favor the
Socialists to win a majority in next week's runoff because of the
way support is distributed.
   Marseille and its region has attracted attention because National
Front voters could swing the results in 14 districts.
   A statement by the National Front said its candidates would pull
out in the six districts where they trailed other rightists in the
first round.
   Party leader Jean-Marie Le Pen and National Front members who
finished ahead of conservatives in seven races in and around
Marseille will compete in Sunday's runoff and expect reciprocal
withdrawals.
   If the conservatives do not withdraw in those districts, the
Socialist candidates are likely to benefit from the split in the
conservative vote and win National Assembly seats with less than 50
percent of the vote.
   Any candidate who won at least 12.5 percent in the first round
can compete in the runoff, but those without a chance to win
commonly throw their support to one of the top two finishers.
   Maurice Toga, one of the conservative candidates who withdrew,
said he and three others who belong to the Rally for the Republic
would not endorse the National Front.
   ``Our withdrawals are meant only to respect the will of the
voters and to assure the defeat of the candidates of the left
wherever possible,'' he said.
   Former Security Minister Charles Pasqua said the reciprocal
arrangement Tuesday was ``a local and not a national accord.''
   Any alliance between the conservatives and Le Pen's extreme
right, even an unspoken local agreement in Marseille, could backfire
in the rest of the country.
   Michel Noir, trade minister in the conservative government of
Jacques Chirac that resigned after Mitterrand's re-election May 8,
said a deal with the National Front in Marseille might save three or
four seats but cost about 60 elsewhere in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
