<HEAD>Specter Resting Comfortably After Blood Clot Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., was resting
comfortably at Bethesda Naval Hospital Tuesday after undergoing
surgery to remove a blood clot in his right leg, a spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Dan McKenna, said the clot was caused by Specter
tearing a muscle while playing squash several weeks ago.
   ``I talked to him this morning and he didn't seem to be in any
distress at all,'' McKenna said. He added that Specter hopes to be
released from the hospital Wednesday, in time for an expected vote
on a major trade bill.
   Specter, 58, plays squash daily before work. But he has been
unable to play since he hurt the leg four weeks ago.
   Specter did not know surgery was necessary until several sets of
tests were conducted at the hospital on Monday. After the tests were
done, he went to Capitol Hill for a vote, then returned to the
hospital and found that doctors were recommending precautionary
surgery, according to McKenna.
