<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1932EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailSuicides     06-07 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Suicides,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jail Suicides Nine Times Higher Than Rate for General Populace,
Study Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suicide rate among jail inmates is
nine times greater than that of the general population and continues
to be the leading cause of death in city and county lockups,
according to a federally financed study released Tuesday.
   ``Although the average length of stay in jail is approximately 6
to 11 days, 51 percent of all jail suicide victims were dead within
the first 24 hours of incarceration and 29 percent committed suicide
within the first three hours,'' the National Center on Institutions
and Alternatives said.
   ``While alcohol-drug related and minor `other' charges account
for 37 percent of offenses for which jail inmates are confined, they
represented 55 percent of all suicide victims,'' according to the
study of jail suicides in 1985-86.
   Lindsay M. Hayes directed the project, which was supported
through a grant from the National Institute of Corrections in the
Department of Justice. Hayes said the suicide rate in detention
facilities was found to be 107 per 100,000 inmates. Census Bureau
studies show, he said, that the rate is 12.5 per 100,000 in the
general population.
   ``Further, suicide continues to be the leading cause of death in
our nation's jails,'' Hayes said in a statement.
   Texas, California, New York and Illinois recorded 32 percent of
all the suicides in the study. Those states, according to Justice
Department figures, also house one in three jail inmates.
   The numbers of suicides in jails was 453 in 1985 and 401 in 1986,
the study said.
   The findings also showed that 72 percent of the suicide victims
were white, 94 percent were male, the average age of the victim was
30, 60 percent of the victims were intoxicated at the time they were
jailed and two of three victims were in isolation.
   ``While black inmates comprise 41 percent of the jail population,
they acounted for only 16 percent of the jail suicides,'' the study
said. ``While 31 percent of jail inmates are intoxicated by alcohol
upon arrest, over 60 percent of jail suicide victims were
intoxicated upon arrest.''
   Only Rhode Island and Vermont recorded no jail suicides in the
two-year period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0693 06-07 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assassination Attempt Against Israeli-Appointed Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 8th graf previous, `Israeli-appointed
mayors...' to ADD potential impact of Arab resignations. Pickup 9th
graf previous,`Bar-Lev said. INSERTS four grafs at bottom with
Shamir rejecting Arab-American's request to be released. EDITS
throughout to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL BIREH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli-appointed Arab
mayor of this West Bank town was stabbed in the heart outside his
office Tuesday in an apparent assassination attempt by Palestinian
militants.
   The attack on Hassan Tawil, 74, came as leaders of the Arab
uprising issued a new list of directives, including renewed demands
that all Israeli-appointed Arab officials resign.
   Officials at Ramallah Hospital said Tawil was in serious but
stable condition after surgery. He was stabbed once with a ``very
long knife'' that pierced his heart, diaphragm, liver and stomach, a
doctor said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The PLO-led United Leadership of the Uprising demanded in a new
leaflet that all Israeli-appointed mayors and Arab employees of the
military government step down.
   It called for protests and a general strike Thursday in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, captured by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Since the rebellion began Dec. 8, 201 Palestinians have been
killed and more than 5,000 injured. Two Israelis have died.
   Israeli Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev, who visited El Bireh after
the attack, said he hoped the stabbing would not lead to
resignations.
   Israeli-appointed mayors serve in about a dozen West Bank towns
and cities. Heads of about 85 village councils also are appointed by
the military government.
   The municipalities and village councils provide local services to
the Palestinian population and serve as a buffer and mediator
between the residents and Israel's military authorities. If
appointed officials quit, the Israeli officials replacing them would
find it even more difficult to gain Palestinian cooperation.
   Bar-Lev said police had no immediate leads, but he believed the
assailants had a ``nationalistic motive,'' meaning they were
Palestinian nationalists.
   Yusef Taher, an Arab member of the El Bireh city council, blamed
the attack on Palestinian militants and added: ``I had hoped we
would not descend to the level of assassination.''
   Israel radio reported military officials met with several
appointed West Bank leaders in an effort to persuade them not to
resign. A senior military government official confirmed a meeting
took place but would not elaborate.
   The appointed mayors of Jericho, Ramallah and Hebron refused
comment when asked if they would step down.
   The attacker or attackers ambushed Tawil at about 11:30 a.m. as
he left the town hall, Bar-Lev told reporters. He said Tawil was not
with his bodyguard.
   Minutes after the stabbing, Associated Press photographer Martin
Cleaver saw Tawil slumped against a storefront, surrounded by
soldiers. His face was ashen and a large bloody wound was visible in
his left chest, partially covered by a bandage.
   Cleaver said four soldiers commandeered a passing car and took
Tawil to Ramallah Hospital.
   The army clamped a curfew on El Bireh, a city of 10,000 about
nine miles north of Jerusalem. Hundreds of soldiers patrolled the
city and wouldn't let reporters enter.
   Tawil's wife, Mahdeyah, said in a telephone interview that her
husband had been threatened repeatedly before the stabbing. She said
twice the family house had been attacked with stones and twice with
firebombs.
   ``My kids and I always urged him to resign, but he felt he was
serving his people,'' Tawil's wife said.
   Tawil was named to his post in September 1986 along with the
mayors of Hebron and Ramallah in an effort by Israel to gain
cooperation from Palestinian moderates. The Arab mayors replaced
Israeli officials.
   The appointments came six months after Palestinian militants
assassinated the Israeli-appointed Nablus mayor, Zafer El-Masri.
   Palestinians expressed mixed feelings after Tuesday's stabbing.
   ``He should have stood by his people, but instead he listened to
Israel and Jordan,'' said Mustafa Ibrahim, 25, of Ramallah. ``I hope
we'll hear about the rest (of the appointed mayors) soon.''
   Arab militants have complained that Israel's appointment of
mayors was a scheme to replace the Palestine Liberation
Organization's leadership in the occupied territories with
Jordanian-backed moderates.
   Farah Araj, the elected mayor of Beit Jallah near Bethlehem,
condemned the attack. ``We tried assassinations in the 1930s and
1940s, and it didn't work, but instead made things worse and divided
the Arab community,'' he said.
   Also Tuesday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir sharply rejected a
request to free Mubarak Awad until the Arab-American is to be
deported Sunday, Israel army radio said.
   The Supreme Court last Sunday upheld a government deportation
order issued last month against Awad, who advocates non-violent
resistance to the Israeli occupation.
   The radio said Awad's lawyer Avraham Gal asked Shamir to release
him from jail and place him under house arrest until his deportation
as a good-will gesture.
   Shamir aide Tzahi Hanegbi wrote Gal that Awad's release from jail
could lead to violent disturbances, the radio said.
</TEXT>
