<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldFoodPrize 1stLd-Writethru a0747 06-07 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Food Prize, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Researcher Wins $200,000 World Food Prize</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf bgng ``The prize ... '' to CORRECT that General
Foods is based in Ryebrook, N.Y.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Flint Chandler Jr., developer of a
worldwide agricultural research network which has increased the
availability of food for billions of people, was named Tuesday to
receive the $200,000 General Foods World Food Prize.
   ``This was a total surprise to me,'' Chandler said of the award
given to recognize outstanding achievement in improving the
quantity, quality or availability of food on a significant world
scale.
   Chandler, who will celebrate his 81st birthday on June 22, told a
news conference that world governments must ``support and strengthen
... the connection between the research worker, the extension worker
(in the field) and the farmer'' to increase world food production.
   ``We must meet the farmer where he is,'' he said, noting that
``the farmer is not very often the limiting factor'' in the success
of agricultural programs in foreign lands.
   Instead, Chandler said, ``it's the extension agent who wants to
make sure it's the right thing he's recommending or government
officials who aren't ready to support (new agricultural)
innovations.''
   Chandler, who was chosen from a field of 125 nominees from 39
nations, will receive his cash award and an original sculpture by
Saul Bass during a ceremony at the Smithsonian Institution on Oct. 4.
   The prize, first awarded in 1987, is funded by the General Foods
Fund Inc, a non-profit arm of General Foods Corp. of Ryebrook, N.Y.
   As the founding director of the Philippines-based International
Rice Research Institute (IRRI), Chandler oversaw the development of
high-yielding varieties of rice in the 1950s and 1960s that helped
form the basis for the green revolution in Asia.
   ``The single most important thing I did was to help establish
IRRI, to hire competent scientists, to stimulate them, lead them
into productivity along practical lines of getting increased food
production and not having them go off theoretical lines,'' he said.
   The research developments at IRRI are credited with averting a
major famine in Asia in the 1970s. The center became the
institutional model for 12 other agricultural stations around the
world.
   Chandler, a Columbus, Ohio native who now lives in Raymond,
Maine, served as president of the University of New Hampshire from
1947 to 1954 before turning to full-time agricultural research.
</TEXT>
