<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Ali     06-07 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Ali,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese, Ali Welcome Attorney to Justice Department Criminal Division</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former heavyweight boxing champion Muhammad Ali
and Attorney General Edwin Meese III welcomed aboard a new Justice
Department aide Tuesday and Meese declared that the department,
riddled in recent months with key departures, is ``in good shape.''
   The unlikely lineup of Ali and Meese came about because the
former fighter recommended University of Virginia law professor
Stephen Saltzburg for a job at the Justice Department. Saltzburg was
named as a deputy in the department's criminal division.
   Ali got to know Saltzburg when the ex-fighter spoke to one of
Saltzburg's classes on campus about Ali's 1967 conviction for draft
evasion. Ali had sought an exemption from the military draft on
religious grounds.
   Ali called Saltzburg ``a brilliant and compassionate man'' who
would be an excellent addition to the Justice Department ``because
of his character and his background as an expert in criminal law.''
   At a ceremony in the office of Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., who
recommended Saltzburg to the attorney general, Meese said that with
Saltzburg's appointment, the department has ``a new team'' in place
and ``we're in good shape.''
   Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and the former criminal
division chief, William Weld, resigned in protest March 29 along
with two of Weld's aides over Meese's continued tenure at the
Justice Department in the face of an ongoing criminal investigation
of the attorney general. Saltzburg will supervise the narcotics and
dangerous drug section and four other offices.
   Asked whether he was concerned his reputation might be tainted by
Meese's legal problems, Saltzburg replied: ``People will judge me on
the basis of what I do.''
   He said he felt ``very confident'' about the department's
positions on important issues on which he will work, mainly the war
on drugs.
   Saltzburg will be a deputy to acting Assistant Attorney General
Edward S.G. Dennis, the former U.S. attorney in Philadelphia, who
took over Weld's post last week.
   Saltzburg has been a consultant to Herb Stern, a former federal
judge and ex-U.S. attorney who was hired by independent counsel
Lawrence E. Walsh to represent the Iran-Contra prosecutor on the
issue of congressional immunity.
</TEXT>
