<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Wright-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0766 06-07 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Critic Says He Also Use Staff Aide To Work On Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs on Gingrich using Wright case in fund-raising
letter after 11th graf, ``Gingrich said''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The principal critic of House Speaker Jim
Wright's ethics said Tuesday that he too has used a member of his
congressional staff to work on a book he was writing prior to its
publication.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who asked the House ethics committee
last month to investigate Wright, said he is ``fairly confident''
that he asked then-administrative assistant Frank Gregorsky to
review his book, ``Window of Opportunity,'' before it was published
in 1984.
   ``There is clearly a distinction between (using staff on)
legitimate public policy efforts, which may include books and
speeches, which I suspect virtually every member of the Congress
does,'' Gingrich said in a telephone interview.
   ``We all ask our staffs to critique it, to look at it, to make
sure it's all right.''
   Matthew Cossolotto, a former aide to Wright, said in interviews
this week that he spent 150 to 200 hours while on the Texas
Democrat's staff working on Wright's book, ``Reflections of a Public
Man.''
   House records show that Cossolotto also was paid $2,078 from
official congressional accounts to cover his expenses during a 1984
trip to Texas when he oversaw the final editing of the book.
   Wright has refused to comment on the matter since Sunday, when he
defended Cossolotto's assignment during a telephone interview with
The Washington Post. He canceled his regular daily news briefing
Tuesday and denied an Associated Press request for an interview on
the subject.
   Cossolotto's role in the production of Wright's book did not
become public until after Gingrich asked for the ethics committee
investigation into Wright's personal financial dealings.
   But the Georgia congressman said Tuesday he thinks the ethics
panel also should examine whether Wright violated House rules by
assigning Cossolotto to work on the book.
   ``The idea of using 200 hours, of having it be your only job
assignment, of charging over $2,000 for a trip which a staffer says
was only for the purpose of going to Fort Worth in order to write
the book, it seems to me that's clearly wrong,'' he said.
   Gingrich said Gregorsky's only role in his own book was reviewing
the manuscript before it was published. He said he wrote the first
draft himself and the final draft was done with help from his wife
and a professional writer who was paid by the publisher.
   In a related development, aides said Tuesday that Gingrich has
begun using his role in the ethics campaign against Wright to raise
money for GOPAC, a political action committee that supports
conservative candidates for state offices.
   Gingrich, who is general chairman of GOPAC, sent a fund-raising
letter June 1 seeking $75 contributions ``to help us keep the heat
on the Democrats and make the gains we need this November.''
   The letter also included a postcard for recipients to send to
Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the House ethics committee,
urging the panel to launch an investigation of Wright.
   Wright's book was the subject of part of Gingrich's complaint to
the ethics committee. He asked the panel to investigate reports that
Wright was receiving unusually high royalties of 55 percent for the
book, which was published by a company which received more than
$250,000 for services to Wright's re-election campaign in 1985-86.
   Carlos Moore, whose company published the book, said Tuesday that
it had a press run of 20,000 and is sold out. He said most copies
were sold directly by his company for $5.95 each, with Wright
receiving $3.25 and the company $2.70.
   Some copies of the book, however, were sold to bookstores for $3,
Moore said, and Wright received only $1 per book royalties on those.
   In the interview with the Post, Wright responded to reports that
lobbyists had purchased multiple copies of the book by saying he
would be glad to have Moore provide a list of the purchasers.
   But Moore said he had no such list available, although he
speculated that ``very few'' were sold to bookstores.
   ``If I had to guess how many we sold to bookstores, I'd say
between 2,000 and 3,000,'' he said. ``Why take in $3 when I can take
in $5.95?''
  
</TEXT>
