<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CliffFall     06-07 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cliff Fall,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Teen Dead, Two Seriously Injured In Fall From Bluff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four teen-agers who tumbled over a 100-foot
cliff beside the Mississippi River early Tuesday were running down a
dark path that led over the edge, police said.
   Troy Meyer, 16, of Dubuque, died after the four plunged over the
cliff shortly after midnight near the Julien Dubuque monument, which
overlooks the river and Catfish Creek, the Dubuque County Sheriff's
Department said.
   Craig Haverland, 15, and Carl Fink, 17, both of Cuba City, Wis.,
and Jolene Schmitt, 14, of Dubuque, were injured.
   Haverland and Fink were listed in serious condition Tuesday at
the intensive care unit of Mercy Hospital in Dubuque.
   Schmitt fell into some trees and scrambled to nearby rocks. She
was in satisfactory condition.
   ``They thought they were on a path leading down and it was
leading right to the edge of the cliff,'' sheriff's Capt. Milt
Chapman said. ``For some reason, they just took off running. When
one of them tripped, the rest just tumbled right over the top of
him.''
   Chapman said he did not know if the four had been drinking. The
monument area is a favorite place for teens to go and drink, Chapman
said.
   Police were hampered in piecing together what happened because
they had not talked to Haverland and Fink, and managed to speak only
briefly with Miss Schmitt.
</TEXT>
