<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Walsh-Messing     06-07 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walsh-Messing,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecutor Accused of Illegally Using Free Legal Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three conservatives filed a complaint Tuesday
against independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, saying the
Iran-Contra prosecutor may have violated federal criminal law when
he accepted free legal services from Harvard law professor Laurence
Tribe.
   Tribe, at Walsh's behest, wrote a brief in support of another
independent counsel, Alexia Morrison, who is seeking to have the
Supreme Court reverse a federal appeals court decision which
declared that independent counsels are unconstitutional.
   The criminal complaint filed with the Justice Department's
criminal division says Walsh may have violated the Anti-Deficiency
Act, which makes it unlawful for a government employee to accept
voluntary services from private individuals.
   Walsh said his office had researched the question and concluded
there was no violation, and that his office was checking with the
Justice Department on the matter.
   The complaint was filed by three men, including F. Andy Messing
Jr., executive director of the National Defense Council Foundation.
Messing is a conservative activist who worked with fired National
Security Council aide Oliver L. North in attempts to aid the Contras.
   The complaint asks the Justice Department to look into the free
services of Tribe and calls for appointment of an independent
counsel to conduct a criminal investigation.
   The maximum penalty for violating the Anti-Deficiency Act is two
years imprisonment and a $5,000 fine.
   The others filing the complaint were Kenneth Boehm, treasurer of
the Conservative Campaign Fund, and Peter Flaherty, chairman of
Citizens for Reagan.
   ``We have carefully researched this issue and are satsified that
there is no violation whatever of the Anti-Deficiency Act,'' Walsh
said in a statement.
   ``We have communicated this conclusion to the Justice Department,
which has expressed no disagreement and has sought the views of its
office of legal counsel,'' Walsh added.
   The Citizens for Reagan group issued a statement quoting Boehm as
saying ``Walsh has sought to privatize our judicial process.''
   Flaherty said that ``one must question the financial
arrangements'' in which Walsh is allowing senior staff lawyers to
retain their relationships with private law firms. Flaherty said
this has created ``the potential for huge conflicts of interest.''
   A spokesman for Walsh, Jim Wieghart, said a special panel screens
potential conflicts of interest and that ``we're aware of none.''
   Wieghart said Walsh tried to get the most qualified lawyers
possible for his investigation and acknowledged that some have come
to work on a part-time basis.
</TEXT>
