<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AlienExclusions     06-07 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alien Exclusions,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governent Ordered to Grant Visas to Four Barred Due to Communist
Affiliations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Tuesday ordered the government
to grant visas to Nicaragua's interior minister and three others
barred from entering the country because of their membership in
communist or communist-affiliated groups.
   U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene, reversing an earlier
finding that had been set aside by a federal appeals court, ruled
that Nicaraguan Interior Minister Tomas Borge, two Cuban officials
and a former Italian senator should be admitted to accept speaking
engagements at the invitation of U.S. citizens.
   Greene held that the State Department had violated the 1952
Immigration and Nationality Act by denying the four visas simply
because the applicants were members of communist or
communist-affiliated organizations.
   The law authorizes the State Department to exclude aliens if a
consular official determines they would engage in activities during
a visit that ``would be prejudicial to the public interest'' or
endanger the safety of citizens.
   The State Department had invoked the 1952 law saying that visits
by Borge, former Italian senator Nino Pasti and Cuban officials
Leonor Rodriguez Lezcano and Olga Finlay would be prejudicial to
U.S. interests.
   Borge had been invited in 1983 to speak by members of Congress,
university professors and religious leaders, but the State
Department said his presence in the country would be ``highly
prejudicial to the foreign policy interests of the United States.''
   To keep Pasti out, the government cited his membership in the
World Peace Council, a group it considered controlled by the Soviet
government, and said his speech to a nuclear disarmament rally on
Boston would merely advance Soviet interests.
   The two Cuban women had been delegates to the U.N. Commission on
the Statute of Women and were invited by New York City to attend a
conference on the subject.
   The American Civil Liberties Union argued that to bar someone,
the law requires the State Department to determine that an alien's
proposed activities during the visit _ as opposed to political
affiliations _ would endanger U.S. interests.
   Greene originally sided with the government's application of the
law, but a divided panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here
reversed his 1984 ruling.
   The appellate court finding was upheld last fall on a 3-3 vote by
the Supreme Court, which did not issue an opinion.
   The appellate panel ordered Greene to determine if Congress had
acquiesced to a longstanding State Department practice of refusing
visas to individuals simply because their mere presence in the
country would hurt national interests.
   ``In the opinion of this court, the government has failed in this
task,'' Greene said in Tuesday's ruling. ``The court finds that the
evidence of administrative acquiesence is only imperceptibly more
weighty than it was when these cases were before the court in 1984.''
   Arthur Eisenberg, an ACLU lawyer in New York who worked on the
case, said Greene's ruling means ``you can't penalize individuals
for their associational activities, for their expression and for
their ideology.''
   ``We believe the statute looked to conduct,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0184 </DOCNO>
