<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     06-07 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Says One-Fourth Of Soviets Withdrawn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib of Afghanistan said Tuesday
more than 34,000 Soviet soldiers _ about 30 percent of the total _
have been withdrawn but the pace may be slowed if Pakistan continues
arming Afghan insurgents.
   ``If the Pakistani side does not ... end interference in the
internal affairs of Afghanistan from its territory, Afghanistan
reserves its right to react to this in a manner warranted,'' Najib,
who uses only one name, said in a speech to a special General
Assembly session on disarmament.
   He did not elaborate in the speech, but told a news conference
later: ``We want to visualize an optimistic situation ... but should
such violations acquire a permanent character ... in such a case we
would certainly renew our consideration on the schedule of
withdrawal and take proper reactions, together with the Soviet
Union.''
   Najib added, however, that his government intends to meet the
troop withdrawal schedule set by the Geneva agreement with Pakistan,
which requires all Soviet soldiers to be out within nine months of
May 15.
   In his first speech to the General Assembly, delivered in the
Dari language, Najib accused Pakistani authorities and Afghan
guerrillas of hindering the voluntary return of Afghan refugees to
their homeland.
   ``Such actions are sheer violations of the letter and spirit of
the Geneva accords and an affront to the United Nations,'' he said.
   ``They in Islamabad will be gravely mistaken should they think
that only one part of the Geneva accords, the return of the Soviet
troops, will be implemented and the other parties will not live up
to their commitments,'' Najib said.
   About 5.5 million people, roughly one-third of the population,
have fled Afghanistan in 10 years of civil war _ more than 3 million
to Pakistan and 2 million to Iran.
   The U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14 in Geneva requires
the Soviets to withdraw the more than 100,000 Red Army soldiers who
have been helping fight Moslem rebels in Afghanistan.
   Soviet officials also have threatened to slow the withdrawal.
   In a statement May 28 announcing that 10,000 soldiers had left
Afghanistan, the Soviet Foreign Ministry said the pullout could slow
if the United States kept delivering ``lavish supplies'' to the
rebels.
   Najib spoke to the General Assembly disarmament session for 30
minutes, devoting most of his remarks to the situation in
Afghanistan. He again called for national reconciliation and
establishment of a coalition government, including opposition forces.
   He said the death toll in the war was 243,900 soldiers and
civilians, including 35,700 women and 20,700 children. He said
77,700 people have been wounded.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a Communist
coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in
December 1979.
   The insurgents were not involved in the Geneva negotiations.
Leaders of the seven-party guerrilla coalition have said they would
ignore the agreement and continue fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     06-07 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Afghan Prime Minister Announces Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Afghan Prime Minister Mohammad
Hasan Sharq announced his 24-member Cabinet on Tuesday, state-run
Radio Kabul reported.
   Sharq, who replaced Sultan Ali Keshtmand on May 26, presented his
Cabinet to the National Assembly while President Najib was in New
York to address a United Nations special assembly on disarmament.
Before leaving, however, Najib issued a decree naming four vice
presidents to serve under Sharq.
   The time gap between Sharq's appointment and formation of a
government fueled speculation that Najib faced a deep split within
the governing People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan. Najib is
trying to hold together his Parcham faction, divided between loyalty
to him and to former President Babrak Karmal.
   Sharq's Cabinet returns Sayed Mohammad Gulabzoi, leader of the
party's opposition Khalq wing, to the Interior Ministry although
diplomatic reports said Najib has been trying to push Gulabzoi out
of the government.
   Afghanistan's negotiator at the Geneva peace talks, Abdul Wakil,
was returned as foreign minister. The talks resulted in the April 14
accord under which the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in
Afghanistan are to leave for home.
</TEXT>
