<HEAD>Toxic Wastes From Italy Dumped in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,400 tons of toxic waste from Italy
have been dumped in Lebanon, maritime authorities revealed Tuesday.
   The poisonous chemicals were shipped to Lebanon in containers and
barrels to be dumped in the Kesrouan coastal strip, about 20 miles
north of the capital city of Beirut, the authorities said.
   Some of the waste material was left in barrels in the Kesrouan
area, authorities said. Some reports say part of the shipment was
buried in that region.
   Raymond Farhat, director of the Marine Transport Authority, told
reporters investigations were under way to determine how the
chemicals entered Lebanon.
   The Lebanese Broadcasting Corp., a Christian TV station, said
Monday a Lebanese importer, identified only as Haddad, concluded an
agreement with an Italian chemical firm for bringing the waste into
Lebanon.
   Christian sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Lebanon's telecommunications authority intercepted a message from
the importer to his Italian agent demanding $500,000 for his
services.
   Interior Minister Abdullah Rassi said the waste was being
examined to see if it was radioactive.
   The reports came as the Syrian freighter Zanooria was docked in
Genoa, Italy, waiting to unload more than 2,000 tons of unidentified
industrial waste that first sailed from Italy last year. Various
countries refused to accept the wastes.
</TEXT>
