<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AntitrustGuidelines     06-07 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Antitrust Guidelines,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Issues New Guidelines for International Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Tuesday proposed new
antitrust guidelines for international operations that generally
give greater flexibility to U.S. and foreign firms to engage in
cooperative ventures.
   The draft would replace guidelines issued more than a decade ago,
which have become ``badly outdated'' due to changes in federal law,
developments in case law and changes in economic thinking, said
Charles Rule, assistant attorney general for the Justice
Department's antitrust division.
   The 1977 guidelines were ``very restrictive and hostile'' to
intellectual property licensing agreements, said Rule. Under the new
guidelines, such agreements won't be challenged unless it is found
they will drastically raise prices to consumers or unduly restrict
output.
   The 1977 guidelines provided an ``ill-defined analysis'' for what
types of joint ventures were permitted, said Rule, who contended
that the proposal provides a ``structured approach.''
   A summary of the draft guidelines says that joint research and
development, technology licensing restrictions and vertical
non-price distribution arrangements ``often are not
anti-competitive, and often substantially benefit U.S. consumers.''
   ``The most important thing the new guidelines do is provide
certainty and clarity in the law, which reduces the cost of
international transactions and increases the competitve ability of
U.S. firms and ultimately enhances the welfare of U.S. consumers,''
Rule said.
   The proposed guidelines contain 17 hypothetical cases of ways in
which the new policies would apply.
   The new guidelines say the Justice Department's top enforcement
priority in the antitrust area internationally remains the
prosecution of ``naked'' cartel arrangements among competitors
engaging in price-fixing and bid-rigging agreements.
</TEXT>
