<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People--MoodyBlues     06-07 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People--Moody Blues,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Moody Blues Say Retirement Not In Their Vocabulary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moody Blues say they have no plans to retire,
with their 13th album to be released next week and more than 50
million records sold worldwide since the band formed in the 1960s.
   ``We might go on forever,'' lead singer Justin Hayward said in an
interview Tuesday. ``There is no such thing as retirement as far as
we are concerned. After all, what would we do then?''
   The group's five members now are in their 40s. Their latest
album, ``Sur la Mer, (On the Sea)'' is due to be released Monday.
   ``This is not a job to us,'' said bass player John Lodge. ``It is
a way of life, and as soon as we retired from the way of life, it
would all be over for us. We may still be going at 80 _ well, why
stop at 80?''
   The Moody Blues began their career in Birmingham in 1964, quickly
rising to fame with hits like ``Nights in White Satin,'' which
entered the pop charts three times and spent 33 weeks there. ``Go
Now'' was the No. 1 single in Britain in December 1964.
</TEXT>
