<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PoliticalPrisoners     06-07 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Prisoners,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spectators Scuffle With Officer, Get Arrested Outside Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two spectators at a court hearing on conditions
at a federal prison in Kentucky were held Tuesday on charges they
assaulted a U.S. marshal.
   The two men, believed to be supporters of a prisoner who
testified at the hearing, were arrested after they scuffled with a
deputy U.S. marshal outside the courtroom of U.S. District Judge
Barrington Parker, according to federal law enforcement authorities.
   The incident occurred while Parker was conducting a hearing on a
lawsuit challenging conditions at a high-security isolation unit for
a half-dozen women prisoners at the Federal Correctional Institution
in Lexington, Ky.
   Parker had heard testimony about prison conditions from prisoner
Susan Rosenberg, identified by law enforcement officials as a
left-wing terrorist who is serving a 58-year prison term for
possessing 600 pounds of weapons and explosives.
   Ms. Rosenberg is among seven people recently indicted for placing
a bomb that exploded in the U.S. Capitol in 1983.
   One of the two men in police custody following the hallway
scuffle had refused to stand up when the judge returned from an
afternoon recess, said authorities.
   When asked by Parker why he had not stood up, the man said he did
not respect the authority of the court.
   Authorities said Deputy U.S. Marshal William Pickett was jumped
from behind while escorting the man down a hallway outside Parker's
courtroom.
   Pickett was then punched by the man he was escorting before he
and other courthouse guards subdued his attackers, authorities said.
   The two men, identified only as John Heild and B. Wardlaw, were
being held in the city police lockup Tuesday night on charges they
assaulted a marshal, said authorities, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Ms. Rosenberg and two other inmates, Sylvia Brown and Silvia
Baraldini, charge in the lawsuit brought by the American Civil
Liberties Union that they are being held in the Lexington isolation
unit because of their political beliefs.
   Baraldini was convicted of racketeering and conspiracy in aiding
a bungled $1.6 million robbery of a Brink's armored car in Nyack,
N.Y., that left a guard and two police officers dead in 1981.
   At the unit in Lexington, guards escort the prisoners to and from
the locked cellblock. Prisoners' hands and feet are shackled every
time they leave the unit, Ms. Rosenberg said.
   Ms. Rosenberg, who was in the general populations of two other
federal prisons, said authorities told her she was placed in the
unit in October, 1986 because she was considered a terrorist.
   ``They said I had a one-way ticket,'' she told Parker.
   ``The isolation and the control and the dependency has taken away
any semblance of any kind of self-determination about my life,'' Ms.
Rosenberg said. ``Nobody should have that happen to them, no matter
what they've been convicted of. That's punishment on punishment.''
   ``I really think that in prison you can't control all aspects of
your life,'' Ms. Rosenberg said. ``But when you can't control
anything at any level, that's out of your hands, the frustration is
really unbearable.''
   Ms. Rosenberg said the isolation and strict control by guards has
inflicted severe emotional and psychological stress.
   ``Trying to suppress the anger asks an enormous amount of energy,
an enormous amount of self-control and it's making me sick,'' she
said.
   Dr. William Logan, a psychiatrist hired by the government to
inspect the prison, testified that he found no evidence that
conditions had caused any unusual emotional or psychological damage.
But Logan said his findings were based only on observations and
conversations with prison doctors because the prisoners refused to
talk to him.
   Federal authorities contend that the extra security is required
to protect the facility from terrorist attack. They said they plan
to move the unit to a prison in Mariana, Fla., in July.
   J. Michael Quinlan, director of the Bureau of Prisons, in a 1987
letter to the House Judiciary Committee, denied that inmates are
sent to the unit because of political beliefs.
   But affiliation with groups that use violence in ``attempts to
disrupt or overthrow the government of the United States, or whose
published ideology includes advocating law violations in order to
`free' prisoners is a factor,'' he said.
   Last weekend, Lynette Alice ``Squeaky'' Fromme, convicted of
trying to shoot President Ford on Sept 5, 1975 in Sacramento,
Calif., was transferred to the unit last weekend, authorities said.
</TEXT>
