<2ND_LINE>AM-Airfield Rampage,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Shot By Authorities During Rampage at Airfield</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man went on a rampage Tuesday in a road
grader and badly damaged at least three planes at the airport here
before he was shot by police and sheriff's deputies, authorities
said.
   The man, identified as Randy LaComb of Anaheim, was shot several
times below the waist, said Jim Bryant, spokesman for the San
Bernardino County Sheriff's Department.
   No other injuries were reported.
   LaComb, 37, was airlifted to San Bernardino County Hospital where
he was listed in stable condition, Bryant said.
   Authorities said he was charged with assault with a deadly weapon.
   Police and sheriff's deputies on the ground and a sheriff's
deputy in a helicopter opened fire on the man after he ran into the
side of Flight Craft, a business that gives flight lessons and
refuels planes at the airport. Chino is located about 40 miles east
of Los Angeles.
   LaComb is a construction worker in the area and had access to the
grader, but he took it out of the authorized area on his day off,
another sheriff's spokesman said.
   The chase began in the Chino Hills area, about six miles west of
the airport, after the sheriff's station received a complaint at
9:41 a.m. that someone was operating a road grader in an erratic
manner, Bryant said.
   Chino police detectives began chasing the grader during the
29-minute drive to the airport, during which several people were
nearly hit, he said.
   During the five-minute rampage at the airport, LaComb reportedly
struck three small airplanes and barely missed several people on the
ground.
   The chase ended when the grader's front end was jammed into
Flight Craft's hangar. Police officers and sheriff's deputies opened
fire on the man when he attempted to drive away from the hangar,
Bryant said.
   Jett Reeves, who said he was in Flight Craft's hangar at Chino
Airport when the incident occurred, estimated that LaComb came
within 50 yards of hitting the business's fuel tanks.
   ``It almost looked like the guy in there was laughing,'' Reeves
said. ``He sure looked happy.''
</TEXT>
