<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MigrantFatals     06-07 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Migrant Fatals,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Van Carrying 18 Migrants Crashes; Two Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESCOTT, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A van with 18 migrant workers flipped over
after blowing a tire Tuesday, crushing two men to death and injuring
at least a dozen others who were tossed onto Interstate 30,
authorities said.
   One of the men, Moises Ramirez, 18, of Guanajuato, Mexico, said
he heard ``a sound like a rushing tornado, and then the van lost
control, spinning around and turning many times.''
   ``It was a bad scene,'' said Arkansas State Police Cpl. Bobby
Carlton. ``There were bodies laying 75 to 100 feet along the
shoulder of the interstate.''
   The van's occupants were either Mexicans or Mexican-Americans
from Arkansas and Texas en route to a farm north of Prescott,
Carlton said.
   Ramirez, who suffered a fractured arm, said all the workers had
proper legal documents to work in the United States.
   The workers lived on property near Fouke owned by W.H. Lineberry,
who said he heard the van was overloaded because another vehicle in
which some of the men were riding broke down.
   The Chevrolet van has a recommended maximum capacity of 12,
Carlton said.
</TEXT>
