<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 2200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CamarenaTorture     06-07 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Camarena Torture,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain DEA Agent Pleaded With Captors to End Beatings, Tapes Reveal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal drug agent pleaded with his Mexican
abductors to stop beating him during interrogation before he was
murdered, according to transcripts of tape recordings filed in
federal court.
   Transcripts of two tapes obtained by Mexican authorites from the
home of reputed drug kingpin Ernesto Fonseca-Carrillo were filed
Monday in U.S. District Court as part of the prosecution of three of
the nine men indicted in the murder of Enrique Camarena.
   Camarena, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent, was
kidnaped Feb. 7, 1985 as he left the U.S. Consulate in Guadalajara.
Several weeks later his body and that of his pilot, Alfredo
Zavala-Avelar, who was kidnapped separately, were found on a remote
ranch 70 miles away. Camarena had been severely beaten.
   U.S. officials have said Camarena was kidnapped shortly after he
and other agents uncovered a drug trafficking operation run by
Rafael Caro-Quintero, who along with Fonseca-Carrillo was one of
Mexico's biggest drug kingpins.
   Camarena moans and complains of pains and injuries on the tapes.
Federal prosecutors say they believe the recorder was turned off
during beatings.
   The agent says at one point that he has ``sharp pains'' all over
his body and asks his captors: ``Couldn't I ask you to have my ribs
bandaged, please?''
   Affidavits about autopsy reports, which also were filed, state
that Camarena's jaw was broken in several places and his head was
shattered ``like an eggshell.''
   According to documents filed in court, federal prosecutors
believe that Sergio Espino-Verdin, a former Mexican police sergeant,
interrogated Camarena for two days at a large estate owned by
Fonseca-Carrillo outside Guadalajara.
   Prosecutors said the voices of Espino-Verdin and Caro-Quintero
have been identified on the tape.
   The transcript reveals that Camarena told his captors the DEA
knew the whereabouts of Fonseca-Carrillo and Caro-Quintero but that
U.S. agents in Guadalajara were not allowed to carry weapons and so
didn't conduct surveillance of the two men.
   ``To conduct surveillance over there at the house, I have never,
sir ... I am afraid,'' Camarena said.
   ``I did not want trouble. I just wanted to get out of here,'' he
said, referring to his transfer back to the United States that was
pending at the time.
   Camarena may have been attempting to mislead his abductors by
asserting that agents don't carry guns, said Ralph Lockridge, a DEA
spokesman in Los Angeles. Local commanders can authorize agents to
carry weapons, he said.
   ``He was just throwing out something that was wrong,'' Lockridge
said.
   Camarena mentions confidential information at times, indicating
that the tapes are authentic, according to affidavits of DEA agents
who worked with him. That information includes a reference to
complaints about the Guadalajara office from DEA headquarters.
   ``I'm telling you that we are being reprimanded from Washington
because, according to them, we are not working here,'' Camarena
says. ``As I say, well, who is going to do the work if they have one
unarmed?''
   Camarena gave only skimpy information about DEA informants,
causing the interrogator to snap: ``Who is it that put the finger on
Rafael? Don't tell me about your problems; speak of the information
you can give us, you can provide us to finish with this bunch of
jerks....''
   ``Yes, sir. What more can I tell you, sir?'' Camarena says in a
voice described in the transcript as ``very weak.''
   Defense motions have challenged the validity of the tapes, saying
they contain an unexplained burst of music and clicking sounds that
suggest tampering or fabrication.
   Raul Lopez-Alvarez, 28, Jesus Felix-Gutierrez, 38, and Rene
Martin Verdugo-Urquidez, 36, are scheduled to go on trial in
District Court here later this month. All have denied involvement in
the Camarena case.
   Caro-Quintero and Fonseca-Carrillo are in custody in Mexico City
and extradition proceedings are stalled. The other indicted men are
not in custody.
</TEXT>
