<2ND_LINE>AM-NJ Primary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0833,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NJ Voters Chose Lautenberg in Democratic Senate Primary, Payne in
House Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Lautenberg quote, vote
totals in Senate, 10th District; picks up 6th graf: `Third District
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg easily won
his party's backing Tuesday to run for re-election against
Republican Peter Dawkins, and Newark Democrats gave city councilman
Donald M. Payne a chance to become New Jersey's first black in
Congress.
   In the presidential primary, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
coasted to victory over Jesse Jackson for most of the 109 Democratic
delegates at stake. On the GOP side, Vice President George Bush was
unopposed for 64 delegates.
   Lautenberg, 64, overwhelmed primary opponents Elnardo Webster, a
state Corrections Department official who linked his campaign with
Jackson's presidential bid, and Harold Young, a theology student who
describes himself as a ``conservative radical Democrat.''
   ``I'm expecting a good vigorous race, and we are prepared to do
battle, although that may be the wrong terminology since I am going
against a general,'' Lautenberg said, referring to Dawkins' rank at
retirement from the U.S. Army.
   With 52 percent of the vote counted, or 3,028 of 5,825 precincts
reporting, Lautenberg had 161,441 votes, or 79.6 percent; Webster
had 24,494 votes, or 12.1 percent; and Young had 16,834 votes, or
8.3 percent.
   Democrats in the 10th Congressional District chose Payne over his
fellow Newark city councilman Ralph Grant to run against the GOP's
Michael Webb for the seat held by Rep. Peter Rodino, retiring after
40 years in the House.
   With 74 of 328 precincts, or 23 percent, reporting, Payne had
8,326 votes, or 76 percent, to 2,610 votes, or 24 percent, for Grant.
</TEXT>
