<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDSCommission 2ndLd-Writethru a0855 06-07 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Commission, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0855,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Tentatively Endorses Recommendations of its Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 6 grafs after 13th graf pvs bgng, `However, other,'
to
UPDATE with some of the recommendations; ADDS 2 grafs of background
on AIDS, the number of people who have gotten the disease, the
number who have died</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House AIDS commission gave its
tentative endorsement Tuesday night to the bulk of the 579
recommendations the panel's chairman wants to put in a report to
President Reagan later this month.
   In releasing his recommendations last week, retired Navy Adm.
James D. Watkins portrayed most of them as reflecting what he read
as the consensus of the 13-member committee.
   That turned out to be true during an 11-hour meeting as the
commissioners worked through the report page-by-page, making only
minor changes in wording and organization.
   Watkins' had predicted correctly that his final chapter calling
for legislation to vest sweeping new powers in the surgeon general _
currently Dr. C. Everett Koop _ would prove controversial.
   Watkins said Reagan should immediately proclaim AIDS a national
emergency as soon as legislation is passed setting up a new
framework within the government health bureaucracy to put the
surgeon general in charge of dealing with it.
   Although the commission did not reject Watkins' suggestions
outright, there was a sharp exchange of differences between the
chairman and commissioner William B. Walsh and it was clear Watkins
does not have the broad backing of the panel on his proposed shift
of power to the surgeon general.
   The issue of what, if anything, to recommend in the way of
administrative changes to deal with AIDS as well as future epidemics
was left up in the air with the commissioners agreeing to submit
their thoughts in writing for the panel's staff to synthesize and
present for further consideration at the final working session next
Thursday and Friday.
   The final report is due June 24 at the White House and it became
clear after Tuesday's session that it will essentially track
Watkin's recommendations _ including his call for strong federal
legislation to protect people with the AIDS virus from
discrimination.
   Watkins told fellow commissioners he has received letters from
``both sides of the aisle'' that leads him to believe ``there is a
feeling of momentum in Congress'' for passage of such legislation
despite administration opposition.
   ``It is something that can be done in this session of Congress,''
he said. ``I don't know that it will be.''
   Walsh had expressed some concern about the anti-discrimination
recommendation in early discussions, saying it ``would not be
fruitful and would not be fair'' to make a specific recommendation
about AIDS discrimination.
   ``If we're going to make it, we should expand it to cover not
just AIDS, but all diseases,'' said Walsh, the director of Project
HOPE, a private international health delivery organization.
   However, other commissioners noted that the recommendation is for
a law that spells out that people with the AIDS virus are to be
treated just like people with any other handicapping disease _ no
worse, no better.
   Watkins said the anti-discrimination recommendation should be the
No. 1 priority in the final report's introductory chapter.
   Among the other Watkins recommendations the panel agreed to
emphasize at the forefront of the final report:
   _That all of those infected with the AIDS virus _ an estimated
1.5 million Americans compared with fewer than 70,000 actually
diagnosed with the full-blown illness _ should be considered part of
the epidemic.
   _That intravenous drug abuse is a national emergency that must be
successfully dealt with if the AIDS epidemic is to be curtailed.
   _That the fight against the disease will require resources of
private as well as government resources.
   _That compassion for those with AIDS should be empasized at all
levels.
   Tuesday's marathon session was designed to reach as much
consensus as possible. Any lingering differences over final wording
will be resolved by votes, if necessary, at next week's sessions.
   Watkins assured panel members there would be ample time for
debate, promising to run the planned Thursday-Friday session into
the weekend if necessary.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus most
often is spread through close contact with blood, blood products or
semen from infected persons. Its chief victims have been homosexual
men and intravenous drug users.
   As of June 6, AIDS had been diagnosed in 64,506 Americans, of
whom more than half, or 36,255 have died since June 1981, according
to the federal Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to have
recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
