<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0876 06-07 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0876,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras And Government Work Toward Lasting Truce</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf ``The Resistnance...'' to
UPDATE with comment from rebel leader. Pickup 8th graf pvs ``The
talks...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government and
U.S.-backed rebels held daylong talks Tuesday on a government
proposal for democratic reform in exchange for rebel disarmament.
   The fourth round of peace talks resumed Tuesday in a climate of
mutual distrust, but both sides said they might be nearing agreement
after more than six years of war.
   Information Minister Manuel Espinoza reported after the talks
adjourned at 7 p.m. (5 p.m. EDT) Tuesday until 9 a.m. Wednesday,
``We have made substantial advances.''
   A representative of the leftist government, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said earlier that the government proposal
bows to almost all the rebel demands for democratic reforms.
   The rebels, known as Contras, described the proposal as vague but
said it raised hopes for an agreement.
   Contra negotiator Alfredo Cesar said: ``The Nicaraguan Resistance
is here with a political decision to sign a definite agreement for
permanent and lasting peace in Nicaragua if the government shows its
political commitment to make the democratic reforms in this country
to achieve that lasting peace.''
   The Resistance is the Contras' umbrella organization.
   Bosco Mamatoros, spokesman for the rebels, told reporters after
the meeting ended ``there were advances in the discussion on themes
of a substantial character,'' but said political reform remained
``the biggest problem in the discussions.''
   He charged that the government was ``using the dialogue to gain
time. They have to demonstrate the opposite to us.''
   The talks are taking place amid a temporary truce enacted March
21. The rebels have extended the truce until Thursday, and the
government has declared a unilateral cease-fire until the end of
June. Each side accuses the other of violations.
   The government proposal promises press freedom, the right to
strike, electoral reforms, an end to Sandinista control of the army
and freedom for political prisoners.
   The proposal offers the Contras a role in talks begun late last
year with opposition political parties. The so-called national
dialogue has made little headway. On April 26, the opposition
parties suspended the talks pending settlement of a workers' strike.
   The scars and bitterness of the civil war were dramatized Tuesday
in dramatic full-page ads by the Mothers Committee of Heroes and
Martyrs in the two pro-government newspapers. The committee is
comprised of mothers whose children have died in the war.
   The ad in the Barricada newspaper showed pictures of wounded
children along with rebel commander Col. Enrique Bermudez. ``We
don't want amnesty for criminals,'' it said.
   The ad in El Nuevo Diario showed women carrying a coffin, a child
leaning on a cross and a bullet-riddled body. ``We won't forget,''
it said. ``Our pain calls for justice.''
   The Sandinistas have called for disarmament of the rebels to be
completed by September while the Contras have proposed January. The
Contras say they will not lay down arms until the nation of 3
million people is a democracy. The Sandinistas say it already is.
   Vice President Sergio Ramirez said Monday night the Contras
should accept the Sandinista proposals because ``at best, within a
month they will not have the capacity to negotiate more.''
   U.S. military aid to the rebels ended on Feb. 26. Three weeks
later, the rebels signed a temporary cease-fire and began talks on a
permanent peace with the Sandinistas. The Contras are also plagued
by deep divisions within their ranks.
   The Sandinistas, who get military and economic aid from the
Soviet bloc, also have compelling reasons for ending a war that has
claimed 26,000 lives.
   The Nicaraguan economy is a shambles and the government faces
widespread public dissatisfaction over chronic shortages and its
failure to deliver on promises made when it took power in July 1979.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
expressed hope that the talks would be productive and that the
Sandinistas would negotiate in good faith.
   ``The key issue is the Sandinistas' willingness to democratize,''
Ms. Oakley said. ``We're hopeful, but we note that in recent weeks
the Sandinistas have increased repression of the internal
opposition.''
</TEXT>
