<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChildPreachers     06-07 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Preachers,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street-Preaching Children Promoted To Next Grade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM FOREMAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite missing several weeks of school
because of suspensions, three street preaching children were
promoted to the next grade, their father said Tuesday.
   The Strode children, Duffey, Matthew and Pepper, were suspended
numerous times because they refused to proceed into the Eastfield
Elementary School building when they arrived on school property each
morning. Instead, the three children began preaching. Marion, N.C.,
school officials have stressed that the suspensions resulted not
from the preaching, but from failure to adhere to school rules.
   Their father, David Strode, said in a telephone interview that
McDowell County school officials notified him Tuesday afternoon that
his children had passed. Matthew will be in the first grade, Pepper
moves to the second grade and Duffey will go to the sixth grade.
   The children took comprehensive tests to complete the school
year. School officials would not release the test results, nor would
they say whether the children were promoted to their respective next
grades.
   Strode, who is building a house in another school district, said
the preaching will stop if the local schools end their teaching of
the theory of evolution.
   ``We don't think people who think Jesus Christ was a liar should
be teaching our children in our schools, unless people have
liberties the other way,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, residents of Marion are circulating a petition asking
Strode to either keep his children from preaching in the schoolyard
or to leave the town.
   ``If you're going to be a preacher, public opinion can't bother
you,'' Strode said.
</TEXT>
