<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Hearing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0734,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Brawley To Seek Sanctuary In Church</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 10-11 ``But New'' with two grafs to UPDATE with
police saying ``sanctuary'' is decided on a case-by-case basis.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman sentenced to jail for refusing to testify
about her daughter's claim that she was the victim of a racist
attack will seek sanctuary in a church and dare authorities to
arrest her there, her lawyers said Tuesday.
   ``The question would be whether this government can respect the
right of the black church, because if it cannot we are prepared
tomorrow and the day after that to put our lives on the line,'' said
attorney Alton Maddox Jr.
   ``Before you put a hand on Glenda Brawley, you will come through
me. Please have a bullet designated for me,'' he said.
   Mrs. Brawley's daughter Tawana, 16, has said she was abducted and
assaulted last November in Wappingers Falls, 95 miles north of New
York City, by six white men, including one who flashed a police-like
badge.
   But she and her family have refused to cooperate with
investigators, claiming local and state officials are engaged in a
racially motivated cover-up.
   Mrs. Brawley, 33, was sentenced to 30 days in jail Monday for
defying a grand jury subpoena to testify, but upon the urging of
state Attorney General Robert Abrams she was given one more chance _
an opportunity Wednesday to tell a judge why she had refused to
cooperate.
   But Maddox insisted at a news conference that Mrs. Brawley would
not appear Wednesday.
   ``Glenda Brawley will be seeking relief before a higher
authority, she will be putting her life in God's hands,'' he said.
   Neither Maddox nor others at the news conference would say what
church would offer Mrs. Brawley asylum. They insisted authorities
had no right to enter a church to arrest her.
   But Sgt. John Clifford, a spokesman for the New York Police
Department, said the decision to arrest people who request sanctuary
privileges is decided on a case-by-case basis. ``There's no hard and
fast rule,'' he said.
   Police are allowed to arrest suspects who run into a church, the
spokesman said. However, if the suspect requests refuge and is
granted sanctuary by the pastor, police have to obtain a search
warrant to make an arrest or negotiate with the parties involved,
Clifford said.
   Attorney C. Vernon Mason reiterated the theme of the Brawleys and
their advisers _ ``It is clear we cannot get justice for Tawana
Brawley.''
   He said authorities had ``done everything possible to blame the
victim even more. How ludicrous it is for the nation to see that the
only person arrested in this case is the mother of a black rape
victim. People should be outraged.''
   Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28, four days after she had
disappeared. She was lying dazed in a plastic bag in a road in
Wappingers Falls. Her hair had been shorn, animal excrement had been
smeared on her body and racial epithets had been scrawled on her
torso.
   Abrams said unless Miss Brawley's family cooperates soon, the
state's investigation into the incident will end without resolution.
</TEXT>
