<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Students     06-07 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Students,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Warn Students Not to Demonstrate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City authorities tried to head off a planned
pro-democracy march by university students on Wednesday by warning
that demonstrations without approval are illegal. They urged
students to ``keep a sober mind.''
   In front-page editorials, major official dailies accused some
student leaders of being agitators trying to negate China's reforms
and appealed to students to avoid the ``methods of anarchy.''
   The planned Wednesday afternoon march to Tiananmen Square, the
symbolic political center of China, would be the first major
political protest by students since the winter of 1986-1987.
Nationwide student unrest then led to a conservative backlash
against Western liberal ideas.
   Hu Yaobang was removed as Communist Party chief for failing to
stem the pro-democracy movement. The party purged several outspoken
political thinkers.
   More than 1,000 students rallied from Tuesday night into early
Wednesday at Beijing University, China's leading university, to
voice demands for greater democracy, more press freedom, better
living conditions for intellectuals and better campus security.
   The turmoil was prompted by the June 2 slaying of a university
student in an off-campus brawl. Six non-students were arrested in
the death.
   The killing brought to the surface student unhappiness over poor
living conditions on campus and bleak economic prospects after
graduation for the nation's low-paid intellectuals.
   Hundreds have gathered on the campus in the evenings for
impromptu debates on what broader lessons are to be learned from the
incident.
   Dozens of posters have gone up demanding democracy, a free press,
an end to government corruption and petty bureaucracy and greater
respect and higher salaries for intellectuals.
   In an announcement Wednesday, the Beijing municipal government
denounced a ``handful of people with ulterior motives who have taken
the opportunity of this criminal case (the murder) to concoct rumors
and slander the reform and open policy in violation of the law, and
sabotaging political stability and unity.''
   It reminded students that all demonstrations without previous
approval from police are illegal. That regulation was imposed after
the 1986-87 disturbances.
</TEXT>
