<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Classof'38 Adv19-4Takes   06-07 1137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Class of '38, Adv 19-4 Takes,1164</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ They came to college during the Great Depression.
They graduated, worked hard and shaped fulfilling lives. When the
University of North Carolina's class of '38 held its 50th reunion
recently, reporter Sid Moody _ who had chronicled their 25th in 1963
_ returned to round out their passage through five eventful decades.
Their story, as he presents it, is a memorable yearbook of half a
century of history as ordinary Americans lived it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This spring, in the autumn of their
time, they returned to where they once had been young.
   ``Red clay people from a red clay state,'' said one in the class
of 1938 at the University of North Carolina.
   Once, maybe. Not now.
   Thunderheads darkened the evening sky that June 7, 1938 when they
were given a diploma in one hand, a Bible in the other. Unforeseen
winds were to strew them across the globe in a half-century of
bearing witness.
   Depression. Three wars _ a victory, a standoff and a defeat _
burying their loss from each. The Bomb. Ike. JFK. Watergate. Heart
transplants. The Bomb. 747s. TV. The '60s. The Bomb. LSD. PCs. PCBs.
The Bomb.
   Once poor, they raised families in a flood tide of prosperity.
And the Japanese cars some drove back to their 50th reunion gave a
hint, perhaps, of its ebb. What their nation has seen and become,
they have seen and become.
   They are a yearbook of their times.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Hold up your head and be yourself.''
   _ From ``Be Yourself,'' by Joe Patterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Flanner Patterson Jr.: Permanent class president ...
Harvard med school ... combat surgeon in Okinawa. Illness ended
surgical career. Studied three years in mid-life while raising four
children to become anesthesiologist. Won't retire. Instead, travels
the country and beyond usually with wife, Alice, and Lab, Beau, in
camper surveying hospitals for accreditation. ``Something I've
learned which Alice knew all along: If you don't have a goal even at
our age, maybe especially at our age, life can be difficult.''
   During the war in Vietnam, Joe ``Pat'' was on the faculty at UNC
School of Medicine. In his quiet way he proposed that his fellow
doctors should do something to help the children maimed by that
conflict. The majority demurred. Too political.
   ``If you're so concerned about those kids,'' said one. ``why
don't you go over there yourself, Joe?'' A lifetime in medicine had
taught Joe Patterson, son of a doctor, grandson of a U.S. senator,
this: ``A good doctor is a person who with a clear mind and proper
training cares for his patients to the best of his ability in a
humane way.''
   So he went to Vietnam to heal children. Twice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Human rights _ freedom rights _ education's tallest heights.''
   _ From ``Dr. Frank,'' by Joe Patterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Frank Porter Graham: President University of North Carolina
1931-49. Died 1971.
   Dr. Frank is remembered by his former students of '38 as the best
of men in the worst of times. He was a focus of rectitude and
example when a quarter of the U.S. work force was unemployed; when
`Hoover carts,' wagons with rubber tires, replaced too-expensive tin
lizzies; when cotton was 7.9 cents a pound and the new minimum wage
a quarter; when a third of his 3,207 students worked their way
through raking leaves, stoking furnaces to meet an average of
$406.50 in annual fees. Hang on, he would urge his students at his
Sunday open house, I'll go to Washington to get the money.
   The UNC of the '30s strikes a bittersweet, simpler nostalgia
today. In 1938 there was a waiting line for the 100 copies of ``Gone
With the Wind'' on loan at the library. For a dime you could see
Clark Gable, Myrna Loy and Spencer Tracy at the movies in ``Test
Pilot.'' ``Our Town,'' Thornton Wilder's small-town epic, won the
Pulitzer for drama.
   Harsh reality was buried under corsages, crepe ribbons and ball
gowns as the class of '38 danced in the transformed field house, The
Tin Can, to Kay Kayser or the Dorsey brothers. Seventy-nine of 89
coeds said they'd go no farther than a goodnight kiss.
   But there were harbingers, unsuspected, among the dogwood. In
Great Britain TV signals had been beamed 220 miles. In Germany, Otto
Hahn and Fritz Strassman were about to split an atom. Scientists at
Oxford were about to investigate why a mold called penicillium
seemed to kill bacteria.
   War? Twenty-two at that commencement would die in World War II.
But in 1938 a majority of the students approved Neville
Chamberlain's appeasement of Hitler. In a poll, 599 of 974 said they
would fight only if the United States were invaded. The Army Air
Corps had only 13 of the B-17s that Red Benton, awaiting his diploma
alphabetically down front, would one day fly over a beach in
Normandy named Omaha. Behind him tennis star Ramsay Potts, who had
been repulsed by Hitler's ``Mein Kampf,'' would one day interrogate
the author's deputy, Hermann Goering, who ``cowered like an animal.''
   America had not then learned war, not even Dr. Frank. When Nick
Read planned a peace strike, the president, a pacifist, said he'd
ring the bell emptying the classrooms. ``Then it wouldn't be a
strike,'' Read protested. ``It'd be a better strike,'' said Dr.
Frank and rang the bell.
   But Dr. Frank knew other things. When a faculty member dined with
a black radical in Raleigh, some on the all-white campus called for
his dismissal.
   ``If a professor has to go on a charge of eating with another
human being, then I will go first,'' said Frank Porter Graham,
doctor of philosophy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We inherited a lemon and made lemonade.'' _ Wade Cavin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Wade Leonard Cavin: Family lost farm to Depression ... arrived
UNC with $1.05 in pocket: three Indian head pennies, two Lincolns,
the rest silver coins, none a quarter ... lived under football
stadium, later $5-a-month attic...raked leaves, cut grass, stoked
furnaces to send home $5 to $10 a month to help three sisters
through business course ... now owns lucrative business machine
dealership ... two-term mayor of Durham ... jogger 53 years ...
married secretary of prospective employer, who was only hiring Phi
Betas ... urged boss to take a chance on poor boy who worked way
through ... named a son for Winston Churchill ... drives Jeep
Wagoneer, wife Chevy, instead of Cadillacs once dreamed of ...
``Material things are not as important as I once thought.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
