<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-07 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Inch Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished lower against the yen in
trading in Tokyo today, while stocks fell back modestly from their
record-high close the previous day.
   The dollar closed at 125.77 yen, down 0.30 yen from Monday's
finish. It opened the day at 125.75 yen and moved in narrow range
between 125.60 and 125.85 yen.
   ``The trading was relatively quiet without incentives to direct
the market, and the dollar remained stable throughout the day,''
said a foreign exchange dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues closed at 27,967.32, down 28.92 points, or 0.1 percent.
   On Monday, the stock market's key indicator rose 89.76 points and
closed at an all-time high of 27,996.24 points.
   ``The Nikkei index is down a little, but issues such as large
capitals, including shipbuilding and steel, continued to attract
buying interest, raising the trading volume,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama
of Nikko Securities.
   The market remained strong without any fear among investors that
prices were rising too high, he said.
   Some other traders, however, attributed the drop in the Nikkei
index to a sense among some participants that the market was
overheating, leading them to stay on the sidelines.
   The Nikkei index closed the morning session at 28,034.61 points,
making today the second consecutive day it went above 28,000 at the
end of the morning session, only to fall back in afternoon trading.
   Declining issues included automobiles and machineries. Advancers
included steels, cements and high-tech issues.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at a heavy 2.2 billion
shares, up from 1.6 billion shares Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
