<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     06-07 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off 8.7 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the London stock exchange moved lower
Tuesday as the market pulled back from Monday's 13.5-point advance.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks
was off 8.7 points, or 0.5 percent at 1,824.0 at midday. Trading
volume was a modest 305.8 million shares, compared with 192.5
million shares the same time Monday.
   ``There isn't enough in this market to shove London prices
further forward at this stage,'' said Jeffrey Thompson, chief equity
strategist at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
   Market players were still dubious that last week's 114.86-point
surge on Wall Street could be sustained. That was the biggest point
gain on record for a calendar week.
   Monday's 3.91-point rise in the Dow Jones industrial average to
2,075.21 didn't convince many skeptics.
   ``There are a lot of people who feel that Wall Street's rise last
week was fairly frothy and premature,'' another equity analyst said,
adding that most European equity markets have adopted a wait-and-see
attitude in order to get a better handle on the outlook for
inflation and interest rate movements.
   Thompson said the London exchange remains highly vulnerable to
Wall Street's movements.
   ``Sentiment is such that if Wall Street gets knocked on the head
at any stage, so could we get bumped at any time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
