<DOCNO> AP880607-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0918EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Autos-Japan     06-07 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Autos-Japan,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Exports to U.S. Fall 20 Percent in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exports of Japanese cars and trucks to the United
States fell a steep 20.3 percent in April, the Japan Automotive
Manufacturers Association said.
   The association attributed the decline to a drop in sales of
Japanese models and an increase in U.S. production by Japanese
automakers.
   JAMA said Japanese automakers sent 274,162 cars and trucks to the
United States in April, the latest month for which statistics are
available. That was down from 344,068 in the same month last year.
   For the first four months of 1988, combined car and truck exports
are down 14.5 percent from the comparable period in 1987.
   While Japanese exports have fallen, the Big Three domestic
automakers increased their market share. General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have picked up a combined 3.2 points of
market share in the car and truck market so far this year.
   The decline in the value of the U.S. dollar versus the Japanese
yen has forced Japanese automakers to raise prices to the point
where many Japanese vehicles are more expensive than comparable
American-made vehicles.
   Japanese automakers began May with a 66-day supply of cars and
trucks in the United States, up from a 58-day supply at the same
time last year, according to the industry statistical journal Ward's
Automotive Reports.
</TEXT>
