<2ND_LINE>PM-Foley's Layoffs,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foley's Laying Off 5 Percent of Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foley's Department Stores is laying off 5 percent
of its system-wide work force, some 800 employees, in an effort to
pare costs, company officials said.
   Foley's, taken over last month by May Department Stores Co., said
Monday the layoffs will affect executives as well as hourly workers.
   ``It's an attempt to get our operating costs down,'' said Dan
Hagan, Foley's vice president of public affairs.
   Foley's, which has 39 stores in Texas, Arizona, New Mexico and
Oklahoma, employs about 16,000 workers.
   May, the nation's seventh-largest retailer, bought Foley's and 18
Filene's stores from Federated Department Stores Inc. last month
after Campeau Corp. took control of Federated.
   Linda Kristiansen, a retailing analyst with the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said May is known for tough expense
controls.
   ``Senior management is closely involved with the divisions,'' she
said.
   May spokesman Jim Abrams has said May does not plan to close any
Foley's stores.
   Last year, Foley's merged with another Federated store,
Sanger-Harris of Dallas, resulting in the loss of 200 workers in
Houston and Dallas.
</TEXT>
