<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Beech-Nut     06-07 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Beech-Nut,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Beech-Nut President Seeks Probation as Alternative to Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for the former president of Beech-Nut
Nutrition Corp., who was convicted of distributing phony apple
juice, have asked that their client be ordered to speak to business
students about his mistakes as an alternative to a prison term.
   Niels Hoyvald was found guilty Feb. 17 of 351 counts of violating
the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carries a
possible three-year prison term and a $10,000 fine.
   Hoyvald and a co-defendant, former Beech-Nut Vice President John
Lavery, are scheduled to be sentenced Friday in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn. Lavery was found guilty of 429 counts of violating the
same act, along with 18 counts of mail fraud and one count of
conspiracy.
   Hoyvald's attorneys said in a presentencing memorandum,
``Business students undoubtedly hear this principle regularly in
their ethics classes. But the impact of the message would be far
clearer coming from Niels Hoyvald, whose career has been shattered
because he did not heed it, than it could ever be coming from a
textbook or a professor.''
   Thomas Roche, the lead prosecutor in the case, said the
government's sentencing recommendations would be made public at the
sentencing hearing. He declined comment on the memorandum.
   Hoyvald, president and chief executive officer of Beech-Nut from
April 1981 until shortly before his indictment in November 1986,
said in his defense during the trial he did not know about the
distribution of flavored sugar water as juice until June 25, 1982.
   After that date, Hoyvald said, he relied on the advice of four
attorneys in allowing continued distribution of the phony juice.
According to the government, the product contained little or no
apple juice.
   Beech-Nut, based in Fort Washington, Pa., is a subsidiary of
Nestle SA of Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
