<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TennecoSale     06-07 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco Sale,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Financial Offers to Buy Tenneco Oil and Gas Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Financial Resources Inc. has offered to buy
Tenneco Inc.'s oil and gas business for an undisclosed amount of
cash.
   Gulf Financial, a private Houston-based investment and financial
advisory firm, has requested a meeting with Tenneco Chairman James
L. Ketelsen.
   The offer is believed to be the first for the operations since
Tenneco put them up for sale on May 25. Analysts have estimated that
the units could fetch between $5 billion to $7 billion.
   In a letter to Ketelsen, Gulf Financial set a Friday deadline for
a meeting on the proposal, said Henri A. Soussan, a principal in
Gulf Financial.
   ``We're making a friendly and attractive offer,'' Soussan said
Monday. ``We're waiting to hear from Mr. Ketelsen.''
   Soussan would not reveal how much Gulf Financial is offering or
other details of the proposal, which was outlined to Tenneco in a
letter last Wednesday.
   He said the offer is for both the exploration and production and
the refining and marketing operations of Tenneco Oil.
   ``We plan to keep them as one entity in an ongoing company,''
Soussan said. ``We intend to retain the senior management and all
employees. We would form a new company, Gulf America Resources Ltd.,
to continue the business.''
   Soussan said the bid is the first by Gulf Financial in the energy
field.
   Gulf Financial was formed two years ago to make real estate
acquisitions but has yet to make a purchase, Soussan said. The
company has bid for a number of large organizations _ real estate
giant Cadillac Fairview Corp., department store owner Joske's and
most recently, Westin Hotels & Resorts _ but has come up empty each
time.
   Soussan said that Gulf Financial has no staff. He said European
interests back the company, but he would not disclose names.
   ``They are certainly one of those whose interest will be
considered,'' Tenneco spokesman Joseph Macrum said. ``If they are
deemed as being a qualified buyer, they will be invited'' to make a
bid.
   Macrum said he could not say if Ketelsen would be meeting Gulf
Financial representatives.
</TEXT>
