<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened sharply
higher again this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, but many
contracts quickly began to fade in early dealings.
   Wheat fell into the minus column shortly after the opening.
   All the major agricultural futures advanced the permissible
limits Monday, and the exchange expanded both the trading limits and
margin requirements for today.
   The exchange's action puts traders in greater jeopardy and
dampens the upward price movement, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with
G.H. Miller & Co.
   In addition, weekly crop reports released after the close of
trading Monday showed some deterioration of the wheat crop, but it
less than had been expected, said Gidel.
   Weather conditions remain severely dry and warm in the Midwest,
although there was some promise of showers in parts of Indiana and
Ohio.
   In early trading, wheat was 6} cents lower to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.76 a bushel; corn was 5}
cents to 10 cents higher with July at $2.52 a bushel; oats were 10{
cents to 12{ cents higher with July at $2.19 a bushel; and soybeans
were 14 cents to 25{ cents higher with July at $9.04 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .80 cent higher with the June
contract at 73.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .55
cent higher with August at 75.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .30
cent lower to 1.05 cents higher with June at 52.65 cents a pound;
and frozen pork bellies were .35 cent lower to 1.13 cents higher
with July at 55.77 cents a pound.
   On Monday, feeder cattle were lower, but other livestock and meat
were higher.
</TEXT>
