<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FDA-Additives     06-07 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FDA-Additives,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA To Ban 4 Color Additives Used in Cosmetics, Drugs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is planning to
ban four color additives used in cosmetics and drugs because they
may cause cancer.
   Officials announced Monday that the additives _ red dyes Nos. 8,
9 and 19, and orange dye No. 17 _ will be banned beginning July 15.
   The announcement followed an April 18 Supreme Court decision in
which the high court refused to let the government approve the use
of color additives that pose a minimal risk of causing cancer.
   The court rejected arguments by the cosmetics industry that safe
substances are being forced off the market.
   The Supreme Court let stand a ruling last October by the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals here that federal law prohibits the FDA
from approving use of red dye No. 19 and orange dye No. 17 even
though the cancer risks are ``trivial.''
   Government researchers, citing tests with laboratory animals,
said the lifetime use of a product with orange dye No. 17 poses a
cancer risk of one in 19 billion, and for red dye No. 19 one in nine
million.
   The FDA said the threat from each use was ``so trivial as to be
effectively no risk.''
   The appeals court gave a strict interpretation to a 1960 federal
law that prohibits FDA approval for any color additive ``found ...
to induce cancer in man or animal.''
   William B. Schultz, a lawyer for the activist consumer group
Public Citizen, said the decision was important because the dyes
offer no health benefit and some cancers will be prevented.
   ``For cosmetics, it may mean there a few shades of lipstick that
will be lost. I think that will make no difference to people,'' he
said.
   Peter Barton Hutt, a lawyer representing the Cosmetics,
Toiletries and Fragrances Association, said the decision was a
disappointment but that it was ``more important as a symbol than in
terms of its specific impact.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
