<1ST_LINE>d f BC-India-StockExchange     06-07 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Stock Exchange,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brokers Boycott Stock Exchange To Protest Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian stock brokers on Tuesday boycotted
trading on the Bombay Stock Exchange to protest violence on the
trading floor a day earlier.
   The exchange, India's largest, was officially open, but no
transactions were reported.
   The exchange was shut down Monday afternoon after disgruntled
exchange workers agitating for higher pay attacked brokers on the
trading floor. The United News of India said that 12 brokers were
injured in the melee.
   The workers had staged a one-day strike May 9 to underscore their
demand for pay increases.
   The market, in the doldrums for months, has been recovering in
recent weeks following widespread approval of the Indian
government's 1988-89 budget and its new import-export policy, which
liberalizes trade regulations for many industries.
</TEXT>
