<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-EEC-Unity Adv12-2Takes   06-07 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Unity, Adv 12-2 Takes,0919</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday June 12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>West Europeans Show More Tangible Signs of Greater Unity in EEC</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Accompanying items are BC-EEC-Unity-Members and
BC-EEC-Unity-Movers. Also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Luxembourg, cars carry the first
``European'' license plates, featuring a replica of a
blue-and-yellow European flag.
   At a rural train stop in northern France a new welcoming sign not
only says the town is French but that France is a member of the
European Economic Community, or Common Market.
   In the Dutch town of Sint-Oedenrode a furniture-manufacturing
plant flies the same flag that is on the Luxembourg's license
plates, and a sticker on a restaurant window in Brussels, site of
EEC headquarters, says: ``My country: Europe.''
   Across much of Western Europe outward signs are multiplying that
the EEC is drawing wider public interest in its quest to create a
true community of nations and, in the view of proponents, gain
greater influence on international economic and political matters.
   Already the EEC is in conflict with the United States and Japan
on some economic issues, and business competition with these two
economic powerhouses and other Western allies is growing in many
areas. The most recent dispute with Washington is over EEC farm
subsidies and their effects on American farmers.
   At the same time, the 12-nation community has been improving
trade ties with the Soviet Union and the communist East bloc _ even
more so than with its Western allies.
   While the 31-year-old organization still is far from its goal of
fully weaving together the economic, social and political fabric of
Western Europe, the integration process in recent years has reached
a new plateau, one from which ordinary citizens can feel involved.
   The community has created its own currency, the European currency
unit (ECU), for bookkeeping purposes but eventually hopes to
circulate the currency for common use among its people. To promote
that idea, the winner of an annual EEC-sponsored tennis tournament
is paid in an ECU check which can be cashed for another EEC national
currency.
   It's still not clear how far the EEC can go with its drive for
greater European unity.
   Some of its members, including Britain and Denmark, show little
desire to go beyond the creation of a simple common market in which
goods and people can move freely across national frontiers. Others
are dedicated to a grander goal: a Europe with a single political
identity, or, as its founders liked to put it, a United States of
Europe.
   Whatever the approach, the pool of money available for joint
spending is limited. The members devote less than 2 percent of their
national incomes to the EEC budget, which this year totals $55
billion.
   Even the more modest goal of ending national barriers to trade
has been beyond the EEC's reach. Some European leaders say this is
the organization's most damning failure, although most believe the
bloc will meet its latest self-imposed deadline of 1992 for removing
these barriers.
   An EEC study published in May said creation of a genuine common
market by 1992 would mean a 4.5 percent boost in economic growth for
the region, a 6 percent drop in consumer prices and 1.8 million new
jobs.
   The study said the European economy could save as much as $320
billion over an unspecified ``medium term'' by achieving an
integrated market.
   Despite its slightly blurred vision of the future, the EEC
appears to have found new success in persuading people that the
slow, tedious process of European integration is more than a
bureaucratic exercise.
   Opinion polls show a slight increase in recent years in public
support for the idea of European unification, although most people
still have only a vague notion of what the EEC is and how it
operates.
   A poll of people in all member nations late last year indicated
that 85 percent thought their country's membership in the group was
a good thing. A 1983 poll put the figure at 79 percent, and in 1980
it was 76 percent.
   In some ways the effort to make people feel attached to the aims
and affairs of the EEC is seen by its leaders as their most
important task.
   In the early years of this decade, the Common Market was mired in
a seemingly endless dispute over internal finances. Decisions on
other matters fell far behind schedule. Nothing seemed to be getting
done, and all the while people saw high inflation and growing
unemployment.
   This was more than just another weak moment for an organization
that had survived many while remaining largely on track.
   A turnaround began in June 1984. At a meeting in the 16th century
Fontainebleau Chateau outside Paris, the EEC government leaders
resolved their budget wrangle, although other money problems cropped
up later.
   Of possibly more lasting significance was a decision at that
summit meeting to launch what was called a ``People's Europe''
campaign.
   The leaders at Fontainebleau recognized that the EEC's problems
went deeper than the money debate. They saw a need to make the whole
integration process appear relevant to individual citizens, to make
people believe that the EEC's aspirations were bound up with their
own.
   ``We're putting Europe back in gear,'' Gaston Thorn, then the
EEC's chief executive, said when the Fontainebleau Accords were
announced.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
