<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Europe-DirtySeas     06-07 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Dirty Seas,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Experts Meet on Pollution Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSKRONA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts from eastern and western Europe
met in this port city Tuesday in an attempt to sort out the
pollution problems that are plaguing the Baltic and the North seas.
   A carpet of algae spread in recent weeks along the Norwegian and
Swedish coasts, killing farm trout and salmon worth millions of
dollars and causing unknown damage to wild fish. An epidemic of a
herpes virus has killed hundreds of seals in Danish and German
waters this spring.
   Pollution from farms, sewers and industry was suspected in both
cases.
   About 175 delegates from Sweden, the Soviet Union, Finland,
Poland, West Germany, East Germany, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands
and Britain were attending the three-day meeting, said spokesman
Torsten Wikstrom.
   The timing of the conference, coinciding with the algae plague,
``was not meant that way,'' said Wikstrom. But he said the algae was
a main topic on the first day of talks.
   Farmers from all countries represented have been blamed for heavy
use of fertilizers, which eventually find their way to the seas, and
some municipal governments will face costly outlays for better
sewage treatment if the seas are to be cleaned up.
   Harald Velner, executive secretary of the Helsinki Commission,
singled out the Soviet Union and Poland as major polluters. But
Wikstrom said the meeting has mostly been free of recriminations.
   The delegates included local, regional and national politicians
as well as marine experts
</TEXT>
