<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices slipped in early trading today as
investors apparently refocused their attention on negative economic
signals.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was down 15-32 point, or
nearly $4.70 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its price, rose to 9.1 percent from 9.05 percent late
Monday.
   Analysts said there was no news to send the market downward, but
they suggested investors who ignored economic signs during a
four-day rally last week might again be concerned about inflation
and other factors.
   ``It's behaving more in lines with the (economic) fundamentals
today,'' said Maury Harris, an economist at PaineWebber Inc.
   ``The market has been rallying here for a couple of weeks without
any particular reason,'' said Robert Brusca, an economist at Nikko
Securities Co. International.
   ``I would have to chalk it up to normal, unexplainable bond
market dynamics,'' he said of today's performance.
   Some analysts attributed the recent run-up to technical factors.
During the rally, bond traders ignored soaring commodity prices, a
harbinger of higher inflation that usually leads to credit market
declines.
   Bond traders fear inflation because it erodes the value of
fixed-income securities and can lead to higher interest rates.
   Some commodities prices were sharply higher in early trading
today.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds today, prices of
short-term government issues were unchanged to 1-32 point lower,
intermediate maturities fell between [ point and 5-16 point, and
long-term issues were down ] point, according to Telerate Inc., a
financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.24 to 109.41. The Shearson Lehman Daily
Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, fell 1.89 to
1,145.65.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities were down \ point
in light trading, according to the investment firm Salomon Brothers
Inc.
   However, Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which
measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of
five years or longer, rose 0.19 to 279.58.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were up 1 basis point at
6.44 percent. Six-month bills rose 1 basis point to 6.72 percent and
one-year bills were unchanged at 7.02 percent. A basis point is
one-hundredth of a percentage point.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 7 5-16 percent, up from 7\ percent late Monday.
</TEXT>
