<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Index Off 12.5 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices settled lower Tuesday, erasing most of
the previous session's gains.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed down
12.5 points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,820.2. The index rose 13.5 points
on Monday.
   Volume was a robust 557.4 million shares, compared with Monday's
380.2 million shares.
   Dealers said London players were keeping a close eye on Wall
Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average was 8.53 points lower
at 2,066.68 as the London session drew to a close.
   ``There's concern and lingering doubt whether we have really seen
a turn in the U.S. market over the past week, and that has prevented
people from chasing the market higher,'' said Bob Semple, a market
strategist at County Natwest WoodMac Ltd.
   The Dow Jones average soared more than 114 points last week.
   Semple and others said investors are concerned that British
officials might try to engineer another hike in interest rates soon.
   On Monday, the Bank of England signaled a half-point rise in the
commercial banks' base lending rate to 8.5 percent, the second gain
in less than a week.
   The interest rate worries ``aren't quite over yet, so we're just
marking time and consolidating,'' Semple said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 7.7 points at 1,445.1
at the close, while the 500-share index fell 6.04 points to close at
1,026.55.
</TEXT>
