<DOCNO> AP880607-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Tradss Writer=
   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan is chipping away at its mammoth trade surplus</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>y expanding imports and overseas investment but the United States</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   has yet to adequately address its own foreign trade imbalance, the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry said Tuesday.
   In a report on Japan's foreign trade in 1987, MITI said
structural changes in the country's economy, combined with the yen's
appreciation against the U.S. dollar, have led to increased imports
and a slowing of growth in exports.
   ``Japan's industrial structure is becoming geared to domestic
demand,'' said Atsushi Oi, director of the ministry's International
Trade Research Office. ``Manufactured imports are increasing rapidly
and the distribution system is undergoing a change.''
   Imports of manufactured goods rose to $73.9 billion in fiscal
1987 from $55.2 billion in fiscal 1986, fueled primarily by the
rapid appreciation of the Japanese yen, according to government
statistics.
   But the report warned that the budget and trade deficits of the
United States, as well as other international imbalances, ``are
having a dampening influence on trade and investment by causing
exchange rate fluctuations and destabilizing market prices.''
   Some economists say the period of sharp reductions in Japan's
trade surplus is at an end. While the surplus has been declining
compared with last year's levels, the seasonally adjusted trade
surplus has lately been increasing from month to month.
   Oi said the United States could reduce its trade deficit by
slashing runaway consumer demand, expanding production facilities
and revamping its export policy.
   The ministry report urged major industrial countries to
coordinate their economic policies more closely in light of today's
rising economic interdependence.
   ``International policy coordination is essential to the effective
resolution of imbalances,'' said Oi, whose office compiled the
report, which has been issued annually since 1949.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tuesday that Japan's
exports to the United States will fall from the present 40 percent
of Japan's total exports to 25 to 30 percent of total exports. He
did not predict how long it would take for that to happen.
   Spurred by the rapid rise in the value of the yen, imports of
consumer goods from the European Economic Community rose by 26.3
percent in 1987 over the previous year, the trade ministry said.
   Those from the newly industrialized countries of South Korea,
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore soared by 50.3 percent in the same
period, according to the trade report.
   By comparison, imports of U.S. consumer goods rose only 8.4
percent.
   Since early 1985, the yen has risen by more than 100 percent
against the U.S. dollar, making Japanese exports more expensive
overseas but boosting Japan's import buying power.
   Oi said Japan is prepared to import more manufactured goods from
Asian nations and step up direct investment in the region.
   He said Asia's newly industrialized countries have depended on
the U.S. market for their development, ``but it will be difficult to
continue to depend on exports to the United States.''
   To offset the burden on U.S. markets, Japan was prepared to help
by absorbing more Asian products and offering technological and
economic assistance, as well as stepping up direct investment, he
said.
</TEXT>
