<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChildLabor     06-07 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Labor,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ILO: Unions, Governments Do Little Against Child Labor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal exploitation of child workers is widespread
in much of the Third World, and most national trade unions do little
to combat it, according to a report released Tuesday by the
International Labor Organization.
   The report by the Geneva-based group said some governments fail
to enforce bans against child labor and even facilitate exploitation
because industries that employ children can be important earners of
foreign exchange.
   Some experts cited in the report estimate that at least 100
million boys and girls are employed worldwide, many of them younger
than 10 years old and many unpaid.
   Those who are paid for their work ``rarely receive an income even
approaching the minimum wage,'' the survey said. ``They receive no
fringe benefits, insurance or social security payments ... child
workers are the lowest paid but work the longest hours.''
   The 226-page report noted that such conditions give employers a
competitive advantage abroad. Regional studies included in the
report said some exporters in India and Egypt would rather cease
trading than replace children with adult labor because of the cost
of the switch.
   The report deplored the ``almost total absence of initiatives by
national workers' organizations in the campaign against child
labor.''
   ``Because the exploitation of child workers can be a threat to
their economic interest and because it constitutes a violation of
the rights and dignity for which labor has campaigned all along,
workers' organizations have a particular obligation to promote and
assist in the campaign against child labor,'' the report said.
   Recent efforts by the International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions and by Britain's Trade Union Congress are the ``almost sole
exceptions,'' the report said.
   Case studies in the report acknowledged efforts made in India,
Brazil, Colombia and the Philippines and said child labor was
virtually eliminated in Hong Kong following improvements in social
security benefits and education policy.
   But the report said that in much of the Third World, child labor
continues to be ``widely prevalent _ in agriculture, industry, and
services _ despite national legislation prohibiting it.''
   Payment in many industries is made upon completion of a specified
task or period, it said.
   In Peruvian gold mines and in deep sea fishing operations off the
Philippines, medicines, supplementary food, and working days lost
because of illness are deducted from the pay, according to the
report. Children, more likely to suffer occupational injuries, may
be indebted to the employer at the end of the contract.
   Fifteen years ago, the confederation set a mimimum age of 12 or
13 for ``light work.'' But a study on child labor in the quarries
and brickyards of Peru found the majority of the children working
there started ``even before they were eight years old,'' the report
said.
   The report said that in Kenya, family labor involved around 90
percent of all children between six and 15 years of age and was
common in both rural and urban areas in a large variety of tasks,
from washing clothes to the sale of crops on local markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LawFellowship     06-07 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Law Fellowship,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Offers to Pay 125 for Pro Bono Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major international law firm said Tuesday it
will pay the salaries of 125 young lawyers each year who are are
willing to work for the poor for two years after law school.
   For five years beginning next June, Skadden, Arps will funnel $10
million to qualified public service organizations to pay the
salaries of Skadden Fellows.
   The lawyers would provide legal services in civil law for poor
people deprived of civil or human rights and who, unlike persons
accused of crime, are not guaranteed counsel by the Constitution.
   The program also will instill in the lawyers a taste for pro bono
_ public benefit _ work, said Peter P. Mullen, executive partner of
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom, the firm.
   The program will take the form of fellowships that pay about
$32,500 a year plus fringe benefits, comparable to second-year
salaries of federal judicial clerks, said the announcement from
Skadden, Arps.
   Twenty-five Skadden Fellows will be named each year for the next
five years and each will serve about two years.
   ``There are many lawyers interested in and capable of dealing
with the legal problems the disadvantaged encounter, and there are
many organizations that provide needy persons with legal services,''
said Mullen. ``The problem has been that the organizations lack the
funds to provide enough lawyers to fill the need, much less at a
reasonable salary.''
   A graduating lawyer applying for the fellowship must find a
public service organization willing to employ him.
   Skadden, Arps, founded 40 years ago, has 177 partners and 675
associates in seven major U.S. cities and in London and Tokyo.
</TEXT>
