<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Intel-Siemens     06-07 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intel-Siemens,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intel, Siemens Form Joint Venture In Computing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intel Corp. of Santa Clara and Siemens
AG of Munich, West Germany, said Tuesday they have formed a
joint-venture international computer company to be headquartered in
Hillsboro, Ore.
   The new company will be called Biin (pronounced byne) and
``complement the business strategies of both Siemens and Intel,''
the chief executives of both companies said.
   Biin will offer ``computer systems for mission-critical computing
applications worldwide,'' the companies said. Intel spokeswoman Pam
Pollace declined to be more specific, but said its products would
fit into the category that includes computerized manufacturing,
patient care, reservation systems and automatic tellers.
   Intel manufactures microcomputer components, modules and systems;
Siemens is one of the world's largest electrical and electronic
companies.
   Ownership of the new company will be split 50-50, said Andrew S.
Grove of Intel and Karlheinz Kaske of Siemens.
   Named to head Biin was Joseph J. Kroger, former vice chairman of
Unisys Corp. and before that the chief executive officer of Sperry
Corp., which was merged with Burroughs Corp. in 1986 to create
Unisys.
   While Hillsboro will be the new company's world headquarters, its
European base will be in Nuremberg, West Germany. Biin is expected
to begin production at both sites by the end of the year, the
announcement said.
   Ms. Pollace declined to comment on the size of the company or how
many employees it would have.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
