<DOCNO> AP880607-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 1428EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ICCNomination     06-07 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ICC Nomination,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ICC Nominee Assures Senators on Deregulation Views</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's nominee to fill a
vacancy on the Interstate Commerce Commission assured a Senate
committee Tuesday that she would not vote automatically for less
regulation of the transportation industry.
   ``A blind reliance on deregulation and minimal government
interference cannot always be relied upon to promote the public
interest,'' Karen Borlaug Phillips told a Senate Commerce, Science
and Transportation Committee hearing on her nomination. ``Less
regulation does not necessarily mean no regulation.''
   Phillips, 31, the chief economist for Republicans on the Senate
Finance Committee, was praised by GOP members of the commerce panel.
   But several Democrats questioned her sharply about her views on
the adequacy of government regulation of the trucking and railroad
industries.
   Sen. John D. Rockefeller, D-W.Va., the sponsor of legislation
that would make it easier for shippers to obtain government help in
forcing railroads to lower their rates, complained that ``monopoly
is allowed free rein'' by the ICC in some instances today.
   ``The result can be rail rates for hauling grain that are too
high, rates for hauling coal that are too high, higher food and
utility bills for consumers across the country,'' he said.
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., a former secretary of transportation,
argued against deregulation of the trucking industry.
   ``I don't think it's safe now. I don't see weigh stations open,
and I don't see inspections taking place,'' Adams said.
   Phillips said she favors further deregulation of the trucking
industry, and has ``a very open mind, generally, on rail matters.''
   Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., chairman of the Commerce Committee's
surface transportation subcommittee, said he supports Phillips'
nomination.
   ``I believe on balance, this nomination by the president is about
as good as we could expect,'' he said after the hearing.
   Phillips was nominated to the $77,500-a-year job on Feb. 29. She
would replace Commissioner Malcolm M.B. Sterrett, whose
five-year-term expired Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
