<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-07 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0236</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures advanced strongly while soybeans
surrendered most of their gains in late trading Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat opened sharply higher but faded quickly and was down the
rest of the day.
   With limit gains in all agricultural commodities on Monday and
healthy gains in recent weeks, the markets were ready for profit
taking, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Trading in soybeans was extremely volatile with a sharp upturn on
the opening, an almost immediate selloff, a quick recovery and then
a fast fade at the end.
   A midday, forecasts of cooler temperatures for the Corn Belt may
have triggered some of the price losses, said Spilka.
   ``But mainly,'' he said, ``prices have been going up so much that
traders have made enough money and were willing to sell; and selling
tends to touch off further selling.''
   On the close, wheat was 5} cents to 14 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.77 a bushel; corn was 5 cents
lower to 12{ cents higher with July at $2.57 a bushel; oats were 8
cents to 15 cents higher with July at $2.21{ a bushel; and soybeans
were 16\ cents lower to 4{ cents higher with July at $8.80 a bushel.
</TEXT>
