<HEAD>USG Reschedules Stockholders' Vote On Recapitalization For July 8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG. Corp. has rescheduled for July 8 a vote by
its stockholders on a defensive recapitalization and business
restructuring plan it proposed to counter a takeover attempt by a
Texas partnership.
   The vote was originally scheduled for a special meeting on June
24, but was rescheduled on Monday by USG's board for July 8 at 9 a.m.
   USG said in a statement it was delaying the vote to give
stockholders extra time to consider proxy materials relating to the
proposed recapitalization.
   The plan, announced May 2, would give stockholders $37 in cash,
$5 in 16 percent pay-in-kind junior subordinated debentures and one
new share of common stock, USG said in a release.
   The company would take on $2.2 billion in new debt to pay for the
recapitalization, aimed at warding off a takeover attempt by Desert
Partners LP, a partnership headed by two Texas oilmen.
   USG also announced that, at Desert Partners request, the federal
appeals court in Chicago had delayed the partnership's appeal on a
ruling upholding USG's shareholder rights plan. The appeal was put
off until after the shareholders' vote next month.
</TEXT>
