<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankersConference 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bankers Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Universal Banks: The Wave of the Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDs grafs 10-14, Later at ... anyone else, to Update with
afternoon developments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International bankers and businessmen said Tuesday
that the stage was being set for the eventual creation of a
universal banking system, which would offer a variety of financial
services to customers around the globe.
   For one thing, regulatory barriers that separated investment and
commercial banks, such as the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act in
the United States, were being abolished or re-examined, Rainer E.
Gut, chairman of Credit Suisse in Zurich, told the International
Monetary Conference.
   He said the bank of the future will have to change its business
strategy by becoming more competitive and aggressive.
   ``In the 1990s, the typical manager in a successful universal
bank, will be globally oriented, have a flair for market
opportunities, and possess entrepreneurial instincts,'' Gut said in
prepared remarks made available to the news media.
   The three-day monetary conference, in its 34th year, provides
leaders of the top commerical banks and corporations in about two
dozen countries an opportunity to confer with government officials
on topics affecting the world economy and international banking.
   Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan and other central
bankers from abroad were scheduled to attend Wednesday's closed-door
session.
   Much of Tuesday's session focused on the U.S. banking system with
some conference participants criticizing the inconsistencies between
domestic and foreign regulations.
   ``Effective governance, both domestic and international, has not
kept pace,'' American Express Co. chairman James D. Robinson III
told the conference.
   ``Our sites must be set on achieving an environment in which all
types of financial institutions can compete with adequate rules of
fair play _ a credible regulatory framework,'' he said.
   Robinson said all financial institutions should have fair access
to the global markets while countries work together to harmonize
otherwise outdated regulations.
   Later, at a media briefing Tuesday, several bankers, including
John S. Reed, chairman of Citicorp, the nation's biggest banking
company, briefly discussed the level of regulation among global
institutions.
   Philadelphia National Bank Chairman Frederick Heldring said big
banks that take risks shouldn't always expect government protection.
   ``We ultimately could come to a form of Chapter 11'' federal
bankruptcy reorganization, Heldring said. ``If a bank is too large
to fail, it is subject to the risk of becoming an arm of
government.''
   Reed agreed, ``It makes us more vulnerable to becoming bullied by
the regulators.''
   He noted that while government regulators look at the role banks
play in society, ``the sociology doesn't play in the management
room. We should be allowed to fail as anyone else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
