<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Aspartame     06-07 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aspartame,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Approves Aspartame For Six New Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has
approved the use of the artifical sweetener aspartame in six new
food categories, the NutraSweet Co. announced Tuesday.
   Aspartame, marketed as NutraSweet, now may be used in yogurt-type
products, refrigerated flavored milk beverages, ready-to-serve fruit
juices, refrigerated ready-to-serve gelatin desserts, fruit wine
beverages and frozen desserts, the company said in a statement.
   ``I expect some of these products to be in stores and markets in
the near future,'' said Robert B. Shapiro, chairman and chief
executive officer of NutraSweet Co.
   Shapiro said the FDA approvals were ``another affirmation of the
increasingly important role of NutraSweet in the diets of
health-conscious consumers and their families.''
   He also said the company has been working with its customers
together to develop products in the new categories.
   Aspartame has been used in 1,250 products since it was first
approved in 1981 for chewing gum, the company said.
   NutraSweet Co., headquartered in this northern Chicago suburb, is
a wholly owned subsidiary of Monsanto Co.
</TEXT>
