<2ND_LINE>AM-Murray-Electrolux, 1st Ld-Writethru,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murray Ohio Rejects AB Electrolux Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 4th graf pvs, Electrolux negan ...
with Electrolux reaction. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Murray is ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murray Ohio Manufacturing Corp. said
Tuesday that its board rejected as inadequate a $52-a-share takeover
offer from AB Electrolux of Sweden, and recommended that
shareholders refrain from tendering their stock under the $197
million offer.
   Murray's directors also authorized the company's management to
explore possible alternatives to the Electrolux offer.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Murray fell 50 cents a
share to $62.50.
   Electrolux began a tender offer of $52 a share for all of
Murray's 3.8 million shares on May 24. It had previously proposed
$48 a share.
   In a statement released in New York, Electrolux said it was
``disappointed'' with the Murray board's rejection of its offer, but
said it will continue with it, subject to previously-stated terms
and conditions.
   ``We continue to believe that the acquisition of Murray by AB
Electrolux is in the best interests of Murray shareholders and its
other constituencies,'' the Electrolux statement said.
   Murray is a leading manufacturer of power lawn mowers and
bicycles with a headquarters in Brentwood, a Nashville suburb, and a
plant in Lawrenceburg.
   AB Electrolux is an appliance maker that owns such trademarks as
Frigidaire and Tappan. It has no connection with Electrolux Inc.,
the Marietta, Ga., company which makes vacuum cleaners.
   In announcing Tuesday's action, Murray chairman William M. Hannon
said the board felt ``the Electrolux offer understates the values
represented by the company's shares _ values built by Murray's
long-standing tradition of quality.''
   The company said the directors considered a number of factors in
making their determination, including the opinion of its financial
advisors, Goldman, Sachs & Co.
   Hannon also said the board had amended the company's takeover
defenses to ``enhance Murray's ability to respond to the Electrolux
offer and to develop possible alternatives to it.''
</TEXT>
