<HEAD>Financier Amends SEC Disclosure Showing Film Company is for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Kirk Kerkorian disclosed he may sell
his controlling share of MGM-UA Communications, or restructure the
corporation by selling a film production unit and other assets, a
top executive said Tuesday.
   MGM-UA has acknowledged receiving offers from more than one
potential buyer, but none of the suitors have been identified, said
Stephen D. Silbert, MGM-UA's president and chief operating officer.
   ``We have not disclosed that at all,'' Silbert said.
   Asked about reports that N.V. Philips was the leading contender
among several foreign firms interested in acquiring the movie and
television company, Silbert said, ``I really can't confirm or deny
it.''
   Kerkorian filed an amendment Tuesday to an April 6 report to the
Securities and Exchange Commission, which stated he was considering
selling all or part of his 82 percent stake in the company.
   Silbert said Kerkorian's amended SEC filing shows he is
considering disposing of his shares as well as considering a
restructuring.
   The restructuring ``could involve the sale of one of the motion
picute production units and additional assets such as interests in
our distribution organizations,'' Silbert said. A substantial amount
of the proceeds would be distributed to stockholders, he said.
   Kerkorian has spent the past two decades buying, selling and
buying back assests of the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer and United Artists
studios. The movie and television conglomerate has been on the
auction block for the past two months.
   The latest transactions involving the two studios occurred two
years ago when Kerkorian sold MGM-UA Entertainment to Atlanta
broadcaster Ted Turner, then bought back UA's distribution
operation. Several months later, Kerkorian bought back the UA film
library for $480 million and then repurchased the MGM name and logos.
   MGM-UA stock rose 37{ cents a share Tuesday to $16.87{ in trading
on the New York Stock Exchange. It was trading at $13.62{ a share on
April 6 when the company first announced inquiries from interested
buyers.
</TEXT>
