<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     06-07 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Payout for Closed Thrifts; U.S. Productivity Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's thrift industry is showing more signs of strain, but
the government says the productivity of the nation's work force is
still on the rise.
   Federal regulators announced a record $1.35 billion payout to
close two insolvent savings institutions Monday. Meanwhile, the
Labor Department reported a big increase in productivity statistics
for the first quarter.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board closed American Diversified
Savings Bank and North America Savings and Loan Association, both of
Costa Mesa, Calif., without arranging for a takeover by another
institution.
   Only 10 of 235 failed S&Ls handled since 1981 have been resolved
with a straight payoff of depositors. Usually, the bank board pays a
bonus to a healthy thrift to buy a sick S&L or arranges to transfer
deposits to another institution.
   But bank board Chairman M. Danny Wall said the thrifts had little
value as going concerns because they had few retail deposits and
lacked branch offices. Both also relied on high-cost, short-term
deposits arranged through brokers, which they in turn lent out for
speculative real estate ventures and other risky investments.
   The institutions have been insolvent for some time. Regulators
took over the management of American Diversified in February 1986
and of North America Savings in January 1987.
   Wall said the bank board is paying $1.14 billion from the Federal
Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. to American Diversified depositors,
the largest cash payout the agency has ever made. It is covering
$209 million in deposits at North America Savings.
   Deposits up to the insurance limit of $100,000 will be available
beginning Tuesday. A total of about $500,000 in both institutions
exceeded the limit. Those depositors will share in liquidation
proceeds.
   In a new economic report, the Labor Department said the nation's
efficiency in churning out goods and services improved more than
four times more rapidily during the first quarter of 1988 than it
did in 1987.
   But average annualized hourly wage gains of only 3.4 percent
failed to put most workers ahead of inflation for the fifth quarter
in a row, it said.
   Not since the spiraling inflation of 1979-81 have workers gone
that long without an improvement in their standard of living through
wage gains, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   Productivity among the nation's non-farm businesses increased at
an annual rate of 3.6 percent during January through March.
Preliminary figures last month had put the improvement at only 0.9
percent. But those earlier figures were issued before the gross
national product _ the broadest measure of economic growth _ was
revised upward.
   In another sign of improving economic conditions, the number of
Americans late on their mortgage payments fell to the second-lowest
level of this decade during the first three months of the year, a
trade group of lenders reported.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association said the number of mortgage
payments late by 30 days or more dropped to 4.78 percent of total
mortgages in the first quarter, down from 4.95 percent in the last
three months of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880607-0284 </DOCNO>
