<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-07 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rumors in advance of the upcoming OPEC meeting
sent oil prices into a tailspin.
   A selloff in the last hour of trading Monday took prices
substantially lower.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for July delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at
$17.26 per 42-gallon barrel, down 24 cents.
   Among July contracts for refined products, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled down 1.16 cents at 49.73 cents a gallon, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 45.84 cents per gallon, off 1.29
cents.
   Traders dumped oil contracts on rumors that the Persian Gulf
states hope to isolate Iran, which is demanding higher oil prices be
established at the ministerial meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, set to begin on Saturday in Vienna,
Austria.
   According to the rumors, ``the Gulf states will cooperate among
themselves'' regarding pricing and not include Iran, said John
O'Connell, senior energy analyst at Refco Inc.
   O'Connell stressed that the rumor was not confirmed and said he
was ``a little surprised people would sell that aggressively on an
unverifiable rumors.''
</TEXT>
