<DOCNO> AP880607-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexacoSale Bjt   06-07 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco Sale, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Sells West German Subsidiary For Slightly More Than $1.2
Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. has agreed to sell its West German
subsidiary to that country's largest utility in a deal worth
slightly more than $1.2 billion, the two companies said.
   The sale of Texaco's 99.12 percent interest in Deutsche Texaco AG
to Rheinish-Westfaelisches Elektrizitaetswerk AG, also known as RWE,
represents the first part of a $5 billion restructuring plan by this
nation's third-largest oil company.
   RWE said at its Essen headquarters that it would pay $1.23
billion to close the deal, which was signed Monday in Luxembourg and
which is subject to approval by the West German Federal Cartel
Office. Both sides said they expected no problems with the German
authorities.
   It will become effective five days after the permission arrives,
probably by the end of the month, RWE spokesman Friedhelm Gieske
said.
   Texaco began negotiating the sale months ago, as it prepared for
its April emergence from a year under Chapter 11 bankruptcy court
protection.
   The White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant had filed for that
protection a year earlier to avoid having to post an $11 billion
security bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgment held against
it by Pennzoil Co. A jury ruled Texaco had interfered with
Pennzoil's 1984 attempt to acquire part of Getty Oil Co. so it could
buy Getty itself.
   In December, Texaco agreed to settle the suit by paying $3
billion to Pennzoil as part of a restructuring plan that included
sales of $3 billion worth of assets.
   Soon afterward, takeover artist Carl C. Icahn, its largest
stockholder with 14.8 percent of the company's shares, stepped up
pressure on Texaco's management to do more to increase the value of
its stock.
   In March, he threatened to run a slate of five candidates,
including himself, for Texaco's board, if the company did not take
steps that would raise the price to $55 per share from then-current
levels in the $30-to-$40 range.
   Texaco, in an apparent bid for stockholder support, announced the
restoration of its dividend and an expansion of its planned asset
sales to $5 billion a month later.
   But Icahn was not satisfied. Recently, he offered $60 per share
for those Texaco shares he does not already known, and launched his
threatened proxy fight for the five seats on the company's board.
The results will be announced at Texaco's annual meeting on June 17.
   Texaco's stock, meanwhile has continued to hover at levels near
$50 per share, as Icahn kept up his attacks on its management.
   Commenting on the Deutsche Texaco sale, James W. Kinnear,
president of the parent company, apparently had those criticisms in
mind.
   ``The proceeds from this transaction, together with those from
other imminent asset sales and joint venture partnerships, will be
providing real benefits to our shareholders,'' he said in a
statement. ``We are committed to significantly enhancing the value
of our shareholders' investment.''
   Exactly how Texaco shareholders would benefit from the sale,
Kinnear did not say. There has been speculation that it might issue
a special dividend to shareholders or disburse the proceeds in some
other manner.
   On Monday, Texaco's stock rose 87{ cents a share to close at
$50.87{ in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   As part of its restructuring, Texaco has also been negotiating
the sale of 60 million barrels of U.S. oil and natural gas reserves,
and has been talking with Saudi Arabia about establishing joint
ventures involving East- and Gulf-coast refining and marketing
interests.
   RWE, West Germany's eighth-largest corporation, is active in the
production and supply of electricity, brown coal mining, and the
petroleum and chemicals businesses, Texaco said.
   It said it acquired Deutsche Texaco, in the mid-1960s. The German
company is active in all phases of the oil business, from
exploration and production to petrochemicals.
   It owns two refineries, capable of producing 140,000 barrels
daily, and holds a 10.2 percent share of the West German retail
gasoline market, with about 1,900 Texaco-branded retail outlets
throughtout the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
