<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan-Bass Bjt   06-07 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan-Bass, Bjt,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bass, Macmillan Move Buyout Battle To The Courtroom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The courtroom is likely to be the scene of the
next encounter between Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass and
Macmillan Inc., the giant publishing company he has offered to buy
for $1.9 billion, or $73 a share.
   Bass filed a lawsuit Monday after Macmillan failed to respond to
his latest offer, but Macmillan had already filed its own suit
charging Bass with securities laws violations.
   ``Going to court clearly makes this unfriendly, but it already
really was,'' said Bruce Thorp, an analyst with Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia.
   On Wall Street, Macmillan jumped $3.50 a share to $75 in trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Analysts were nonplussed by the legal developments and said it is
likely the Bass suit will delay the restructuring dividend Macmillan
plans to begin paying shareholders on Friday.
   The Macmillan board, which rejected Bass's initial $64-a-share
offer as inadequate, adopted a plan to split the company's
publishing and non-publishing operations into two separate, publicly
owned corporations.
   Part of the plan includes paying shareholders a special dividend
of $52.35 a share.
   In a suit filed Monday in Chancery Court in Delaware, Bass is
seeking to block the company from proceeding with the payout.
   In what analysts characterized as a further attempt to appease
management, Bass alternatively offered to restructure the company
along the lines of a plan Macmillan unveiled last week, but on terms
more favorable to shareholders. He is offering a payout of $58 a
share.
   Bass representatives made the proposals at a meeting over the
weekend with Macmillan's investment bankers and requested a response
by noon Monday.
   But Macmillan allowed the deadline to tick by, saying in a
statement it would consider the proposal ``later in the week.''
   In its suit filed Monday morning in federal court for the
Southern District of New York, Macmillan charged Bass with
``repeated filing and public dissemination of misleading statements
... in order to engage in creeping tender offers ...''
   The suit further claims that the defendants were ``so anxious to
hide their intent, to deceive Macmillan and its shareholders, and to
manipulate the market in Macmillan shares, that on or about Oct. 13,
1987, the broker who was placing defendants' orders for Macmillan
shares falsely stated that he was acting on behalf of Macmillan
itself.''
   The Bass group holds about 9.1 percent of Macmillan's roughly 26
million outstanding shares. The stake was built between August 1987
and last month, according to the lawsuit.
   Neither side would comment further on the latest developments.
   Analysts had predicted the battle would move to the courtroom.
``It was a logical reaction for both sides to what was going on,''
said Berk Boksen, an analyst with Raymond James & Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
   There has been considerable speculation that a third party might
surface, and that remains a possibility, analysts say.
   ``But with both Bass and Macmillan putting short deadlines, it
puts a squeeze on anybody new coming in,'' Thorp said.
   Separately, Macmillan disclosed that ``an entity related to the
Bass Group'' has requested government approval to acquire more than
50 percent of Macmillan's outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
