<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankersConference Bjt   06-07 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bankers Conference, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankers Stress Need For Global Harmony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world economy is ``on a much more solid
footing'' thanks to past efforts among major industrialized nations
to coordinate international policies, U.S. Treasury Secretary James
A. Baker III says.
   Baker told a gathering of bankers and businessmen attending the
34th annual International Monetary Conference, which began Monday
and runs through Wednesday, that inflation remained low and trade
imbalances were narrowing because of global harmony.
   In fact, he said, by working together to stabilize exchange rates
and coordinate economic policies, the major industrialized nations
withstood the worst effects of last October's global stock market
collapse.
   ``It would have been easy for each of us to turn inward and focus
on short-term measures to address immediate domestic needs,'' Baker
said Monday.
   Instead, he said, the nations ``pulled together and intensified
... efforts to find a compatible and reinforcing set of policies to
achieve common goals.
   ``Since that time, strengthened underlying policy actions have
been reflected in enhanced stability of exchange markets,'' he said.
``... The world economy ... is on a much more solid footing.''
   While many conference participants echoed those sentiments
Monday, others called upon corporate America to work more on its own
to sharpen overseas competitiveness.
   ``Of course American industry owes a large part of these
improvements to the weakness of the U.S. dollar. (But) the
supportive strength of the exchange rates can fade as fast as it has
arrived,'' said West German businessmen Dieter Spethmann, chairman
of Thyssen AG in Dusseldorf, in prepared remarks.
   He said U.S. businesses have more going for them than some of
their foreign competitors, including a mobile labor force, flexible
labor costs, favorable energy costs and the largest single market in
the world.
   Yotaro Kobayashi, president of Fuji Xerox Co. Ltd. in Tokyo,
said, ``For survival in this volatile global business environment,
not only American corporations, but businesses around the world are
making significant efforts to expand from their geographic area of
strength into other major markets of the world.''
   The International Monetary Conference seeks to provide leaders of
the top commercial banks and businesses in about 20 different
countries with a chance to confer with government officials on
topics affecting the world economy as a whole, and the international
banking industry in particular.
   Besides Baker, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and other
central bankers were among those scheduled to attend closed-door
``think sessions'' and speeches.
   At the opening sessions Monday, the main theme was global
cooperation and competitiveness.
   ``If a deficit country reins in domestic consumption too much, a
recession can result,'' said Walter Seipp, president of the IMC, in
a prepared statement. ``On the other hand, if domestic demand in
surplus countries is stimulated too much, this could then create the
threat of renewed inflation.''
   Michel Camdessus, chairman of the Washington-based International
Monetary Fund, agreed: ``Each of the problems in question is a
matter of common concern, in that each has spillover consequences
for the other.''
   The bankers, though, said politics was among the obstacles
standing in the way of global harmony.
   ``Even when there is agreement on the objectives ... there may
well be difficulties in undoing arduously worked out domestic
compromises, or in obtaining timely domestic action where
policy-making is decentralized,'' Camdessus said.
   Specifically, he called upon the United States to reduce its
large federal budget deficit as a way of keeping interest rates down
and narrowing its trade gap. He also said Europe and Japan should
work toward stimulating their economies.
   In his address Monday, Baker said steps taken beginning in
September 1985 to adjust currency rates were largely responsible for
improved economic conditions today.
   At that time, the United States and its four major trading
partners agreed to devalue the dollar to help reduce the spiraling
U.S. trade deficit and stave off protectionist legislation. Last
year, however, that same group agreed that further declines in the
dollar's value would be ``counterproductive.''
   Baker noted the most recent March trade figures showed
significant improvement, dropping to $9.7 billion _ its lowest level
in three years _ on the strength of record U.S. exports.
   ``The success (of the 1985 gathering) ... created certain
momentum that led to further progress,'' Baker said, pointing to
other, subsequent meetings.
</TEXT>
