<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAW-Chrysler Bjt   06-07 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Chrysler, Bjt,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Sign Two-Year Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The signing of a two-year contract
between Chrysler Corp. and the United Auto Workers union has one
union executive wondering how the company will fare in its new era.
   ``The test will really come now as to the (Chrysler Chairman Lee)
Iacocca management's ability to manage,'' UAW Vice President Marc
Stepp said Monday after the contract was signed at a ceremony.
   ``It's been somewhat fortunate with a great deal of assistance,
from workers, suppliers and from the economy,'' he said. ``... Now
they're on their own.''
   Stepp echoed a point made by UAW President Owen Bieber, who said
the signing ceremony never would have been possible without great
sacrifice on the part of all involved with Chrysler over the last
nine years.
   ``I think Chrysler is a good example where cooperation from the
plant floor on up contributed immensely'' to saving the company,
Bieber said.
   Another sign that Chrysler is recovered from the financial
problems that pushed it toward bankruptcy in 1979 is the realignment
of the Chrysler-UAW contract with those at General Motors Corp. and
Ford Motor Co, Stepp said.
   The common expiration date of national labor agreements at the
Big Three gives the union an advantage in picking a company to
target for a pattern agreement. Stepp said Chrysler workers were
hurt financially by being out of synch with GM and Ford, but under
the circumstances, there was no choice.
   ``Many of the benefits the Chrysler workers would have gotten had
to go by the wayside because we had to work to save the company,''
Stepp said.
   ``They are back making profits and they are back on a level
playing field as Lee points out. So they can get back to the
business of competing,'' he said.
   Chrysler Vice President Anthony St. John said the two sides
recognize Chrysler's mission.
   ``I think we all realize we're in a very competitive ball game in
the future and that's going to result in good cooperative efforts to
make sure we stay in the ball game,'' he said.
   The agreement covering 66,000 workers took effect May 16 after
being approved by just 54 percent of the covered workers. One unit,
the skilled trades workers, voted down the agreement, but their
objections were dealt with.
   ``I don't think we should dwell on the question of percentage,''
Bieber said. ``It's a question now of what happens from this point
forward.''
   Chrylser and the UAW began early negotiations April 18 as a way
to calm rising tensions brought on by Chrysler's consideration of a
$2 billion offer for its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary
and the company's decision to close a 5,500-worker assembly plant in
Kenosha, Wis.
   The tentative agreement was reached May 4 and eliminated the
possibility of a strike in September, which observers said would
have been likely because of the anger of rank-and-file workers over
the proposed Acustar sale and the Kenosha closing.
   Bieber said the turmoil during negotiations and that 50 percent
of the rank and file failed to vote during the ratification process
contributed to the low percentage of approval.
</TEXT>
